Fix issue with Default for Runtime props in HeatSWConfigInstance

Replace Runtime property softwareConfigs with variable in HeatSWConfigInstance

Change-Id: I13311d68dfb543637df7983b67620018fd1379f2
Workaround-Bug: #1364484

commit_message:
Render hidden stack parameters with a password field

In the launch stack form, any heat template parameters that are
of type string and marked as hidden are now rendered as a
password field.

Change-Id: Ie9b0a051a8815525c89de31b7ab98d8148166a55
Closes-Bug: 1362846

commit_message:
ModelsMigrationsSync:Override compare_server_default

This test showed an error with alembic 0.6.6:
For MySQL Integer server_default value is compared incorrectly.
For example, when model has DefaultClause('0', for_update=False)
alembic finds it different from server variant "'0'".
For PostgreSQL Sting server_default value is compared incorrectly.
For example, when model has DefaultClause('', for_update=False)
alembic finds it different from server variant "''::character varying".

Such error appear in implementation of ModelsMigrationsSync to Neutron
https://review.openstack.org/76520.

Change-Id: I9730da1c0790a88f81570c51c36cc0cbe0651a5a

commit_message:
Convert v3 servers return_reservation_id behaviour to v2.1

Changes return reservation id format on server create to
the v2.1 format.

Adds api sample tests for the os-multiple-create plugin

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I148cce80fb4b19a4240e00ca206fcb7bac20f357

commit_message:
Fix version number to Juno

We need to update the version number in setup.cfg, otherwise pbr will
fail with:
"error in setup command: Error parsing /opt/stack/new/manila/setup.cfg:
ValueError: git history requires a target version of
pbr.version.SemanticVersion(2014.2.0.0b4), but target version is
pbr.version.SemanticVersion(2013.2.0)"

Change-Id: I608c1dce0169fe78667e5818f2abff3dc8b11447

The modal for creating instance of a database has a flavor dropdown
but it is not clear what the properties of the flavor are. This
patch follows the same convention used in the Launch Instance under
the instances panel. It displays the Flavor Details in a table

Closes-Bug: #1360012

commit_message:
display flavor details on database launch

The modal for creating instance of a database has a flavor dropdown
but it is not clear what the properties of the flavor are. This
patch follows the same convention used in the Launch Instance under
the instances panel. It displays the Flavor Details in a table
under the help section for the flavor selected.

Change-Id: I9ce6d3aa3db3973c5e10a041467d569db328f5b9
Closes-Bug: #1360012

Denis,

The bug says you want to enable H301. Yes, agreed.

The question being asked is this, why are you disabling H302. Why not leave H302 enabled? What problem(s) do you see in enabling H302. 

I think all of us who read the bug and the commit message have this question, and I certainly don't understand the statement in the bug that reads:

"But H302(import only module) should be disabled, since it affects given reason for the bug report".

commit_message:
Enable H301, H304 hacking rules

Reasons:
 - H301 should be enabled to avoid multiple imports per single line;
 - H304(enabled by H301) should be enabled to avoid relative imports.

Changes:
 - ignoring H302(import only modules) because it appears
   to checked when H301 was enabled;
 - H303 wasn`t added to `ignore` list because
   Trove code doesn't have those violations;
 - tox.ini updated

Change-Id: Iaeaaf7e5266aded896efdefc1b4436861a54f835
Closes-Bug: #1337409

[{'created': '2014-01-30 17:55:13.000000000', 'message': 'vmwareapi oslo vmware library integration

These are changes necessary to integrate the vmwareapi driver with the oslo
common vmwareapi code. Much of the change is stripping out code obsoleted by
the oslo code.

Effort was made to minimize the amount of actual driver code changes in this
round by keeping a small amount of shim code. Existing unit tests were modified
as appropriate. Additional patches will be introduced shortly to include
additional conversions and tests.

Summary of changes:

- use common/vmware/exceptions.py - there are a linger bit of code (most
  for defining nova-specific exceptions that are still retained in
  error_util.py)
- use common/vmware/vim.py for the Vim implemenation
- use common/vmware/api.py for api session
- updated existing unit tests
- nova retains its own version of get_{soap/wsdl}_url which using conf
  settings for default and overrides.

commit_message:
vmwareapi oslo.vmware library integration

These are the minimal changes necessary to integrate the vmwareapi
driver with the oslo.vmware code. Much of the change is mechanical
switching to call the library code, and removing obseleted code in the
driver where appropriate.

Effort was made to minimize the amount of actual driver code changes in
this round by keeping a small amount of shim code. Existing unit tests
were modified as appropriate. Additional patches will be introduced
shortly to include additional conversions and tests.

Summary of changes:

- use common/vmware/exceptions.py
- use oslo.vmware vim.py for the Vim implemenation
- use oslo.vmware api.py for api invocation/session
- updated existing unit tests
- nova retains its own version of get_{soap/wsdl}_url which using conf
  settings for default and overrides.

blueprint use-oslo-vmware
Co-authored-by: Radoslav Gerganov <rgerganov@vmware.com>
Co-authored-by: Davanum Srinivas <dims@linux.vnet.ibm.com>
Change-Id: Idab7778d4c7e5e7099d842debbcbc009cf9127b6

commit_message:
Extract database dumps to function

There was duplication between base and target dumps that is resolved
by use of arguments.

By extracting to function it becomes easier to make changes to how
database dumps are performed. The current setup is a bit hairy,
aggregating in a function makes it easier to improve later.

Change-Id: Ic5d4f13eaa7a4d842c9af0073de17e1cffad0a88

commit_message:
Add try/except for timesync in cold_restart_nodes

Do not fail test if time synchronization fails after
node hard reset and just print warning message.

Change-Id: I1e5084476b1006a08e3a2dfd512cd108338f9f5d
Closes-bug: #1365446

commit_message:
Integrate VMDK driver with oslo.vmware library

The common code between various VMware drivers was moved to the oslo.vmware
library during Icehouse release. The VMDK driver should be updated to use
this library.

Change-Id: Ia747c402db82ff78969c50dfe8845f04b304675a
Implements: blueprint vmdk-oslo.vmware

commit_message:
Use different serializers for different envs

We should deploy secondary controllers using sequental logic
for 5.0.x clusters.

The commit implements a very basic approach for versioning serializers,
so it may be revised in the future.

Change-Id: Ia94bd16c3060dff76c2c79dca480784092331deb
Closes-Bug: #1364519

commit_message:
Port volumes extension to work in v2.1/v3 framework

Ports v2 volumes extension and adapts it to the v2.1/v3 API
framework. API behaviour is identical with the exception
that there is no support for XML. Also

- unittest code modified to share testing with both v2/v2.1
  where appropriate
- Adds expected error decorators for API methods

Note that there will be further code cleanup in the future
but the code currently is mostly as-is from the v2 codebase.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: If2a9dd1f5233812a1177b54ded6f0ae115c54e97

Looks good. However there is another solution, using css+js, for example - directly forcing background-color of fields with:

    input:-webkit-autofill {
      -webkit-box-shadow: 0 0 0px 1000px white inset;
     }

and a simple trick on page load:

    $('input#email,input#password').prop('disabled', true);
    setTimeout(function(){
      $('input#email,input#password').prop('disabled', false);
    }, 500);"}, {'account_id': 2455, 'date': '2014-08-15 16:03:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

To continue previous comment - using JS requires some timeout for page-load. There are different examples with setting field.val(''), but it is tricky because of the timeouts.

I am not sure if js+css is a good solution, just an idea. Thoughts?

The trick with fake fields seems to work, but we cannot be sure how the default behaviour of browsers' autocomplete will change in the future ;)"}, {'account_id': 9576, 'date': '2014-08-15 22:59:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

wow.. looks like you need to have the hidden fields to trick chrome into populating. It's such a hack and the only solution that would work... 

On the one hand, I can see the benefit of having this, but on the other, should we introduce browser hacks into our code?"}, {'account_id': 9576, 'date': '2014-08-15 23:09:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Tihomir: You can ignore the use of timer completely by using jquery's ready event handler. However, I actually prefers the hidden HTML approach."}, {'account_id': 2455, 'date': '2014-08-16 14:04:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Thai, I've did some tests, and attaching to $(document).ready doesn't work, as the auto-fill is not performed by the $(document) itself, but by the browser extension, that probably also attach itself to .ready() event. It is a bit tricky.
The only concern about using the hidden fields is that it might act unpredictably for some browsers and some future versions of the browsers. Both ways - the hacks are ugly enough... It seems for chrome developers, there is no form with password field that is not used for login..."}, {'account_id': 12826, 'date': '2014-08-16 15:47:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

From discussion it seems this is the only viable way to solve the bug at present - is there anywhere we maintain a list of "hacks", or code that may need to be reviewed in the future?'}, {'account_id': 11599, 'date': '2014-08-18 04:29:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 6637, 'date': '2014-08-18 08:33:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I admit this is a bit of a hack, which is one reason that I made sure that its always off unless the form variable is present and true, if people are suffering weird issues because of it, then they can simply set no_autocomplete = False. 
I think passive solutions like this are better than relying on timed JavaScript to actively update the fields because this way, there shouldn't be any collision with the UX e.g. initial form load lag etc. 
The fields themselves clearly state they are fake in the name and should hopefully not collide with other developers forms.  
At least from what I've read the Chromium team aren't going to start supporting autocomplete="off" any time soon, so hacks like this may be necessary until they give us a better solution.'}, {'account_id': 6638, 'date': '2014-08-18 09:57:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

Sam Betts, I agree here I prefer this solution to one using JS and it is clear that the fields are fake'}, {'account_id': 2455, 'date': '2014-08-19 08:06:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-19 08:06:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: -Verified

commit_message:
Allow forms to disable autofill in all browsers

New variable added to form to specify whether it should autofill or
not. This updates the modal forms autocomplete attribute. Hidden
fields are required because Chromium v34+ based browsers ignore the
autocomplete=off form attribute, so the hidden fields catch autofill
data. Any form without self.no_autocomplete = True will just act
like before.

Change-Id: Ibb1722023eea8f57312e1133939d1f75cd909467
Closes-Bug: 1352459

commit_message:
API v1 for creating domains ignore some attributes now

Now API v1 for creating domain returns status 400 when in request POST
body are send attributes like 'created_at', 'updated_at', 'id', or 'serial'

Change-Id: I0b4deda212d3e5137d1224f3fd738e2bc68539bd
Closes-Bug: 1291595

Okay, we'll need a better fix then.. Right now, this migration can intermittently fail - irritating!"}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2014-08-30 14:35:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

this is easy to fix.  instead of running the statements on the engine, which has to reconnect every time for each call to execute(), run them on an individual connection, so that they are all within the same database session:

    with migrate_engine.begin() as conn:
        conn.execute(<foreign key thing>)
        try:
            for <migration> in migrations:
                conn.execute(<migration>)
        finally:
            conn.execute(<reset foreign key thing>)'}, {'account_id': 395, 'date': '2014-09-01 15:04:16.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-01 16:03:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

commit_message:
Use 1 connection when running ALTER migrations

if you use migrate_engine.execute() you may get 1 different connection pr call
to execute(), to avoid this we use migrate_engine.begin() to get a connection.

Change-Id: I4600c11be678cbae4810618b5c3a1e38daa45161

commit_message:
Fixes Hyper-V 2008 R2 instance creation failure

Creating an instance on a Hyper-V / Windows Server 2008 R2
compute node fails due to a WMI exception. This happens
while creating creating and configuring the resources to be
added to the VM.

The resources already have set default values for
certain properties, while other properties have NULL.
Trying to set a new value over the NULL causes the exception.

This issue can be avoided by bypassing the WMI object's
__setattr__ and instead set the attributes via WMI object's
wmi_property method.

Co-Authored-By: Cristian Valean <cvalean@cloudbasesolutions.com>

Fixes-Bug: #1356884

Change-Id: I54d61989ab97c63207bf6a5b985a3e596f89c20f

commit_message:
Don't expect a remote "origin" if you're setting local REPOREFs

If one uses set-sources-vars -l $DIRNAME where $DIRNAME is a git
repository without a remote called "origin", it produces gibberish
output.

This fixes the get_name function so that it behaves correctly in
that instance.

Change-Id: I109315a776b3ab95ba75fe05399d487f6e0b3df8
Closes-bug: 1365022

If I was a cloud operator I would prefer to use the version and configuration of libvirt that is being tested the most, so not just setting  version_cap to disable new things but the exact version of libvirt."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-14 19:02:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

(3 comments)

> Being this patch doesn't do anything itself, I would rather hold off until there is a case where we really need it.

We've already seen cases where this would have been useful in our own gate CI system. For example, when we hit a firewall problem in libvirt we wanted to be able to upgrade to newer version with the fix, but when we did that it enabled new live snapshot feature which was buggy in the gate. If we had applied the version cap we could have had the new libvirt to fix the bugs we were seeing, without immediately causing the massive instability see with the live snapshot feature.

This is exactly the sort of scenario our end users can see in cloud deployments too as well as the other scenarios outlined in the commit message.

> I think we should have a broader discussion about driver
> CI and versioning. If we agree that this is good idea,
> then other virt drivers may want to do this as well.

Some, but not all, policy choices for CI testing may have a use for this feature.  Even if the driver CI testing policy we decide on does not need this feature though, it does not invalidate the usefulness of this patch to cloud admins deploying libvirt as described in the commit message. So gating this feature on the driver CI testing discussion is inapporiate."}, {'account_id': 1812, 'date': '2014-08-15 11:45:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

While I can see the immediately benefit of this, I'm wondering about the generality. libvirt wouldn't be the only component with this issue and it worth considering how manageable this would be over multiple components, especially in the presence of backports that would confuse what's in which version. A more general method might be to  have the features individually enabled through config. That would give users direct control over features though would require that CI would enumerate exactly the features tested. Need to think a bit more about this..."}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-08-15 11:55:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Having features independently toggled is somewhat risky IMHO because the code can easily make assumptions that all features at a particular version are enabled at the same time.

If other non-libvirt components want to do a version cap of their own that's fine, but I don't think we need try to solve a bigger problem until we actually find ourselves in the situation where other parts of Nova need to do this too. eg don't need to create solutions for bigger problems that might not ever exist"}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2014-09-03 19:41:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

At this point we are just going in circles on this issue. Lets  see what we can do to hash this out at the summit in Paris.'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-09-04 09:07:05.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Lost any motivation to continue working'}]

Add a new 'version_cap' setting in the 'libvirt' group of the
nova.conf file. This allows the cloud admin to artifically
restrict what libvirt features are used by nova. This can be
useful in a number of scenarios

 - Admin wishes to pull in newer libvirt version to address
   a bug, but does not want any change in behaviour of nova
   by having it use different libvirt features

   and wants Nova to use the same libvirt feature set across
   all nodes despite some nodes having newer libvirt.

 - Admin wants to ensure their cloud deployment is only using
   libvirt features that were tested by the OpenStack CI
   system.

The default value of the config parameter is None, so no
attempt is made to cap the version out of the box.

Change-Id: I1e056d1136b83fc0626529b2fbb617e048132c36

commit_message:
libvirt: add version cap to allow limit on use of new features

Add a new 'version_cap' setting in the 'libvirt' group of the
nova.conf file. This allows the cloud admin to artifically
restrict what libvirt features are used by nova. This can be
useful in a number of scenarios

 - Admin wishes to pull in newer libvirt version to address
   a bug, but does not want any change in behaviour of nova
   by having it use different libvirt features

 - Admin is running a cloud with a variety of base OS versions
   and wants Nova to use the same libvirt feature set across
   all nodes despite some nodes having newer libvirt.

 - Admin wants to ensure their cloud deployment is only using
   libvirt features that were tested by the OpenStack CI
   system.

The default value of the config parameter is None, so no
attempt is made to cap the version out of the box.

DocImpact: libvirt.version_cap config parameter added
Change-Id: I1e056d1136b83fc0626529b2fbb617e048132c36

Add some prose to the README

It's a little distressing that os-cloud-config's README still has
"Features: TODO", so let's fix that with some prose.

commit_message:
Ensure subnet_create does not use explicit arguments when setting enable-dhcp

* [--disable-dhcp] [--enable-dhcp] was added in python-neutron-client 2.3.5
* --enable-dhcp=BOOL was ignored with python-neutron-client <= 2.3.4 -
  puppet-neutron had it since quantumclient times...

Change-Id: I8e9d79126be46d202a94053127e09cd1088997da

commit_message:
Requirements for fuel_health changed

Higher boundary of the version interval for paramiko removed to meet
consistency with version defined in packages spec for fuel-ostf in
fuel-main.

Change-Id: Icadf93f6c2ad1892651b2719b2fb1a123852b74a
Closes-Bug: #1361730

commit_message:
Lower log level for notification registration

Registering an internal notification isn't something that an admin
would generally be interested in, and if they are they can configure
debug logging for keystone.notifications.

Closes-Bug: #1363704

Change-Id: Id7cd3bf2e1f373b818329978553eb53af399386c

(4 comments)

I'm not sure a spec is really all that helpful for this work

The oslo.i18n docs describe what needs to be done, and this spec could basically just say "follow the recommendations from the oslo.i18n docs". At the very least, we should reference thos docs

One thing the spec *could* mention is places where we've almost made mistkaes during this conversion e.g.

              reason = last_close_event['reason']
              _error = _("Connection to libvirt lost: %s") % reason
              LOG.warn(_error)
              self._set_host_enabled(False, disable_reason=_error)

In this case, the value of _error is used for a warning log but it also ends up being exposed to the user through the REST API - it needs to be marked with _() so that translators who choose to not translate warning logs still translate this message'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2014-07-06 14:47:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Add log translation hints for Nova

Current oslo libraries support translating log messages using different
translation domains and oslo would like to see hints in all of our code
by the end of juno. So cinder should handle the changes out over the
release.

blueprint log-translation-hints
Change-Id: Ib5280f560fec4e53ee591d3e17b48b64c4d96314

commit_message:
Fix a wrong argument name at Heat keystoneclient plugin

After this fix, the Heat keystoneclient plugin should pick up
the right region to authenticate.

Change-Id: I9bb5fe5fd767997b4118cf674a17de9f8be503fe
Closes-Bug: #1213291

commit_message:
Fix for adding panel to panel group via plugin

When adding panels to panel group, it should also be added to the
list of panels at the class atttribute. Otherwise, it will lose the
reference to the panels when _autodiscover() is triggered.

Change-Id: Ifa530d5a39f48d9fd9cd0ea66f6c16594447058b
Closes-Bug: #1329050

commit_message:
Fix order of arguments in assertEqual

Some tests used incorrect order assertEqual(observed, expected).

The correct order expected by testtools is
assertEqual(expected, observed).

Change-Id: Iabf6e55146412b57b6a6544f312f9510f762566a
Partial-Bug: #1259292

commit_message:
Fix wrong redirect url after instance resizing

When the instances is paginated in multiple pages, the redirect
url for instance resizing best to be the current page.

Change-Id: Ifa7f9c5cd57430640af35b49f93c1cb1c6c5521d
Closes-bug: 1354969

The session object is a cross-client means of standardizing the
transport layer.

HTTPClient object has diverged significantly from other clients. It is
easier to simply replace it if a session is provided. If a session is
provided then users of the library need to be aware that functions such

"}]
commit_message:
Allow us to use keystoneclient's session

The session object is a cross-client means of standardizing the
transport layer.

HTTPClient object has diverged significantly from other clients. It is
easier to simply replace it if a session is provided. If a session is
provided then users of the library need to be aware that functions such
as authenticate() will no longer have any effect/are in error because
this is no longer managed by cinderclient.

Change-Id: I8935598bda8adb014d1055e39721d8eb35b3ef50

commit_message:
Convert console_output v3 plugin to v2.1

Changes required to have v3 plugin natively support
the v2 API

The get_console_output action is reverted to os-getConsoleOutput

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api
Change-Id: I71b0d5fd1a098052f8e11f60a19113b6d647ef2d

commit_message:
Need ability to evacuate host in syspanel

Implement host evacuate in the hypervisors panel.
An extra tab was added to show in the first one hypervisors
and on the second one compute host. on each compute host
that is down an evacuate host button was added.
If the user press the button a modal windows is shown to
request the needed data to perform the evacuation.

blueprint evacuate-host

Co-Authored-By: Leandro Costantino <leandro.i.costantino@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: David Lyle <david.lyle@hp.com>

Change-Id: I57a16f99fddd84c287429085c7e90beb59a17aa3

commit_message:
Cleanup superfluous string comprehension and coersion

Remove the superfluous string comprehension and coersion to string
type in a join within the keystone.notifications module. The elements
in the namedtuple are already string types.

Change-Id: I107102fabc2f6671e10bcf1b5db40529fdb19d69

subject: Ensure token is a string

commit_message:
Ensure token is a string

Token is passed as a header from wsgi to HTTPD
If that token is unicode, it triggers an exception in mod_wsgi

Closes-Bug: 1312971

Change-Id: I4bb6ef6c98fbcd35435956d701f1ee3281e9935a
(cherry picked from commit ba1bba8257716c2f5aa668e496173e96a80f0e43)

commit_message:
Prevent SystemExits when running tests

Adds a check for SystemExit exceptions during tests
to convert them into a test failure rather than an exit.
Includes the traceback in the failure so the source of
the exit can be located.

Related-Bug: #1364171
Change-Id: I2c7d9010ebf935d39ed58fe7a6fc4a1a867e2548

Hi, Eric,

Thanks for your revirwing.

H302 rule requires to import not Class but Module.
The point you mentioned, sleep is Class defined in time.

commit_message:
Preparation for enabling H302 rule

Currently H302 rule is ignored by tox. However, this rule should
be enabled. This patch partially fixes this problem to prepare for
H302 rule.

Change-Id: I8ede94ed865c699fc287af3af01aae0e631db720

commit_message:
Skip functional l3 agent test

Since this test merged there have been periodic failures that
seem to be related to SystemExit being raised.  Skipping for now
to give us time to fix.

Change-Id: Ia857835102a9c4c74820cf5eb3c529a3c2fb421e
Related-bug: 1364171

commit_message:
Test cleanup: do not leak FDs during test runs

Avoid leaking file descriptors during test runs. Instead use a secure
tempfile fixture that guarantees the file descriptor from
tempfile.mkstemp is closed and that performs the appropriate cleanup
on the tempfile name in the cleanup phase.

Change-Id: I7e1ddd3122d72d8850794df9467f7b6c0608ac2d

commit_message:
ofagent: Local arp responder for VLAN

Implement local arp responder for non-tunnel network types.
Enable it for VLAN by requesting l2pop for VLAN.

Related: blueprint ofagent-l2pop
Related: blueprint ofagent-merge-bridges
Change-Id: I2f200a1ae2bd769ea1f83fe65e58e82325ed92b0

commit_message:
Default to keystone V3 for software deployment

This patch makes keystone V3 as the default auth_url for software
deployment metadata, as expected by heat collector of
os-collect-config.

Change-Id: Ie90978f79e4e8521caad8a12272105e842ef63a5
Closes-Bug: #1337689

commit_message:
Modify the way to get 'network_id' of the port

This patch change to get 'network_id' from port info, instead of
from subnet info.

Implements blueprint implement-ec2eip-updatable

Change-Id: I51ed7e71af4c7223df9e399e189389fd655a9746

Add validate function for AWS::EC2::EIPAssociation

This is second part of blueprint implement-ec2eip-updatable to
add validate function for AWS::EC2::EIPAssociation

Implements blueprint implement-ec2eip-updatable

commit_message:
Add initial files for certificate event handling

The SSL certificate generation and workflow blueprint called for adding
support for a certificate events plugin. This CR defines an interface for this
plugin, a simple default logging-based implementation, and an example
integration with the task resource logic.

Change-Id: Ia46793a1ce767ff03d77da06bf5a2803e7dce121
Implements: blueprint add-ssl-ca-support

commit_message:
Changed order of arguments

The order of arguments for the following trove commands
was changed:

trove backup-create

trove configuration-attach

This change is documented in the following bug:

https://bugs.launchpad.net/openstack-manuals/+bug/1325121

What changed is that now (for both cmds), you pass in the
instance ID as the first arg.

The following doc page contains examples that show the
old syntax:

http://docs.openstack.org/user-guide/content/trove-manage-db.html

I updated the doc so it shows the new syntax.

Change-Id: Ic7fd24947332500ce102c3902a7ec84be4f3d542
Partial-Bug: #1325121

This does not address my, Mikes, and Christopher's comments."}, {'account_id': 10014, 'date': '2014-08-27 02:02:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

The User's Guide is supposed to be a "happy path" document that only covers procedures done from the GUI.  We did add the Fuel CLI info at the end but that IS still Fuel.

We could move this material to the Ops Guide.  That is a total mess right now -- Chris and I need to restructure it when we merge fuel-docs and fuel-web docs. This piece doesn't have a logical home there and will get lost but perhaps that is the right place -- that is supposed to be about command-line procedures that regular users might need.

Mike, the section you linked to could be xref'ed from here -- it explains the format and restrictions of the settings but I don't see just basic instructions -- set this then run dockerctl/supervisor/ctl. Chris is right -- people have to do this if they want to run Zabbix; a lot of people might want to do that without building their own iso.

What should we do about documenting Zabbix (and, eventually, other experimental features)?

If we put this in the User's Guide, do we put it at the point where one logically does this?  That would be after they install Fuel but before they create any environments, correct?  Is this the consensus?  

If so , does the User Guide piece include a list of the services that are considered experimental?  Right now, it's only Zabbix, but someday it may be a longer list.  I am inclined to leave a short Terminology article here that explains the concept and lists the services then links to the User Guide for how-to information.'}, {'account_id': 9788, 'date': '2014-08-27 02:11:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I think putting this in the Users Guide after installing Fuel is the right place.

I do not necessarily think the users guide should have a list of experimental features, as that list can be expected to change all the time - seems like release notes is the place for that right?  I'm conflicted though - it's likely the experimental features will be the cool new stuff, and if people have to chase all over the place just to see what they get by enabling experimental mode, we will probably lose all but the most dedicated...

I would probably be happy to see the experimental features listed here, and kept up to date on a release-by-release basis. Would go a long way towards keeping our innovative stuff in front of the broadest audience."}, {'account_id': 10014, 'date': '2014-08-27 04:31:35.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-27 04:31:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

If we are about to put links in fuel-dev docs, then they should refer to "master" user-docs, not some particular version.
If we are about to put content in fuel-dev docs and just refs from user docs (that's how I want it to be), then we should have only refs from user docs to fuel-dev docs, to avoid duplication.'}, {'account_id': 9788, 'date': '2014-09-02 22:11:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

I can add mention of building ISO with experimental features enabled to the fuel-dev docs later today, and link back to the user docs regarding more information on enabling experimental features.

reference.

commit_message:
Fixed two bad xrefs in terminology/overcommit

Link to "Scheduler" needed explicit text
Link to community overcommit doc was poorly formed

Also deleted extraneous bullet from security-groups

terminology/identity-service -- fixed poorly formed link.

terminology/security-groups -- replaced link to gerrit with link
to sahara section in ops-guide

Change-Id: Id8bab877c38ced27dbb4f3dcf98fe41ad395504d

commit_message:
Use mkstemp() instead of deprecated mktemp()

The tempfile.mktemp() function has been deprecated since Python 2.3
due to security issues.

https://docs.python.org/2/library/tempfile.html#tempfile.mktemp

Fixes bug 1348869

Change-Id: Ief35c662580364499991fb520b69d2039e8b7ad0

commit_message:
Add note about neutron-db-manage

I added a note to cover occasional instances where users
may need to run neutron-db-manage to populate the neutron
database. I want to leave this note out of the Juno version
for now.

Change-Id: Ia80f8f8f3768467c59dab98e0e5569aeb211206e
Closes-Bug: #1343277

commit_message:
Fix wrong disk type limitation for disk IO throttling

The disk I/O limits feature in QEMU block layer allows I/O throttling
to be used across all underlying storage types.

Change-Id: If99107955fc976b00ee101d4c6a685c29e655f82
Closes-Bug: #1362129

I did some testing on patchset 10 in devstack. I built an ubuntu image using disk image builder. This enables ssl support in postgres by default, and adds symlinks for certs. These are not copied by migrate_data, so instance ends up as FAILED. 

Something akin to below will fix, but might be better to force config to use ssl=false

--- a/trove/guestagent/volume.py
+++ b/trove/guestagent/volume.py
@@ -43,1 +43,1 @@ mysql_base = "%s/" % mysql_base
-        utils.execute("sudo", "rsync", "--safe-links", "--perms",
+        utils.execute("sudo", "rsync", "--links", "--perms",
   
In addition I noticed that user creation could sliently fail e.g:

$ trove user-create [uuid] user password --databases db

Now "user" is reserved so complains! Otherwise looks great!'}, {'account_id': 12613, 'date': '2014-08-20 06:26:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Patch Set 10: 

Returning to the issue of error checking, I see that issue is tied up with not using sqlalchemy and the model design. It would make sense for the design to be as similar to the Mysql flavour as possible.

Postgres does make come things harder if we want to use sqlalcheny - e.g you can't create databases inside a transaction, but this is fixable e.g:

from sqlalchemy import create_engine

engine=create_engine("postgresql://postgres@localhost")
con = engine.connect()
con.connection.connection.set_isolation_level(0)
con.execute('CREATE DATABASE debug1')
con.connection.connection.set_isolation_level(1)'}, {'account_id': 7850, 'date': '2014-08-21 02:38:03.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 11.'}, {'account_id': 7850, 'date': '2014-08-21 02:42:41.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 12.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-21 03:44:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12: Verified-1

Apologies if it is not appropriate to give a -1 on the basis of what I am about to say. 

I'm concerned about the use of psql client instead of sqlalchemy (see pgutil.py). Specifically:

1/ Makes the code vastly different from the Mysql case, which is likely to hamper future updates and additions.

2/ Makes it hard to use the model etc design used by the Mysql code, and introduces new bugs (e.g try creating the same user or database twice)."}, {'account_id': 4240, 'date': '2014-09-03 05:03:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15:

Mark, the use of sqlalchemy when communicating to the database that the guest agent is managing is actually something we want to remove. When we do not need anything as robust to do the few cmds that we call the database. Add PostgreSQL support

Commit adds instance creation, CRUD operations, and backup/restore
operations for postgresql to Trove.

Implements: blueprint postgresql-support

commit_message:
Adds SNMP power driver

Add a new PowerDriver module for remote control of node power by
enabling or disabling sockets on a rack power strip via SNMP.

Implements: blueprint ironic-snmp-power-driver
Change-Id: Ib16781eaa9737525c4d8a9231ecd9e72d7e2645e
Co-authored-by: David Hewson <dhewson@cray.com>
Co-authored-by: Mark Goddard <mgoddard@cray.com>

commit_message:
Datacenter moid should not be tuple

Remove the comma, because it will convert the string to tuple
Closes-bug: #1362480

Change-Id: I2debb76bae26fe3d437a431f2946f66a1cbe6851
(cherry picked from commit ace3a01ebf980c166b4dfe6d1216b17bf0aec2ed)

commit_message:
Previously, the Modulefile did not include Keystone.

This would cause the module to not install all necessary
dependencies for Heat services.  This patch allows Heat to have
consistent dependencies with other OpenStack services.

Change-Id: Ie9dffb84b19db152c5bfd251cd96d41baabdd31f

commit_message:
Adds ability to override service name for service catalog

Instead of forcing the name of the service in the service catalog to
match auth_name, this allows the ability to explicitly set the service
name, separately from auth_name.

Change-Id: I142b9e944eacdeba8a029d7f15f067ef5f1f87a4

commit_message:
Clusters troveclient Implementation

adds clusters support to the troveclient.

Co-Authored-By: Ranjitha Vemula <rvemula@ebaysf.com>
Co-Authored-By: Michael Yu <michayu@ebaysf.com>
Co-Authored-By: Mat Lowery <mlowery@ebaysf.com>

Partially implements: blueprint clustering

Change-Id: I6ed2c4c79a17fcf8f14c587cab6a8ec3acaf319f

commit_message:
Enable and start httpd

The Horizon element should enable and start httpd during
os-refresh-config so that the dashboad is useable without any manual
intervention.

Change-Id: I76c2f39b64728e80caa764c248c4a387f35b3391

commit_message:
Remove some inline if/else statements

Even though python syntax allows it, assignment of variables using
inline if...else... statements have the nasty problem of not showing
relevant information in the test coverage. Thus, by writing the
assignment in a more canonical and verbose form, we are sure that we are
actually covering the possible branches while testing.

Change-Id: I4fbce4422f4986a76255ad468ee7dd7475e3f1cf

commit_message:
Add id_attribute and resource_name to resource

The resource had 'id' hard coded all over the place and this
caused problems if the key for the resource was not 'id'.
The id_attribute can be used to override that now.  The
resource_name can be used for printed errors and strings
associated with the resource rather than teh resource_key.

Change-Id: I66afa842b8315e24d1a2e0698983440bf97ae986

commit_message:
Remove disable_interface from dhcp-all-interfaces

I don't actually think there is a way that disable_interface
would get called on Fedora... because if config_exists
it takes a different path. Furthermore we really don't
want to mess w/ configured interfaces in dhcp-all-interfaces
because that could be side effecty (and is arguably the
job os os-net-config anyways).

This function already did nothing on Debian so removing
shouldn't hurt anything.

Change-Id: Ic53bbab98aa03d487efd290ae8e076045781b5b1

commit_message:
Support the same api versions format as keystone

This will allow us to take advantage of the discovery functionality that's gone
into keystone meaning less of our own discovery code in the client.

Change-Id: I51550d0c4994ad3b2f9320dea9b8fc9090ade78f

commit_message:
Creating a Recordset doesn't increment the serial number

 If a new recordset is created that contains records, most of
 the time the serial number should be incremented. This fixes
 that problem.

 Closes-Bug:#1361342

Change-Id: Ie5207be43bd30c49914ef1edb960c4bfc58e6892

commit_message:
Fix DVR to unbind SNAT namespaces on gateway clear

Earlier fix to enable LBaaS in DVR with review #114141
updated the get_compute_ports_on_xxx ml2 plugin method
with get_ports_on_xxx.

The DVR scheduler needs to be upgraded to use this
new method to unbind SNAT namespaces.

Change-Id: I08a2b30a1ad0da222276f5d2a1cd1c3f840787a2
Closes-Bug: #1362908

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-14 21:00:49.000000000', 'message': 'Add UEFI based deployment support in Ironic

Most of the new hardware comes with UEFI boot mode, which has several
technical advantages over the traditional BIOS system.

Operator inform the boot mode to ironic using the "capabilities" property
of the node.  The operator may add a new capability "boot_mode=uefi" or
"boot_mode=bios" in "capabilities" within "properties" of the node.

Add new pxe config options:
  - "uefi_pxe_bootfile_name": specify the efi bootloader to be used.
  - "uefi_pxe_config_template": specify the respective efi bootloader config
    template.

As of now only elilo.efi bootloader is supported.

elilo.efi bootloader requires the configuration file to be named after the
ip-address assigned by the DHCP server.

Change-Id: I0ad399b2207d7c66f6887e56470ba553b3c87b53

commit_message:
Add UEFI based deployment support in Ironic

Most of the new hardware comes with UEFI boot mode, which has several
technical advantages over the traditional BIOS system.

Operator inform the boot mode to ironic using the "capabilities" property
of the node.  The operator may add a new capability "boot_mode=uefi" or
"boot_mode=bios" in "capabilities" within "properties" of the node.

Add new pxe config options:
  - "uefi_pxe_bootfile_name": specify the efi bootloader to be used.
  - "uefi_pxe_config_template": specify the respective efi bootloader config
    template.

As of now only elilo.efi bootloader is supported.

elilo.efi bootloader requires the configuration file to be named after the
ip-address assigned by the DHCP server.

Implements: blueprint uefi-boot-for-ironic
Co-Authored-By: Jim Rollenhagen <jim@jimrollenhagen.com>
Change-Id: I0ad399b2207d7c66f6887e56470ba553b3c87b53

commit_message:
TripleO and backwards compatibility

TripleO has run with good but not perfect backwards compatibility
since creation. It's time to formalise this in a documentable and
testable fashion.

We will stop deliberately breaking backwards compatibility that is
needed by any supported OpenStack release, unless there is a PTL
signoff (which will be reserved for exceptional circumstances).

Semantic versioning will make it clear to consumers of TripleO -
whether distributors or end users - when this has happened.

Change-Id: I7b63e7860d0ea58faf46c5f5483ae9fc475dbbe9

commit_message:
Improve install guide cinder controller section

I improved the cinder controller section of the installation
guide as follows:

1) Reordered instructions.
2) Added python-cinderclient package to all distributions.
3) Added glossary terms.

Change-Id: Idecafff0a1cd2f98ca7d2666bd1e402df341de7a
Implements: blueprint installation-guide-improvements
Co-Authored-By: Matt Kassawara <mkassawara@gmail.com>

@Sahid

Agree with Jay.

If there is not the place which passes None as image_id, this decorator catches an unexpected error.

I guess this exception would be translated to HTTPNotFound response and return it to a client. However, there is nothing the client can do because that seems an internal server error.'}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2014-04-23 05:53:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

soft -1 for my previous question."}, {'account_id': 7730, 'date': '2014-04-23 08:30:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Jay - I guess some unexpected behaviors can happen. If you are looking at this patchset; https://review.openstack.org/#/c/71907/ You can see a private method '_get_image' which handle this case.
Ken - I just want to avoid the call to glance since we already know the response.

Thanks for reviewing."}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2014-04-23 08:47:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I agree to this patch's purpose. It would be nice to avoid unnecessary calls.

My concern is ImageNotFound does not fit to this case.

In many cases, ImageNotFound exception would happen due to wrong image-id which was specified by a client. and it is nice to notice it to the client as HTTPNotFound, because the client can try it again with right image-id.

However this case seems an internal error, so better to separate it from ImageNotFound exception for translating it to suitable HTTP exception on API layer."}, {'account_id': 5511, 'date': '2014-04-23 10:41:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Agree with Ken'ichi here - we should be raising something like Invalid to signal that the request never even made it to glance.

Also a suggestion on how to solve this without this patch, although it might be worth keeping it since it's really a nice validation feature."}, {'account_id': 7730, 'date': '2014-04-25 16:01:44.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-04-25 16:01:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/api/openstack/compute/images.py#L155

It would be cool to have a unit test of the API that raises the 400 errors, when passed an image of None. Its possibly overkill, but it would determine if the above statement is true or false.

commit_message:
Glance: Avoid unecessary call if image_id is None

This commit adds a check to avoid an unecessary api call
if image_id is None when using methods: 'show', 'delete',
'update', 'download'.
Also it updates delete from the API to handle the new introduced
exception 'InvalidImageRef'

Change-Id: I8e7920d90ea02e3b17d9773324fbe1b082fd0353
Closes-Bug: #1311137
Signed-off-by: Sahid Orentino Ferdjaoui <sahid.ferdjaoui@cloudwatt.com>

commit_message:
Add vmedia boot support in IPA

This commit adds support for booting IPA from virtual
media cdrom.  When IPA is booted over virtual media cdrom,
the parameters to the IPA are passed in a text file within
the virtual media floppy.

Change-Id: Ia04585416aada85022af73fb2b945bd3895606f0
Closes-Bug: #1358723

subject: Move cinder volumes to compute node

[{'account_id': 7007, 'date': '2014-09-02 20:51:31.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-02 22:08:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded.

- gate-training-guides-tox-checklinks http://logs.openstack.org/62/118462/1/check/gate-training-guides-tox-checklinks/cb68605 : SUCCESS in 2m 10s (non-voting)

- gate-training-guides-tox-doc-publish-checkbuild http://docs-draft.openstack.org/62/118462/1/check/gate-training-guides-tox-doc-publish-checkbuild/bbff2b6/publish-docs/ : SUCCESS in 5m 23s'}, {'account_id': 11889, 'date': '2014-09-03 06:50:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Pranav, I'm not so sure about this. What if we extend the default setup to more than one compute node (e.g. if you want to show scheduler tuning or how host aggregates, availability zones work, ...)? 

Are there already performance problems on the controller node?"}, {'account_id': 7007, 'date': '2014-09-03 07:29:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Matjaz, I think its better to keep the cinder volumes on compute node.

For now it fixes the issue where cinder volumes could not be attached/booting from volumes was not possible.

1. Scalability: If you add another compute node (with cinder volumes), it should scale normally (we have cinder-scheduler). It should not make any difference.

2. Performance: If cinder volumes is on controller node, it will be bad for performance since the communication of data happens over the network (iSCSI).

We are running on VirtualBox VMs, trying to keep cinder volumes on another node would mean high overhead and degradation of performance. On top of that we would also have to run iSCSI services on the compute node as well, which means same services running twice.

This is not beneficial for our use-case.

I would like to know Rogers point of view on this.'}, {'account_id': 7007, 'date': '2014-09-03 07:29:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 11889, 'date': '2014-09-03 08:57:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

1. scalability is not an issue in training labs (we won't scale beyond few nodes, I guess). 
2. Performance: In virtual env. network should also not be an issue, as it is not a real network in the first place. Also, it is quite beneficial to show also all that iSCSI stuff that happens under the hood when you attach a volume to the VM

Image also what would happen in a following scenario:
- you have 2 compute nodes (so that you can show how nova-scheduler works, showing availability zones/host aggregates, etc.)
- you create a volume on one compute node.
- you attach it to the VM spun up on another compute node...
- so here you still have all the problems of Cinder on controller node, you just postponed it for one use case (where VM and cinder volume are on the same node)?

It is also a possibility to just merge this patch and describe this issue in Readme or something similar, so users can plan their use cases accordingly ..."}, {'account_id': 7007, 'date': '2014-09-03 10:37:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

iSCSI is still being used, nothing is changed there, conceptually the same thing can be demonstrated. The overhead is significant on Virtual Network since its emulated network, it runs on your hosts ram and processors.

The given scenario:

No, this is not postponing the problem, its fixing it. In case of multiple compute node (that is my point of scalability!), multiple cinder-volumes will exist. They will be scheduled to given compute node by cinder-scheduler. In this scenario we remove the requirement for iSCSI drivers to be installed on the controller node, which is a plus point.

We will showcase the use-case's in operators guide"}, {'account_id': 7007, 'date': '2014-09-03 10:37:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Workflow'}, {'account_id': 11109, 'date': '2014-09-03 15:33:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I think both of you make good points. I'd like us to stay close to the openstack-manuals/install-guide where possible, but they assume a dedicated block storage service node, so that's not helpful.

One goal of the osbash archtitecture has been that users can change the cluster with a simple configuration file change (which is what this patch does). This may not always work, but it would be a good demonstration of the flexibility of OpenStack (and osbash) if moving services around was as simple as this patch.

I am inclined to support this patch (and others like it) because it forces us to keep our scripts clean and flexible. I'd like the cluster to get to a point where we can actually _test_ performance in different configurations rather than speculate about it, and then we may decide to distribute services differently again, based on numbers."}, {'account_id': 7007, 'date': '2014-09-03 18:05:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Roger, Matjaz ... this is the cleanest solution that I can come up with this cluster as of now. Infact many small deployments of openstack (in production) also practise this style to run cinder volumes on the compute nodes. This patch is kind of critical in the terms of making Cinder work as required. And IMHO, this is not a bad hack around to get features of Cinder working.'}, {'account_id': 11889, 'date': '2014-09-03 19:30:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

OK, good points guys. Let's just roll with this and see where it takes us. In the end, the trainer can easily move this back to the controller if it suits him."}, {'account_id': 11109, 'date': '2014-09-03 19:33:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

Thanks guys for this insightful discussion from which I benefited quite a bit.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-03 19:33:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

Starting gate jobs.
http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-03 19:39:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+2

commit_message:
Move cinder volumes to compute node

Moving cinder volumes to compute node for better performance. This
will also reduce the load on the networks as the volume drive to be
attached will work on the same node as the VM instances are launched.

Change-Id: Ibc4c5b371882e71c30a1c5ee4517e6b5f93daf13

commit_message:
Only bind SAIO daemons to localhost

The SAIO configs have no default bind_ip setting configured
which causes them to listen on all available IP addresses.
This can be dangerous on a test machine with public interfaces,
especially with the default passwords set. Its reasonable to
choose a more restrictive setup, especially in SAIO which uses
127.0.0.1 throughout ring-builder, example commands and the
probe tests.

Change-Id: I471c49705ce09e07ec7acc07ee42a1e220529b82

commit_message:
Fix file location for nova compute rbd secret

The rbd secret location was mixed between /etc/nova
and /etc/ceph. This patch changes the secret to
be in /etc/nova for both the file and exec
resources so that virsh secrets are set correctly

Change-Id: I50f0324d911f20d5a072c769edcf289ae59f817a
(cherry picked from commit aad7a0a7cbb2770d4d1f668c1b8fe871cd7d7205)

[{'created': '2014-05-23 21:55:39.000000000', 'message': "Add functions to setup user namespaced filesystems

When using user namespaces, the contents of the container's
file systems need to be owned by the targeted user on the host.
These functions will change the ownership of the files in the
filesystem to the proper owners.

For example, when mapping root in the container to user 500
on the host, the contents of the filesystem owned by root need
to be changed to be owned by user 500.

Partially implements: bp libvirt-lxc-user-namespaces

Change-Id: I78afc2686f17b5e5ec740a3d0a1963df7cc92755

commit_message:
Add functions to setup user namespaced filesystems

When using user namespaces, the contents of the container's
file systems need to be owned by the targeted user on the host.
These functions will change the ownership of the files in the
filesystem to the proper owners.

For example, when mapping root in the container to user 500
on the host, the contents of the filesystem owned by root need
to be changed to be owned by user 500.

Partially implements: bp libvirt-lxc-user-namespaces

Change-Id: I78afc2686f17b5e5ec740a3d0a1963df7cc92755

commit_message:
Adds a manual garbage collector script

It's the responsibility of the operator to call the garbage
collector manually. Using crontab or a similar tool is advised.

A more intelligent approach for this will be added in a follow-up
patch.

Change-Id: I9cf22a5c65920be0eaff909c8f090d29ef300d1f

[{'created': '2014-06-22 02:18:42.000000000', 'message': 'Made unassigned networks visible in flat networking

This change fixes a bug in Nova's
GET /v2/{tenant_id}/os-networks

The doc
http://docs.openstack.org/api/openstack-compute/2/content/GET_os-networks-v2_ListNetworks__v2__tenant_id__os-networks_ext-os-networks.html
says this "Lists networks that are available to the tenant".

When invoked by a non-admin user it was returning only networks
assigned to the user's tenant.  But in flat and flat DHCP nova
networking, networks CAN NOT be assigned to tenants --- thus a
non-admin user would get zero networks from this operation.

The fix was to make this operation conditionally use an option already
present in the lower-level code to "allow_none" when fetching the list
of networks, meaning to include networks whose project_id field in the
DB held "none" (meaning the network is not assigned to a tenant).  The
condition under which this is done is that the Nova configuration
option named network_manager contains the string
"'nova.network.manager.Flat" --- which is true for flat and flat DHCP
nova networking and false for VLAN nova networking.

Change-Id: I64c5a3f31c912cca6b5b9987152ba7a9b3f5987d
Closes-Bug: #1327406

commit_message:
Made unassigned networks visible in flat networking

This change fixes a bug in Nova's
GET /v2/{tenant_id}/os-networks

The doc
http://docs.openstack.org/api/openstack-compute/2/content/GET_os-networks-v2_ListNetworks__v2__tenant_id__os-networks_ext-os-networks.html
says that "Lists networks that are available to the tenant".

When invoked by a non-admin user it was returning only networks
assigned to the user's tenant.  But in flat and flat DHCP nova
networking, networks CAN NOT be assigned to tenants --- thus a
non-admin user would get zero networks from this operation.

The fix was to make this operation conditionally use an option already
present in the lower-level code to "allow_none" when fetching the list
of networks, meaning to include networks whose project_id field in the
DB held "none" (meaning the network is not assigned to a tenant).  The
condition under which this is done is that the Nova configuration
option named network_manager contains the string
"'nova.network.manager.Flat" --- which is true for flat and flat DHCP
nova networking and false for VLAN nova networking.

Change-Id: I64c5a3f31c912cca6b5b9987152ba7a9b3f5987d
Closes-Bug: #1327406

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-02 23:02:27.000000000', 'message': "Improve install guide security content

I improved security content in the installation guide as
follows:

1) Renamed basic environment 'passwords' section to 'security' to
   generalize topic.
2) Generalized existing content.
3) Added content about administrative privilege requirements
   including potential interference with deployment automation
   tools.

commit_message:
Improve install guide security content

I improved security content in the installation guide as
follows:

1) Renamed basic environment 'passwords' section to 'security' to
   generalize topic.
2) Generalized existing content.
3) Added content about administrative privilege requirements
   including potential interference with deployment automation
   tools.

Recommend backporting to Icehouse.

Change-Id: Ide9785728c7b52ee1dc59a533b3486b99ee11139
Closes-Bug: #1311426
backport: icehouse
(cherry picked from commit 80ca377eb8c4d2a448f707cdb663d5e0f0db857e)

commit_message:
Encrypt heat template parameters

Encrypt hidden parameters before storing them in database
and decrypt on stack load.

Specification document https://review.openstack.org/#/c/100343/

Change-Id: I8fe686ab1dfd86baa4b29d9ad4604873e48fa03e
Implements: blueprint encrypt-hidden-parameters

Uses these resources for information:
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Neutron/DVR_L2_Agent
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Neutron/DVR/HowTo
https://docs.google.com/document/d/1iXMAyVMf42FTahExmGdYNGOBFyeA4e74sAO3pvr_RjA/edit

commit_message:
Anticipate Plan delete DBReferenceError

Catch the DBReferenceError when trying to delete a Plan
with living Assemblies, and hand back a friendlier error message
and a 409.

Change-Id: I716441b7fde6e69cbf69a9d29fa5180c7290cd68

commit_message:
Ensure volumes are detached and that instances are deleted

This patch is based on https://review.openstack.org/#/c/86638/ but
we still use the nova calls instead.  We fall back on metadata
to cinder api calls to cleanup metadata and continue when we have
a failure.  This should do the trick for the time being.

Close-Bug #1298350

Change-Id: I8e556d6b8655b22c6bf71fb7a372338de51f22fd

commit_message:
Octavia v0.5 component design

This design represents the overall layout of components that will
make up the first major milestone release of Octavia (v0.5). The
intent here is to have a scalable service delivery layer, to get
communication with external components right, and not yet worry
about making the command and control layer scalable.

Change-Id: I09ab7185683b66ec2567119616bc54cf9d8cc000

@Ruby, @Roman - thanks for your comments

>> What are your thoughts; that ironic-dbsync will default to 'upgrade' and the user will have to specify 'create'? Or change the default to 'create'?

I have no preferences about it, but leave ironic-dbsync default to 'upgrade' looks more suitable to me.

>> Or check if the dbfile exists, and if not, use create and if so, use upgrade?

Well, i can try to do it, if folks from core team will approve :)

>> What happens if the db exists already and you do a create?
>> What happens if the db exists but needs an upgrade, and you do a create?

Fail in the both cases


>> Would it be good to have unit tests to test the above scenarios?

Victor, thank you for your answers. I think The logic should be quite simple here: we check whether the schema already exists. If it does, it just stops and raises something to make it clear for everyone.

Another topic: is it possible to create a database itself? For me it sounds unreasonable to do that manually if there is already a script that can do that for me.

And one more nit: Ironic models don't set charset for the appropriate mysql tables so the default one is used (which is usually latin). Since we declare UTF8 support for some data and there are tests for that I'd wait until this fix I3dafed9dfe5042fab1cff2ea029ea62c5e5cbea3 is merged."}, {'account_id': 7491, 'date': '2014-08-04 09:29:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Roman, yes is it possible to create a database, but anyway it will be not related to this patch'}, {'account_id': 6623, 'date': '2014-08-04 12:33:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

I actually agree with Victor. We also discussed it in person and came up with this thoughts:

    1. Creating a database by a script is indeed a useful feature
    2. It may require specific permissions on different DBMS which the Ironic user might not be granted
    2.1. That should be a separate command, e.g., ironic-dbsync create_database which will be used or not by a deploy engineer dependent on their DB security settings
    3. That should definitely be in a separate patch.'}, {'account_id': 7491, 'date': '2014-08-07 11:01:36.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-07 11:01:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

commit_message:
Use metadata.create_all() to initialise DB schema

There is no need to run database migration each time, when we want to
get a new actual database schema. Running all migration scripts takes a
long time on production databases and can be not suitable for SQLite
because of Alembic limitation.

Added create_schema() method, which supposes to be used for initial
installation instead of upgrade('head').

Partial-Bug: #1347604

Change-Id: I039d955f051eda015bef2299122fd1f0fb5c46da

commit_message:
Sort requirement files in alphabetical order

This makes code more readable, and can check easily for specific library
in the requirement files. We also enforce the check in pep8.

Change-Id: I71d125671ce51fcbddeef66bdc4516800b6e4cbc
Closes-Bug: #1285478

commit_message:
Implementation of Endpoint Grouping

The Endpoint Filter extension has been extended to support Endpoint
Grouping which provides a dynamic endpoint attribute filtering capability
that is directly associated with a project.

Change-Id: I7b628ac565f58077ff7521458cc1d02b3bf47d29
implements bp multi-attribute-endpoint-grouping

commit_message:
Control extra space for images conversion in image_cache

Size of image converted to raw format can be growing up to virtual_size.
This patch adds new _fetch_to_raw function to image_cache which try to
free extra space for image conversion if needed.

Closes-Bug: #1356362
Change-Id: I69712b078113ef0640859389ef4ab9039135f612

commit_message:
Cleanup WBE example to be simpler to understand

This makes the example simpler to follow and understand when
it is using threads, is in one file and just uses the simpler
in-memory kombu backend by default (it can still use the file
transport if configured to use it).

Change-Id: I7fe9758e3285e7f0a610482bf26322841fb22f39

commit_message:
Removes test_force_delete_server_invalid_state negative test

Commit I06a476701ccb47d8f7fd6e43c394ccb3fac2b3aa allows the force
deleting of running instances as well as those in soft-delete state
so this negative test is no longer appropriate.

Related-Bug: #1351001
Change-Id: Ia6d09fea753196a8bc9f33ac8acaae49f1d306e7

commit_message:
tests: fix test_compute to have predictable service list

The _create_service_entries() method in test_compute.py accepted
a dict for the list of services. The tests would then pull out
the first item in the list of keys of the dict. When the python
hash seed is set to a random value the list of keys has no
predictable ordering, causing the test suite to break. Changing
the data structure to use a list of lists instead of a dict
ensures strict ordering.

Related-bug: #1350287
Change-Id: I01a0d4cfb086eb94b49d25b65daf08e55e2087b4

commit_message:
Add use of guestagent install shell script in infra dibs

all dibs elements have to be placed in the same directory
otherwise we cannot execute diskimage-builder command with
multiple elements. In our case we have to use guestagent
element with each infra element (drone, jenkins, gitolite).

Change-Id: I6e55350630e982adec1b338309421c7bdca4c9c3

(24 comments)

I see several improvements:

- Trace functions  might be useful in development, but I don't think that will be useful for operators. This tracing routines are bloating the code and won't be useful for users.

- logging scheme and options are different from default used in cinder, please log only on volume.log. Do consistent logging, and make then similar to other drivers in the codebase

- mutual exclusion should be granted with @utils.syncronized('') and you will be fine with concurrency problems. you will get a much cleaner code using that. See doc strings here: https://github.com/openstack/cinder/blob/master/cinder/openstack/common/lockutils.py#L138
  there also plenty of examples in other drivers.

- remove function that only call another functions (get_volume_metadata, get_snapshot, etc)

- several functions on common (get_volume_metadata, get_key, get_is_vvol, etc), are only used internally and should be declared as private. _func()

- keep in the common library only things that are really shared among FC and iSCSI drivers. For example, in HitachiLibrary._check_param() iSCSI and FC check whether they will use HSNM or RAIDCom. This is noly needed for FC, wich can use both command tools.

- you can post the new patches under the same Change-ID, so you don't have a separate thread for the same driver

- other inline comments"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-05-29 20:02:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

Erlon,

Thank you for your review.

Here is answer to your comments for both set1 and set4.

>Trace functions might be useful in development, but I don't think that will be useful for operators. This tracing routines are bloating the code and >won't be useful for users.
>logging scheme and options are different from default used in cinder, please log only on volume.log. Do consistent logging, and make then similar to 
>other drivers in the codebase

This driver logs messages to volume.log as other drivers do.
And we expect that operators diagnose issues with it.
As for our original debug.log, it it used for Hitachi engineers to analyze issues in detail.
So, there is not negative impact for users with our logging scheme. 

>keep in the common library only things that are really shared among FC and iSCSI drivers. For example, in HitachiLibrary._check_param() iSCSI and FC >check whether they will use HSNM or RAIDCom. This is noly needed for FC, wich can use both command tools.

It is already fixed in a latest code.

>- mutual exclusion should be granted with @utils.syncronized('') and you will be fine with concurrency problems. you will get a much cleaner code using >that. See doc strings here: https://github.com/openstack/cinder/blob/master/cinder/openstack/common/lockutils.py#L138

We tried to use @utils.syncronized(''), but decided not to use it because it can lock only method basis.
On the other hand, we want to lock a volume basis to have fine-grained lock. 

Of course, if our method is useful for others, we can consider to implement to cinder-core
for Kilo release or later.

>you had posted a change log somewhere, I can't find it, can you place it here?

change from "set3" to "set4".
 -  Add "AddFCZone" and "RemoveFCZone" decorators 
    to initialize_connection() and terminate_connection() for FC.

>there are several comments I made in the first review that wheren't addressed, 
>eg. using the serial number to select the array family, 

The serial number is an only way to detect an array precisely in case multiple arrays are connected.
So, I don't change a current implementation for Juno release.

If we find any other idea, I will consider to implement it for Kilo release or later.

>Line 106: # The following information is passed on to tests, when createing a volume
>"creating"
>Line 140: # The following information is passed on to tests, when createing a volume
>creating!

I will fix the misspelling. Thanks.

>Line 169:     def get_volume(self, volume_id):
>You don't need to define a function only to call another function. 

This function name is logged to our log file.
It makes easy to analyze a problem by logging it
because we can trace what operations are kicked by the function name.

>And, is get_volume used anywhere else outside this class? If no, it should be _private().

I don't think it is not essential. 
Actually, flake8 and pylint testing are passed.
So, I don't change the code at this time.

Seiji'}, {'account_id': 10058, 'date': '2014-07-24 11:46:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

Hi Seiji,

Those actually are not blocker problems. Just needed to understand why you did like that.

Introduce Hitachi storage volume driver

This patch introduces Hitachi storage volume driver.

Implements: blueprint hitachi-block-storage-driver

Certification test result for FC:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/cinder/+bug/1336661/+attachment/4189194/+files/FC%20tmp.pTAkWV3eWb

Certification test result for iSCSI:

Change-Id: Ie9b5df6d223b47d176c4e80fcf7e110543ce1d37
Signed-off-by: Seiji Aguchi <seiji.aguchi.tr@hitachi.com>

Hi Rajesh,

Many thanks for your patch. I've just given it a quick once over (not a full review since it's WIP) -- it's looking good :-)

In terms of picking up those oslo-incubator dependencies.

I had to do something similar for a keystone patch a while ago and I think it's typically done in two steps. So, first, a patch for the oslo-incubator bits you need, similar to this:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/98839

I added the module I needed to openstack-common.conf, and then ran

 python update.py ../keystone" (from oslo-incubator)

which auto-detected the full set of files required.

Then I pushed up a second patch (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/42967/) with a dependency on the first.'}, {'account_id': 9303, 'date': '2014-08-25 06:46:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hi All,

After syncing oslo-incubator common service framework with glance, some of the functional test cases were getting hanged even after completing the client requests.

IMO, functional test cases invokes RESTful APIs in three different ways:
1) httplib2
2) requests python module
3) glance db APIs

In the functional test cases when the requests is send, the server socket is not closed after sending the response to the client, and it hangs in 
[1] self._pool.waitall() method forever.

To fix this functional test case hangs issue, we need to make two changes:

1) eventlet.monkey_patch, this will fix all tests that hangs using glance db apis

2) If the RESTful APIs are called using 'httplib2' or 'request' python libraries, then you must pass "Connection:close" to the header.

By doing above changes all functional test cases are passing.

Please let me know your thoughts on the solution which I have applied to fix this issue.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/110012/2/glance/common/wsgi.py'}, {'account_id': 10795, 'date': '2014-08-27 11:24:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)

Hi Stuart McLaren,

As per your suggestion I have submitted two different patches for this change.

1. Sync oslo-incubator service module: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/117135/
2. Changes required to incorporate service module: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/117191/'}, {'account_id': 10795, 'date': '2014-09-03 17:17:31.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Marking this patch abandoned as it has been addressed in the new patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/117988/.'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-28 15:02:18.000000000', 'message': "Made provision for glance service to use Launcher

After sending SIGHUP signal to glance-service parent process,
it will call SIGHUP callback handler and then throws OSError.
The OSError is thrown because os.wait system call was
interrupted due to SIGHUP callback handler. As a result of
this parent process closes the server socket.
All child processes also gets terminated without completing
existing api requests because the server socket is already
closed and the service doesn't restart.

Added service module, launcher and common service module with
its dependencies from oslo-incubator in glance service.

After modifying the implemenatation, glance-service is able to
restart on sending SIGHUP signal to parent process and also
completing existing api requests.

Change-Id: I04d65225c3d01985fe35f36bf87b662bf190e23a

closed and the service doesn't restart.

Added service module, launcher and common service module with
its dependencies from oslo-incubator in glance service.

After modifying the implemenatation, glance-service is able to
restart on sending SIGHUP signal to parent process and also
completing existing api requests.

Made provision to pass default hub to eventlet.hubs.use_hub()
in oslo-incubator common service famework. Defined new configuration
parameter 'eventlet_hub' with default value as 'poll' in glance.cmd.api
and glance.cmd.registry  and leveraged same to service framework of
oslo-incubator.

Change-Id: I04d65225c3d01985fe35f36bf87b662bf190e23a
"}]
commit_message:
Made provision for glance service to use Launcher

After sending SIGHUP signal to glance-service parent process,
it will call SIGHUP callback handler and then throws OSError.
The OSError is thrown because os.wait system call was
interrupted due to SIGHUP callback handler. As a result of
this parent process closes the server socket.
All child processes also gets terminated without completing
existing api requests because the server socket is already
closed and the service doesn't restart.

Added service module, launcher and common service module with
its dependencies from oslo-incubator in glance service.

After modifying the implemenatation, glance-service is able to
restart on sending SIGHUP signal to parent process and also
completing existing api requests.

Made provision to pass default hub to eventlet.hubs.use_hub()
in oslo-incubator common service famework. Defined new configuration
parameter 'eventlet_hub' with default value as 'poll' in glance.cmd.api
and glance.cmd.registry  and leveraged same to service framework of
oslo-incubator.

Change-Id: I04d65225c3d01985fe35f36bf87b662bf190e23a

Clusters Guest Implementation

adds guest impl code for creating a sharded mongodb
cluster as the first implementation

Co-Authored-By: amcrn <amcreynolds@ebaysf.com>
Co-Authored-By: Mat Lowery <mlowery@ebaysf.com>
Co-Authored-By: svenkataramanaia <svenkataramanaia@ebaysf.com>

Partially implements: blueprint clustering

Change-Id: Id45f692df377a32310a30487e27cf0f017c93c86

commit_message:
Clusters TaskManager Implementation

adds clusters taskmanager impl, with mongodb sharding as the first
implementation.

Co-Authored-By: amcrn <amcreynolds@ebaysf.com>
Co-Authored-By: rumale <rumale@ebaysf.com>

Partially implements: blueprint clustering

commit_message:
Implement validation on Trust V3 API

Use JSONschema on create operations on V3 Trust API.

This change refactors a lot of the test_v3_auth tests to get them to
pass with proper validation.

Closes-Bug: #1362344
bp: api-validation

Change-Id: If4b59a6ac84e308eff8bf5ea35772173b0ba7fe5

commit_message:
XenAPI support: Disk rates

Implemented inspect_disk_rates() to inspect the disk statistics as rates
for an instance.

Change-Id: I0220e612b156a967745ff281ce09329fa0d15a12
Implements: blueprint xenapi-support

commit_message:
Remove concatenation with translated messages

Translated messages should not be expanded by concatenation.  Instead
the additional text should be replacement text or part of the translated
message to allow the translators as much information as possible when
doing the translations.

Also, when lazy translation is enabled, the object returned does not
support concatenation and raises an exception.  Thus this patch is
needed to support blueprint: i18n-enablement.

This patch includes a hacking check for concatenation with a translated
message.

Change-Id: I8b368d275faa14b4750735445321874ce1da37d5
Partially-Implements: blueprint i18n-enablement

commit_message:
Add support for glusterfs native protocol driver

This patch adds basic support for glusterfs native protocol driver
that uses cert based access type.

A Manila share is a GlusterFS volume. Unlike the generic driver, this
does not use service VM approach. Instances directly talk with the
GlusterFS backend storage pool. Instance use the 'glusterfs' protocol
to mount the GlusterFS share. Access to the share is allowed via
SSL Certificates. Only the share which has the SSL trust established
with the GlusterFS backend can mount and hence use the share.

Establishing the SSL trust between the instance and backend is done
out of band of Manila.

Partially-implements blueprint cert-based-access-type

Change-Id: I229d481086478317f1c43635304a16794372f09d

commit_message:
Context selection for project and region

Providing the mechanism to easily switch between projects and regions.

Only shows domain info if OPENSTACK_KEYSTONE_MULTIDOMAIN_SUPPORT is set
to True in settings.

Will add domain switching for v3 once support for it is complete.
Will add advance filtering rules in follow up patch.

Co-Authored-By: David Lyle <david.lyle@hp.com>

Implements: blueprint context-selection

Change-Id: Ie6e81eebe822ab2394b07345d148a1c06a33a25f

I've been looking at changing this to be more RESTful as Vipul suggested: unset the slave_of_id to detach the slave, rather than using an action.

I see that we already do something similar for configuration groups: a group is detached from an instance by doing a PUT to unset the configuration attribute on the instance.

If we were to handle slave_of the same way, I think there's a race condition between multiple clients independently trying to set or clear the various attributes on instance. commit_message:
Add detach-replica support

Add a PATCH route to unset the slave_of property on an instance, i.e. to
detach a replica from its replication source.

Rename existing 'detach_replication_slave' functions to 'detach_replica'
to be consistent with the python-troveclient.

Add test case to tests/api/replication.py.

Partially Implements: blueprint replication-v1

Change-Id: I3596a3b76cc484b42db38f02e51c028d5ff2ed6c

commit_message:
Big Switch: Separate L3 functions into L3 service

Separate the L3 functions from the core Big Switch
plugin into an L3 service plugin. This is will allow
the L3 functions to be used in ML2 deployments that
use the Big Switch ML2 driver.

DocImpact

Implements: blueprint bsn-l3-service-plugin
Change-Id: I889db0047fb9a85f02d1fb95b9c099e9243a5bb5

commit_message:
Disable oslo.messaging debug logs

ioslo.messaging debug logs are too verbose, turn them off. A similar
patch dropped nova-conductor logs in the gate down from 7MB to under 300K.

Cherry-Pick from oslo-incubator since we are in feature freeze:
Ia12c003dae196e2220a5f6ea768758a75f2ede23 and
Icc61964c6a2b002ac1c8566f174e6a5230674c75

Change-Id: I48733823e178afd2f22d81d584bb73f95ec9a7cd
