commit_message:
Mark the revoke kvs backend deprecated, for removal in Kilo

Although the kvs.Base was marked as deprecated, the individual
backends were not.  This marks the kvs revoke backend.

Change-Id: I6592cce10687e355536a4c9f89fc885692a73e23
Partially-implements: bp deprecated-as-of-juno

commit_message:
VMware: Do not read opaque type for DVS network

Save backend calls when using DVS VIF type. There is no need to
get the opaque network in the event that we have a DVS network.

Change-Id: I75973005193f862dfde3b99167cb53d3114a8349

Fixed DB connection options

* changed placement of database settings from
DEFAULT to database section of the heat.conf
* sql_connection option is deprecated
Related-Bug: #1364026

commit_message:
Port limits extension to work in v2.1/v3 framework

Ports v2 limits extension and adapts it to the v2.1/v3 API
framework. API behaviour is identical with the exception that
there is no support for rate limiting since no one uses that
seriously anyway.

- unittest code modified to share testing with both v2/v2.1
- Adds expected error decorators for API methods

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I072d364f4d2a92a02801862435f11417956d2dc0

[{'created': '2014-07-17 07:44:02.000000000', 'message': "Implement EC2 eip/eipassociation resources updatable

It supports the AWS::EC2::EIP and AWS::EC2::EIPAssociation resources
updatable to be compatible with AWSCloudFormation.
1. Support 'InstanceId' property updatable for AWS::EC2::EIP resource
2. Support 'InstanceId', 'EIP', 'AllocationId', 'NetworkInterfaceId'
properties updatable for AWS::EC2::EIPAssociation resource
3. Add validate function to check whether provide one of 'EIP' and
'AllocationId' for AWS::EC2::EIPAssociation resource
4. Modify the way to get 'network_id' of the port for
AWS::EC2::EIPAssociation resource
5. Modify if the association is not created successful, don't try to
delete it.

Implements blueprint implement-ec2eip-updatable

Change-Id: I1e6fa87ba5dd89ea41ec9639f6a940f857be33da

commit_message:
Implement EC2 eip/eipassociation resources updatable

It supports the AWS::EC2::EIP and AWS::EC2::EIPAssociation resources
updatable to be compatible with AWSCloudFormation.
1. Support 'InstanceId' property updatable for AWS::EC2::EIP resource
2. Support 'InstanceId', 'EIP', 'AllocationId', 'NetworkInterfaceId'
properties updatable for AWS::EC2::EIPAssociation resource
3. Add validate function to check whether provide one of 'EIP' and
'AllocationId' for AWS::EC2::EIPAssociation resource
4. Modify the way to get 'network_id' of the port for
AWS::EC2::EIPAssociation resource
5. Modify if the association is not created successful, don't try to
delete it.

Implements blueprint implement-ec2eip-updatable

Change-Id: I1e6fa87ba5dd89ea41ec9639f6a940f857be33da

commit_message:
Fix file location for nova compute rbd secret

The rbd secret location was mixed between /etc/nova
and /etc/ceph. This patch changes the secret to
be in /etc/nova for both the file and exec
resources so that virsh secrets are set correctly

Change-Id: I50f0324d911f20d5a072c769edcf289ae59f817a

commit_message:
Reorg AutoScalingGroup code

The current class hierarchy of autoscaling groups in Heat is hindering
further improvements to both AWS version and OS version.  On one hand,
we don't want OS resources to extend AWS resources; on the other hand,
we have a lot proposals to enhance the OS version.  Also, the classes
should be split and relocated into different subdirectories.

Change-Id: Idedc141b9f63e4ed20b54bd297d2f737fe1249d1

commit_message:
Configurable base location of worker scripts

Depending on how Solum is installed, the contrib directory
may not exist in the directory three levels above handlers/shell.
In such a case, shell Handler's build and test functions  will fail
as it cannot find those scripts.

This change takes advantage of the Handler's proj_dir property,
allowing it to supercede the relative path if it's set.
The name proj_dir reflects the directory that contains the contrib directory,
among others, because that is where the original project codebase lies.

Change-Id: I9add45d93d5be801193e7ac45235cb55c347020b

commit_message:
Add example of using native waitcondition resources

Adds a simple example of using the native WaitCondition and
WaitConditionHandle resources, which work in a similar way to
the CFN compatible ones, but with more relaxed validation of
data, and some additional helper attributes so you don't need
to remember how to write the curl call in the template unless
you need something unusual in the request.

Change-Id: I2686d07e882781e93949ded9dd260161e4514a3b

commit_message:
Fix and improve autoscaling.yaml

Fixed a problem: the health monitor's delay was less than its timeout,
which is now disallowed.

Added stack outputs that show and explain the webhooks and a
ceilometer query that selects samples about VMs in the stack.
Also added an output that shows the entry IP address.

Change-Id: I11313f05d885cb0698a904f08725227b03617e0c

commit_message:
Get rid of ordered decorator in func tests

Test should not rely on the order of it's execution
Now are tests are independent from each other so ordered decorator is not needed anymore

Change-Id: I2ca86aa91dbe0e6f3b9256d1b2e0005029071118

commit_message:
Moving git_url into git_info dictionary

This patch is done in anticipation of adding extra
git information like the branch and private keys to
expand on unittest-app and build-app's functionality.

Keeping all the information in one dictionary instead of
as additional kwargs will reduce the need for changes to
solum-worker's API.

Change-Id: I4b15e03b183f3cdcd6f9442288a307cb5ec2792f

commit_message:
Adds ability to override service name for service catalog

Instead of forcing the name of the service in the service catalog to
match auth_name, this allows the ability to explicitly set the service
name, spearately from auth_name.
If service_name is not specified, it's value defaults to the value
of auth_name (which maintains the current behavior.)

Closes-bug: #1359755
Change-Id: I66dadaebb526cfae2b6c250b2bef97e1e6d6aafe

commit_message:
Adds ability to override service names for service catalog

Instead of forcing the name of the service in the service catalog to
match auth_name, this allows the ability to explicitly set the service
name, spearately from auth_name.

If service_name is not specified, it's value defaults to the value
of auth_name (which maintains the current behavior.)

Closes-bug: #1359755
Change-Id: I1d26aa7970471a40d7d636387826523925a71844

commit_message:
Adds ability to override service name for service catalog

Instead of forcing the name of the service in the service catalog to
match auth_name, this allows the ability to explicitly set the service
name, spearately from auth_name.

If service_name is not specified, it's value defaults to the value
of auth_name (which maintains the current behavior.)

Closes-bug: #1359755
Change-Id: Ieec7cdaab792b48c4640f6e1f2470e48640387d7

subject: Adds ability to override service names for service catalog

commit_message:
Adds ability to override service names for service catalog

Instead of forcing the name of the services in the service catalog to
match auth_name and auth_name_v3, this allows the ability to explicitly
set the service names, separately from auth_name and auth_name_v3.

If service_name or service_name_v3 is not specified, their values
default to the value of auth_name and auth_name_v3, respectively
(which maintains the current behavior.)

Closes-bug: #1359755
Change-Id: Ie34099d6f9746ce883d711a27b9d93613924c3ee

commit_message:
Add extended logging options.

There is a range of extended logging options in Openstack services that use
openstack.common.logger (Ceilometer, Cinder, Heat, Keystone, Nova). Adding
heat::logging to support them. This change is identical to
<https://review.openstack.org/#/c/113560/> but it applies to puppet-heat
instead of puppet-ceilometer.

No blueprint/spec, as discussed in the IRC meeting on 08-11-2014.

Change-Id: Ia120b799d676e516d8e593088f93d44891c20cbd

commit_message:
Add extended logging options.

There is a range of extended logging options in Openstack services that use
openstack.common.logger (Ceilometer, Cinder, Heat, Keystone, Nova). Adding
cinder::logging to support them. This change is identical to
<https://review.openstack.org/#/c/113560/> but it applies to puppet-cinder
instead of puppet-ceilometer.

No blueprint/spec, as discussed in the IRC meeting on 08-11-2014.

Change-Id: Id1d4380157e681da9ada2e2647ab285ce3cc40ad

commit_message:
Add extended logging options.

There is a range of extended logging options in Openstack services that use
openstack.common.logger (Ceilometer, Cinder, Heat, Keystone, Nova). Adding
keystone::logging to support them. This change is identical to
<https://review.openstack.org/#/c/113560/> but it applies to puppet-keystone
instead of puppet-ceilometer.

No blueprint/spec, as discussed in the IRC meeting on 08-11-2014.

Change-Id: I88fcf025b9467090d21d1a10a5af9b270f8ef11e

commit_message:
Add rabbit_ha_queues option

In current, rabbit_ha_queues option is controled by rabbit_hosts
if conditional statement. When users want to set rabbit_ha_queues
to true and they don't use rabbit_hosts option, this logic will
not satisfy their needs.

This patch adds an $rabbit_ha_queues option, set it to undef by default
for forward compatbility.

Change-Id: Iaf6157f6b7acb148bd7da41421b4a3de6c4e2194
Closes-bug: 1361700

commit_message:
Remove unnecessary whitespace from PKI & PKIZ tokens

This overrides the default key-value separator (normally ": ") in favor
of a separator that does not contain any whitespace (":"), which results
in equivalent JSON.

Change-Id: Iea4a8df74f5e4c511d37894601c28615fb0eda6b
Closes-Bug: 1348262

commit_message:
Fixes glanceclient gating

requests 2.4.0 was released 2014-08-29 and breaks
glanceclient testing with error:
"ProtocolError: ('Connection aborted.',
gaierror(-2, 'Name or service not known'))"

This change limits the requests version <2.4.0 to allow client gating.

Closes-Bug: #1364893
Co-Author: Pawel Koniszewski <pawel.koniszewski@intel.com>
Change-Id: I2f2431230b50646fc942aa79cd25ff7edd973026

framework. API behaviour is identical with the exception
that there is no support for XML. Also

  where appropriate
- Adds expected error decorators for API methods

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

commit_message:
Port v2 images extension to work in v2.1(v3) framework

Ports v2 images extension and adapts it to the v2.1/v3 API
framework. API behaviour is identical with the exception
that there is no support for XML. Also

- unittest code modified to share testing with both v2/v2.1
  where appropriate
- Adds expected error decorators for API methods

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I7b15a56f41612e3bbf5d59c3ad44fd32386ff315

commit_message:
Handle DracInvalidFilterDialect exception

The DRAC wsman_enumerate() method can now raise DracInvalidFilterDialect
if the filter dialect specified is not valid, this patch simply makes
the try..except blocks around the wsman_enumerate() to also handle the
DracInvalidFilterDialect exception nicely when raised.

Change-Id: Ide029562ce74e25c90dedca3dc6479f2caa5db58

commit_message:
Resolve Vagrant issue 1673

When using the shell or puppet provisionier with Ubuntu there is
always an error message 'stdin: is not a tty'. According to the
bugreport https://github.com/mitchellh/vagrant/issues/1673
using 'bash -c 'BASH_ENV=/etc/profile exec bash'' as shell solves
this issue.

Change-Id: I4aa8b51545f881e548830f91d5b5c543bd6ef613

commit_message:
Enfore the used Vagrantfile API/syntax version when not initialised

If there is no base Vagrantfile (~/.vagrant.d/Vagrantfile) it's not
possible to start the box because VAGRANTFILE_API_VERSION is not
initialised by default.

Initializing VAGRANTFILE_API_VERSION when not set will resolve the
following issue: "uninitialized constant VAGRANTFILE_API_VERSION".

Change-Id: Ic3dc7b7e78b2634ad902a713cdac02ace71dce1d

commit_message:
Added ability to create security group automatically

Added ability to ask Sahara to create security group for node group. Feature
is only implemented in vanilla plugin 1.2.1 so far.

Partially implements: blueprint cluster-secgroups

Change-Id: I21d0196396bb966fe3d88f5445e98aebe90ad94b

Comment added.

w.r.t. immutable history - one can fixup (rolling forward of course) anything one wants to, but after we've e.g. released to pypi we can't fix things by rolling back.

Longer version: there are two forms of error here:
 A - failure to indicate a large enough semver change
 B - indicating a too-large semver change

A is easy to fix: just do an empty commit with an appropriate semver statement. Simples.

B is harder - but we could add an override thing if we want to - however if we had pushed a snapshot or release to an external site before we noticed - we can't roll that back sanely, so its best practice to roll forward at that point - suckup the higher version and move on."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2014-08-25 23:27:02.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 18.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-26 02:36:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 18: Verified+1

[{'created': '2014-07-21 05:00:38.000000000', 'message': 'Look for and process sem-ver pseudo headers in git

At the moment careful changelog review is needed by humands to
determine the next version number. Semantic versioning means that all
we need to know to get a reasonable default next version (and a lower
bound on the next version) is a record of bugfix/deprecation/feature
work and api-breaking commits. In this patch we start scanning for
such headers from the git history to remove this burden from
developers/project release managers. Higher versions can of course
be used either via pre-versioning or by tagging the desired version.

implements: blueprint pbr-semver
sem-ver: feature

commit_message:
Look for and process sem-ver pseudo headers in git

At the moment careful changelog review is needed by humans to
determine the next version number. Semantic versioning means that all
we need to know to get a reasonable default next version (and a lower
bound on the next version) is a record of bugfix/deprecation/feature
work and api-breaking commits. In this patch we start scanning for
such headers from the git history to remove this burden from
developers/project release managers. Higher versions can of course
be used either via pre-versioning or by tagging the desired version.

implements: blueprint pbr-semver
sem-ver: feature
Change-Id: Id5e8cd723d5186d1bd8c01599eae8933e6f7ea6d

commit_message:
make backup_incremental_strategy a datastore specific option

backup_incremental_strategy remained a common option even after
backup_strategy became a datastore specific option. This change moves
backup_incremental_strategy to a datastore specific option with the
appropriate decorations for deprecation.

Change-Id: I6113ae9aede6b2c9cb960320e05960df2de34566
Closes-Bug: #1354959

commit_message:
mariadb: call os-svc-enable

When configuring Mariadb we should always auto-start the
Mariadb (or mysql) daemon on startup. This prevents breaking simple
use cases like rebooting nodes, etc.

This patch updates the mariadb-rpm element to autostart mariadb.

The mariadb element is also updated to autostart 'mysql' (which
is the service name that element uses instead).

Change-Id: I02ccead89ce5054557a7037cbf127cbe6e75425b

commit_message:
py3: Use six module for StringIO imports

It is python 2/3 compatibility change.
six.StringIO an alias for StringIO.StringIO in Python 2 and
io.StringIO in Python 3.

Partially implements blueprint py3-compatibility

Change-Id: Ib2f570645d3b0a4b3bd38c017693e0b1b77f3236

commit_message:
Fix minor issues in the DRAC driver

This is a following patch of 2eb3c12ce3fb2b2eb4408367f2c950724a098d93. The
issues this patch fixes are:

* Put the ReturnValue constants in a common place so it can be used by
  the power and management interfaces code.
* Move the filter object creation to inside the client. This also adds
  a new exception DracInvalidFilterDialect which is raised if when an
  invalid filter dialect is specified.
* Fix the docstring of the find_xml method to reflect the values returned
  in case an element is not found.
* Move the helper test function _mock_wsman_root() to a common place
  and update tests to use it.

Change-Id: Iefc3993f61e32a3a50faf4b9bd80aaab6ae1d3bf

The code looks good...although we need an sql upgrade test to be added to test_sql_upgrade.py'}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2014-08-21 09:27:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Actually I may have a more serious concern...(unless I have the wrong end of the stick - in which case, please correct me!!)

Prior to this patch, a region has a region_id (which was usually supplied by the caller of create_region()). For an endpoint to be in that region, the endpoint['region'] field contains this region_id.  After this patch, the "old region id" will be put in region['name'] and a real (but concealed) uuid region['id] will be created, and the new endpoint['region_id'] will point to it.  So far so good.  But think of the following sequence (happening after this patch is in):

- I read an endpoint, and it looks like it always did (since you have wrapped the get_endpoint() call to re-instate the endpoint['region']).  This endpoint['region'] field contains what is (now) in the region['name'] column.
- So as a caller I want to read the region entity for this endpoint...so I do what I always did and call get_region() with the endpoint['region']...and...it fails!  Since get_region wants the REAL region_id, which has been concealed.'}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2014-08-21 10:16:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

It seems to me that what we are saying is:

1) (Potentially) rename region -> region_id in the endpoint entity.  If we do rename it, then we need to allow the callers of the public API to still use region (maybe do this is in the controller rather than the backend).  If we do this, I'd recommend we still expose the endpoint region_id field in the entity...we just still support specify region as well for backward compatibility.
2) Make the region/region_id field in the endpoint be a FK to the region entity PK. which remains a user-defined ID.  No Name field is added.
3) On migration, if there already exists a region entity with the ID that matches the existing endpoint[region] field, then make the Fk link and we're done.  If a region entity does not exist, then we create one with the PK as specified in endpoint[region]"}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2014-08-21 22:47:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

(Damn, I hate the formatting here...): It seems to me that what we are saying is:

1) (Potentially) rename region -> region_id in the endpoint entity. If we do rename it, then we need to allow the callers of the public API to still use region (maybe do this is in the controller rather than the backend). If we do this, I'd recommend we still expose the endpoint region_id field in the entity...we just still support specify region as well for backward compatibility.

2) Make the region/region_id field in the endpoint be a FK to the region entity PK. which remains a user-defined ID. No Name field is added.

3) On migration, if there already exists a region entity with the ID that matches the existing endpoint[region] field, then make the Fk link and we're done. If a region entity does not exist, then we create one with the PK as specified in endpoint[region]"}, {'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2014-08-22 02:56:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Workflow-1

(1 comment)

So in this version:

1) If you use the v2 API to create a endpoint with a region, then only endpoint['region'] is supported - and the region will be automatically created for you

2) If you use the v3 API, then you can use either endpoint['region'] or endpoint['region_id'], but in both cases the region must already exist

While that's a reasonable position, I wonder if we should auto-create the region via the v3 API if you use the endpoint['region'] version...to preserve existing behaviour (but if you use endpoint['region_id'], then the region must already exist)?

This is why we need an identity-api spec patch!!!  If it would help, I'll be happy to proposed one."}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2014-08-26 09:14:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 17:

For v2 catalog endpoint creation, its been taken care that if the enpoint.region is not already created, it will create it before creating the endpoint. so tempest test passed.

But for v3 catalog endpoint test cases, its expected that region needs to be created by user( and tempest) via v3 region REST API. and that region should be used in the endpoint being created via v3 catalog.  But tempest seems to be not creating the region currently and is failing with error : "region not found with xxxx". 

I am not sure how to fix this tempest as part of this patch. could anyone kindly help me here. thanks.'}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2014-08-26 10:42:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 19:

Endpoint table is missing reference to region table

Endpoint table is updated to make foreign key
reference to Region table and this patch
implements the following blueprint

bp: endpoint-table-missing-reference-to-region-table

DocImpact

commit_message:
Implement claim and message expiration logic for Redis

This patch uses Redis where possible to automatically expire
claim and message data. Where it is not possible, manual
GC functions have been added in order to iterate through the
remaining data and clean it up.

Note that this patch does not include an implementation for
a command script that will call the Redis drivers' GC
method. That will be done in a followup patch.

Also, the GC functions in this patch do not decrement the
stats counters, since those are actually removed in the next
patch.

This change has been tested locally on my box using the
ZAQAR_TEST_REDIS=1 flag.

Change-Id: I38bfc52cf2de0ed078478aca80e6ad56b5bd55aa
Partially-Implements: blueprint redis-storage-driver

commit_message:
Cleaned up sample trove-guestagent.conf

Cleaned out the trove-guestagent.conf to only contain values that make
sense for the guest agent. There were also values that were different
between the sample conf, and the defaults in cfg.py, which were fixed
to be consistent, so as to have a single set of sane defaults.

Closes bug: 1336618

Change-Id: Ib3823856c288971665fa29489c4ffc5b899ccbaf

commit_message:
Allow worker count to be specified when no executor provided

When a multi-threaded engine is used it is nice to be able
to inform the engine how many workers should be created when
it creates its own executor. To allow this to be possible accept
a new keywork argument that can be used to set this value.

Change-Id: I0095d548249372440abbcf9b5c3b8fa841ca0ea9

Wouldn't it be useful to use 'w' and put in some information about the process that owns the lock (pid?) to help operators know which lock files they can remove and which ones they shouldn't. TBH, I don't think we need to anyway.  If we want to clean up a lock file, all we need to do is lock it, delete it, and then if someone wants to use that lock again it will be recreated by the file open call.  In fact, I'm wondering if we could eliminate the leftover files problem by just doing that during all lock releases.  Something to look into anyway."}, {'account_id': 708, 'date': '2014-08-25 17:27:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Address some potential security issues in lockutils

Adds a note to the lock_path help text explaining how to secure the
target directory.  Also opens lock files in append mode so there is
no possibility of overwriting a file due to a malicious symlink.

Change-Id: I77b72b20088fe66b573c23bd1fd98376c2b0f168

commit_message:
Reduce boilerplate code using get_client_manager

There are a few Tempest tests that contain boilerplate code used
to create an Openstack manager client. This commit removes this
boilerplate code with the following changes:

1. BaseTestCase.get_client_manager now generates different
   credentials based on the type of user type passed in. There
   are also optional keyword arguments to control the type of
   manager to be instantiate as well as an alternate manager type
   in case tenant isolation is disabled.

2. Updated the test that was using tenant isolation to use the
   updated get_client_manager method

Change-Id: I5c73cb8db96c0e1e97a553404d484996ff7bbf2c
Closes-Bug: #1246932

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-02 15:54:34.000000000', 'message': "Upgrades, don't kill new containers during the upgrade

Stopping of new containers during the upgrade
leads to a lot of errors and raise conditions.
In the same time containers should be run under
supervisor because we need to store logs.

Rewrote upgrade flow:

* stop old containers
* upload the images
* generate supervisor config with autostart False,
  it allows to prevent supervisor to run containers
* run containers in method `create_and_start_new_containers`
  one by one in right order
* regenerate configs for supervisor with autostart
  True, to start all of the containers after supervisor
  restart
* verify containers

How it helps?

* there was race condition when we were running
  services via supervisor and iptables cleaning
  at the same time, supervisor not always was
  able to start all containers, as result we
  could get nat rules with the same port but
  different ip addresses
* containers stopping could interrupt non-atomic
  actions, like db migration in keystone container
* since we run container one by one, we will not
  be able to get problem with ip duplication,
  during the upgrade

Related-bug: #1357357
Related-bug: #1364087
Closes-bug: #1364054
Change-Id: I86accb8b2c2fc5a15425e32838a58c9b45022d8d

commit_message:
Upgrades, don't kill new containers during the upgrade

Stopping of new containers during the upgrade
leads to a lot of errors and raise conditions.
At the same time containers should be run under
supervisor because we need to store logs.

Rewrote upgrade flow:

* stop old containers
* upload the images
* generate supervisor config with autostart False,
  it allows to prevent supervisor to run containers
* run containers in method `create_and_start_new_containers`
  one by one in right order
* regenerate configs for supervisor with autostart
  True, to start all of the containers after supervisor
  restart
* verify containers

How it helps:

* there was race condition when we were running
  services via supervisor and iptables cleaning
  at the same time, supervisor not always was
  able to start all containers, as result we
  could get nat rules with the same port but
  different ip addresses
* containers stopping could interrupt non-atomic
  actions, like db migration in keystone container
* since we run container one by one, we will not
  be able to get problem with ip duplication,
  during the upgrade

Related-bug: #1357357
Related-bug: #1364087
Closes-bug: #1364054
Change-Id: I86accb8b2c2fc5a15425e32838a58c9b45022d8d

commit_message:
addCleanup is missing in create snapshot test

This patch adds "addCleanup" to the create snapshot test.
Without this, the test won't wait for a successful delete snapshot
to complete and causes failure when delete volume happens.

CCLA SCHEDULE B SUBMISSION

Change-Id: I3d7ebfa24c14aa7cafb10e8ee5313bb3d4bce978
Closes-Bug: 1351441

(3 comments)

This has some good ideas for sure but I really think we need to land the other RemoteFS work before this one:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/106066/

The other patch:
 (a) is just a refactor/move of code (this patch actually changes things)
 (b) already created the new RemoteFS exceptions which are also present here
 (c) goes further into the effort to organize this stuff by putting RemoteFS* into its own file and segmenting RemoteFS vs. RemoteFSSnapshot code

So I don't see much motivation to land this one first.  There are changes involved here which are more complex than just refactoring.  (Commit message is a little misleading.)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-31 21:14:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

commit_message:
Just use int(BOOL) to convert to 1 or 0

(This is split out from I24461f4328e188c8983ad574495e11e033ec5ba4 on
neutron, which was a hunt to remove "PRED and A or B" deprecated ternary
idiom.)

int(bool) already returns only 1 or 0 - no need to do our own explicit
version.

Change-Id: Ib482d6cb63ece7e1d5073fa7dc1c7daf9db8a0b3

commit_message:
Make the WBE worker banner information more meaningful

Add in more details that are displayed in the LOG when
a WBE worker is started up that is useful to show to be
able to help in debugging, or other informational and
operational purposes.

Example of the new output is the following:

TaskFlow v0.3.21.62 WBE worker.
Connection details:
  Driver = py-amqp v1.4.5
  Exchange = test
  Topic = test
  Transport = amqp
  Uri = amqp://guest@localhost:5672//
Powered by:
  Executor = concurrent.futures.thread.ThreadPoolExecutor
  Thread count = 3
Supported endpoints:
  - taskflow.tests.utils.NastyTask
  ...
  - taskflow.tests.utils.TaskMultiArgOneReturn
System details:
  Hostname = lappy.gateway.net
  Pid = 28364
  Platform = Linux-3.13.0-30-generic-x86_64-with-Ubuntu-14.04-trusty
  Python = 2.7.6 (default, Mar 22 2014, 22:59:56)
  Thread id = 139875992315712

Change-Id: I6d7dba3406007ddc80cce96cfdbbfd25935a12ae

commit_message:
Mask passwords in exceptions and error messages

When a ProcessExecutionError is thrown by processutils.ssh_execute(),
the exception may contain information such as password. Upstream
applications that just log the message (as several appear to do) could
inadvertently expose these passwords to a user with read access to the
log files. It is therefore considered prudent to invoke
strutils.mask_password() on the command, stdout and stderr in the
exception. A test case has been added to ensure that all three are
properly masked.

An earlier commit (e8199714) failed to address ssh_execute(). This
change set addresses ssh_execute.

OSSA is aware of this change request.

Change-Id: I0db9e98cbeb2a5e6f9ae0074f24717aa91cfc238
Closes-Bug: #1343604

(2 comments)

The proposed fix to use mysqladmin shutdown looks good to me, but I think you'll need to include --password.

FYI: After comparing the source of pexpect 2.3 (which is what a kick-start mysql image currently gets) with and 3.3, I don't see a relevant change there. The close() method has always supported force=True as a way to terminate the child process, and it boils down to series of os.kill calls with different signals.

I believe the issue here is the one described in https://bugs.launchpad.net/trove/+bug/1343344. I had proposed a fix for the restore strategy as well but have removed that file in favor of your change."}, {'account_id': 8415, 'date': '2014-07-18 22:36:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Fixed restore to work correctly with pexpect

Fixed an issue with restore where it was failing with the latest
version of pexpect in Ubuntu 14.04.

pexpect attempts to stop the temp mysqld process which fails due to
a difference in privilege level (since the process was run with sudo).
We now use mysqladmin shutdown to stop the temp mysqld process.

Closes-Bug: 1343344

Change-Id: Iba81648bb1654db97de876dd9a0dbfb04b8811d1

commit_message:
Refactoring to reduce noise in log files

Currently lot of unnecessary log lines are generated during API
invocation and image transfer. This patch makes log printing
statement changes to reduce noise in log files.

Change-Id: Ifdd43a9d1d32cb6d8957b9805b56729eb9270daf

commit_message:
Fix unit tests to work with random PYTHONHASHSEED

Fixed the unit tests that were failing with the random
python hash seed value.

Change-Id: I52afa7446cb2714fbab624d1515bcc6e9d6b98d8
Closes-bug: 1348818

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-14 20:38:01.000000000', 'message': 'Cisco VPN with in-band CSR (interim solution)

Currently, the Cisco VPN drivers use two routers for the proof of concept
solution. A Neutron router provides access to the public and private
subnets, and a Cisco CSR (out-of-band) provides the VPN tunneling.

The end goal is to integrate the Cisco VPN drivers with the Cisco L3
routing plugin being developed (as a separate blueprint), allowing an
in-band CSR to be used as a Neutron router for VPN functionality.

This commit provides an incremental approach to that goal, by modifying
the Cisco VPN drivers to be able to dynamically obtain CSR info from
an INI file, instead of statically reading the INI file at start-up.

A CSR VM can be created out-of-band (or in-band using Nova) and the INI
file can be updated with the router info. Then, the Cisco VPN driver
can use that information (dynamically) to create IPSec connections.

Once the Cisco L3 router plugin is available, the INI file will be
removed, and two calls to the plugin will be used to obtain the needed
router information, for an integrated solution.

The main advantages are:
    - Dynamically use the CSR for VPN.
    - Less manual intervention and setup.
    - Easy migration to final solution.
    - No dependency on the Cisco L3 router plugin implementation.

Note 1: The INI unit tests are moved from device driver to service
        driver and modified.

Note 2: I added a unit test for deleting IPSec site-to-site connection,
        which was missing (pass).

Note 3: For more details on the change, you can view this Google Doc:
        http://goo.gl/DXir8c

Change-Id: I307fc79952e3e12a0f77679ac1fc2b314fa63684
Partially-Implements: blueprint cisco-vpnaas-with-cisco-csr-router

commit_message:
Cisco VPN with in-band CSR (interim solution)

Currently, the Cisco VPN drivers use two routers for the proof of concept
solution. A Neutron router provides access to the public and private
subnets, and a Cisco CSR (out-of-band) provides the VPN tunneling.

The end goal is to integrate the Cisco VPN drivers with the Cisco L3
routing plugin being developed (as a separate blueprint), allowing an
in-band CSR to be used as a Neutron router for VPN functionality.

This commit provides an incremental approach to that goal, by modifying
the Cisco VPN drivers to be able to dynamically obtain CSR info from
an INI file, instead of statically reading the INI file at start-up.

A CSR VM can be created out-of-band (or in-band using Nova) and the INI
file can be updated with the router info. Then, the Cisco VPN driver
can use that information (dynamically) to create IPSec connections.

Once the Cisco L3 router plugin is available, the INI file will be
removed, and two calls to the plugin will be used to obtain the needed
router information, for an integrated solution.

The main advantages are:
    - Dynamically use the CSR for VPN.
    - Less manual intervention and setup.
    - Easy migration to final solution.
    - No dependency on the Cisco L3 router plugin implementation.

Note 1: The INI unit tests are moved from device driver to service
        driver and modified.

Note 2: I added a unit test for deleting IPSec site-to-site connection,
        which was missing (pass).

Note 3: For more details on the change, you can view this Google Doc:
        http://goo.gl/DXir8c

Change-Id: I307fc79952e3e12a0f77679ac1fc2b314fa63684
Partially-Implements: blueprint cisco-vpnaas-with-cisco-csr-router

commit_message:
Explicitly set DIB_REPOREF_*

Explicitly tell source-repositories which revision of a project to pull
in, source-repositories by default pulls in "master", which is ok for
all projects except the one we actually want to test (devstack-gate
leaves the commit we want checked out in a detached head).

Upto now we haven't been testing the correct version of most of the
commits in the experimental queue.

Change-Id: Ibb4be09b22179d62c9d6f0afb2525c521bb3f36d
Closes-Bug: #1364345

commit_message:
Sahara clusters networking parameters

Added support for floating_ip_pool and neutron_management_network
parameters. These parameters will allow to becnchmark Sahara in all
network configurations.

Change-Id: I17c601695a38ed01c6e932b3c18fefe6bee703c7

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

Oleg, Edgar:  Why does execute() need yet another parameter?  If a caller cares about a non-zero exit status, the 'check_exit_code' is how they indicate this and error logging should center around that."}, {'account_id': 5948, 'date': '2014-09-03 11:53:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Maru, in commit 77046d0d889a8bff095083ae80a2accd0e25406b error logging was done outside of checking check_exit_code, so I thought it might be done intentionally for some cases. Also it would require to complicate logic in functions like device_exists or ensure_device_is_ready where we need to know if an operation was successfull or not by catching RuntumeError - so just setting check_exit_code to False to avoid error logging will not work. What do you think?'}]

commit_message:
Make log level in linux.utils.execute configurable

Function linux.utils.execute always logs failures on error level.
Some callers use this function to check resource existance and
interpret failure as normal flow. Log level is made configurable
for such cases.

Change-Id: I8e4cd7b42234426f8fe58d353a64e898f02f8998
Closes-bug: 1339045

Change-Id: Ie16d281aed364e45456296d95606037d54df9651
Implements: partial-blueprint action-aware-sw-config

commit_message:
Extend software_configs API for SoftwareComponent

This patch extends the software_configs API backend to support multiple
'configs' in one resource, as it is the case for the new
OS::Heat::SoftwareComponent resource type that is derived from
OS::Heat::SoftwareConfig.

Change-Id: Ie16d281aed364e45456296d95606037d54df9651
Implements: partial-blueprint action-aware-sw-config

Remove localboot provides.

The current element-provides points to localboot
which results in error. Removing it to make it work
as its not needed at all.

commit_message:
Create files in bootstrap as owner root

Logrotate will not work if its config is
owned by non-root user.

Change-Id: I12fcf970f3e843e92215b19ab651af4dd8a5e48e
Closes-Bug: #1364083

commit_message:
Add send-data-to-ceilometer support for pxe_ipminative driver

This patch will implement pxe_ipminative driver *get_sensors_data* method to get
sensor data by pyghmi get_sensor_data() method call.

Spec:
https://github.com/openstack/ironic-specs/blob/master/specs/juno/send-data-to-ceilometer.rst

Related patch: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/72538/

Change-Id: I2368e78e39970b7a3cffe3d8cb2dd3fce5056635

commit_message:
Set no-quorum-policy using cibadmin patch

Pacemaker crmsh utility may sometimes fail
when trying to set no-quorum policy as
xml-diff becomes outdated.

This approach uses cibadmin patch option
that applies xml diff cleanly.

Change-Id: I63297d33ab20c7dd48ffa5064a981d6555c6b502
Closes-bug: #1363908

commit_message:
Use __qualname__ where appropriate

The __qualname__ attribute simplifies the determination
of an objects class name and callable name and is useful
in python 3.x to be able to use since it can correctly
identify names better than the python 2.x __name__ attribute
can.

Adds a few tests in to ensure that the usage of __qualname__
where available functions as expected.

See: http://legacy.python.org/dev/peps/pep-3155/

Fixes bug 1341441

Change-Id: Ic6942cbbc8e35d65fb3ac603ff1dfc8e20c194a3

The remaining issue is the validity of the assertions. All we are doing thus far is saying "yup there are some metrics there" but not "there are metrics before and after the upgrade". At the moment we don't have a concept of time so I'm not sure how to make the comparison. But if there is not a direct way to do this in ceilometer then I don't think this fits under the current scope of javelin2.  That being said upgrade testing to make sure data is not lost is important for ceilometer.

I think further discussion is needed here."}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2014-08-18 21:31:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 17:

(1 comment)

@Joe, thanks for the comments.

This stuff is in javelin2 because it has been described (to me) as the right tool to use, within grenade, for testing if resources survive an upgrade processes. Resources are not just compute instances or images. It also includes things like meter samples created from notifications and pollings. When javelin runs in create mode some of those notifications happen (even if ceilometer is not running). When javelin run in check mode, after the upgrade process, those samples can be checked.

This is _exactly_ my understanding of what javelin is for.

And testing resource survivability in grenade is exactly what the TC has required ceilometer to do.

Thus this patchset.

If the definition of what javeiln2 is for has changed to something other than what I've said, then that's a bummer because this is the framework for doing resource survivability that we've got and it'd be great to get this out the door.

I think we all want goodness to happen, we just need to figure out the best way."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2014-08-19 02:32:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 17:

'}, {'created': '2014-07-23 18:14:40.000000000', 'message': 'Add a check_telemetry method to javelin

Adds simple queries of the telemetry service to allow checks that meter
data effectively survives an upgrade. The checks make the perhaps
not robust assumption that there will be at least two samples (per
query) and that the first one comes from before the upgrade and the
last one comes from after the upgrade.

This can be made more robust with some awareness of time. That is:
If we know that the upgrade process will last at least N seconds
we can look for that gap in the samples to confirm that earlier
samples are substantially older than the current time or the
time on the more recent samples.

Question:
* How do we get awareness of time?

Partially implements: blueprint grenade-resource-survivability

Change-Id: Ie759d71326916d543c7b3603d8812306d093715a

before and after the upgrade with the same tests.

'}, {'created': '2014-08-10 21:35:30.000000000', 'message': 'Add a check_telemetry method to javelin

Adds simple queries of the telemetry service that check that meter
data properly survives an upgrade. The code is written so it is
possible to make different queries before and after the upgrade.

UPGRADE_GAP provides a timedelta against which it should be
possible to declare that a sample comes before or after
JAVELIN_START (the time at which the javelin command was
called). This is done in an effort to avoid ambiguity of
sample data and race conditions with notifications made
by nova and polling done by the ceilometer compute agent.
This is not yet perfect: a better solution would involve
knowing the timestamp on the data-dumpfile made during
the upgrade process and using that a selector for timestamps.
We can only use JAVELIN_START to ensure that old samples are
in fact old. It does not work for new samples as the ceilometer
compute agent can produce samples at three distinct times:

* in the previous run (before the upgrade)
* in the new run before JAVELIN_START
* in the new run after JAVELIN_START (it takes a while for the
  agent to get rolling).

The latter possibility is covered by a loop which waits up to sixty
seconds for sensible polling data during check mode.

resources.yaml is changed so that the generated servers have
different owners and images as available factors to sample.

Partially implements: blueprint grenade-resource-survivability

'}, {'created': '2014-08-18 16:03:11.000000000', 'message': 'Add a check_telemetry method to javelin

Adds simple queries of the telemetry service that check that meter
data properly survives an upgrade. The code is written so it is
possible to make different queries before and after the upgrade.

UPGRADE_GAP provides a timedelta against which it should be
possible to declare that a sample comes before or after
JAVELIN_START (the time at which the javelin command was
called). This is done in an effort to avoid ambiguity of
sample data and race conditions with notifications made
by nova and polling done by the ceilometer compute agent.
Since we can only use JAVELIN_START to ensure that old samples
are in fact old we also inspect the modified time on the ceilometer
data dump file and use that to compare new samples against it.

With these comparisons we can know that we have samples from before
and after the upgrade, still in the database.

Compute agent can produce samples at three distinct times:

* in the previous run (before the upgrade)
* in the new run before JAVELIN_START
* in the new run after JAVELIN_START (it takes a while for the
  agent to get rolling).

N.B: This currently cannot work and is expected to fail because
it relies on accessing information which grenade does not yet
provide to it.

Partially implements: blueprint grenade-resource-survivability

Change-Id: Ie759d71326916d543c7b3603d8812306d093715a

commit_message:
Add a check_telemetry method to javelin

Adds simple queries of the telemetry service that check that meter
data properly survives an upgrade.

JAVELIN_START is recorded to provide a way to confirm that the
oldest available data is from before the upgrade, thus confirming
that the data survived the upgrade.

Partially implements: blueprint grenade-resource-survivability

Change-Id: Ie759d71326916d543c7b3603d8812306d093715a

commit_message:
Migrate test_network_basic_ops to tempest clients

This patch migrates the network basic ops scenario tests
from official client to tempest clients.

manager:
Creates NeutronScenario subclass to enforce usage of neutron instead of nova
network. Overrides novanetwork helper methods from ancestor (such as secgroup
related methods). Class name is temporary since NetworkScenario is used by
non-migrated scenario. Will be changed to NetworkScenario once all network
tests have migrated

resources:
Creates DeletableResource module in services/network for resources using
the tempest clients. Copy of api/network/common. Original will be removed once
all related scenarios have migrated.
Changes __hash__ to use object's uuid instead of memory address.

network_basic_ops:
Changes references to server object to handle dict and scenarios keypair dict
to use key_name as keys instead of servers (since server is an unhashable dict)

Partially-implements: bp:tempest-client-scenarios

Change-Id: Id7341c662c0faad3ab0cb3fc1579326613ac9c68

representation anyway.

At the moment the only code-side change is get_meters of the sql-a
implementation. In that a subquery (present to duplicate the mongo
behavior) is removed and the sample table is joined. This leads to
a much simpler query plan with 3 tables instead of 5 or 6 tables,
duplicate tables or temporary tables involved. This ought to result
in much better reads when doing a meter-list, even when joining
the metadata tables.

NB: I have not yet performance tested these changes, only explored
the query plan. It is possible (but unlikely) that simple selects
using indexes will be slower than more complex queries, so we should
be sure to do real tests. The current query arrangement is one of
several options. In situations with more data one of those other
options may be better.

Nest steps (if any):

* try with lots of data, explore other options
* explore the other usual queries to see what additional simplifications
  are possible (if any)

commit_message:
WIP to rationalize SQL in alignment with new schema

This is just some exploration to see how much needs to change
to get simpler queries when using the new schema proposed
in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/111313/11

The primary insight here is that the scenario tests create
samples which are considered impossible in the "real" world.
Changing the tests (as done) allows more straightforward
queries of the resource and meter tables (and potentially
more, thus the WIP).

The mongo storage implementation works with _either_ these tests or
the unchanged tests because it only saves the most recent resource
representation anyway.

At the moment the only code-side change is get_meters of the sql-a
implementation. In that a subquery (present to duplicate the mongo
behavior) is removed and the sample table is joined. This leads to
a much simpler query plan with 3 tables instead of 5 or 6 tables,
duplicate tables or temporary tables involved. This ought to result
in much better reads when doing a meter-list, even when joining
the metadata tables.

Note that postgresql requires either many group by statements, or
a distinct(). mysql and sqlite do not.

NB: I have not yet performance tested these changes, only explored
the query plan. It is possible (but unlikely) that simple selects
using indexes will be slower than more complex queries, so we should
be sure to do real tests. The current query arrangement is one of
several options. In situations with more data one of those other
options may be better.

Next steps (if any):

* try with lots of data, explore other options
* explore event handling (other get_* methods already explored)

Change-Id: I28db654fbfe5aa9809e3024770cf7182bcecc58e

commit_message:
Convert migrate_server v3 plugin to v2.1

Changes required to have v3 plugin natively support
the v2 API.

The migrate_live action is reverted back to os-migrateLive

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: Ib3332ecfbf47ed6cad6108399083f0c26b7eebfe

commit_message:
Call policy.init() once per API request

This patch changes the policy engine behaviour and the API base
controller in order to ensure policy.init is invoked only once
for each API request.
This will avoid issues arising from policy file updates during
API processing and speed up response generation for list operations,
by about 5%.

This patch also removes an obsolete TODO comment.

Change-Id: I108ebd26fccdea19cb00959f70d87c3bc1587df9
Closes-Bug: 1302611

commit_message:
console: add typed console objects

Adds typed console objects used by virt driver API to
return information about consoles.

Also updates virt drivers to use them.

Closes-Bug: #1361611
Change-Id: I8f6a857b88659ee30b4aa1a25ac52d7e01156a68

commit_message:
Transfer class LazyPluggable from nova to oslo.utils

Need to transfer code of class LazyPluggable to oslo.utils
because this code copied in different projects. Global
attribute CONF is now transmitted in __init__ function.
Also was written tests for this class.

Change-Id: I1c828b643408d9a458f2facdf7e07b4ca7dfb64a

Hi James,

This is how it was implemented initially. Unfortunately, conditional inclusion of keystone-ldap element into run list involved too many logical changes in tripleo-incubator. You may find some details in https://review.openstack.org/106175. Given that installation of python-ldap module is harmless, it was considered as good lightweight alternative to implementing additional LDAP-related logic in tripleo-incubator.'}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2014-08-15 17:24:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: Code-Review+2

[{'created': '2014-07-10 21:01:42.000000000', 'message': 'CONSER-10489 Keystone/LDAP integration

Provides keystone-ldap element which does the following:

1. Installs python-ldap module into Keystone virtual environment

2. Creates /etc/keystone/ldap.crt file which contans CA certificates
needed to connect to LDAP server. File content is expected to be
passed in as "keystone_ldap_cacertfile" field of $OVERCLOUD_EXTRA_CONFIG
variable.

Configuration settings related to LDAP are supposed to be set via
passthrough feature (i.e. injected into /etc/keystone/keystone.conf file
by setting "keystone" field of $OVERCLOUD_EXTRA_CONFIG env variable).

commit_message:
Keystone/LDAP integration

Installs python-ldap and ldappool modules into Keystone virtual environment.

Configuration settings related to LDAP are supposed to be set via
passthrough feature (i.e. injected into /etc/keystone/keystone.conf file
by setting "keystone" field of $OVERCLOUD_EXTRA_CONFIG env variable).

Change-Id: Ifcd403cff3a75a9926d2a4ee7d041ef9f3171ffb

commit_message:
Make m-shr more stable on start up

When service m-shr is restarted it tries to ensure shares and its rules.
If some error appears whole service fails to start up.
Lets catch all exceptions, log them and let service start anyway.

Closes-Bug: #1351195
Change-Id: I979932b5a80ff2e1494c361887a1c1dea63daeb5

commit_message:
Fix scheduled share creation with generic driver

Generic driver uses separate module service_instance for handling of Nova VMs.
If service m-shr starts and there are existing scheduled shares for creation,
then concurrent issue appears between method 'do_setup', that is called once
on start of service and 'ensure_server', that uses stuff from do_setup.

Main error is in following:
- "Returning exception 'GenericShareDriver' object has no attribute
  'service_instance_manager' to caller"

Changes:
- moved definition of attr 'service_instance_manager' to __init__ method.
- removed attrs '_helpers' and 'share_networks_servers' from
  ServiceInstanceManager as they are redundant.
- updated unittests according to changes.
- used direct import of 'constants' submodule for neutron api,
  to be able to access it on driver init step.
- replaced generic driver with common driver interface for inheritance
  by fake driver for unittests.

Change-Id: I0fe7f097dc03eade5e0d4dfdbda0eb49588f4dde
Closes-Bug: #1362985
Related-Bug: #1330391

commit_message:
Use oslo.serialization

Use jsonutils from lib oslo.serialization instead of
common code.
Module jsonutils from common code in nova can't be removed right
now due to the usage in other common modules. This should
be done after switching oslo code to use serialization library.

Also added hacking check for using jsonutils from oslo.serialization
library

Change-Id: I0d97f9faff081b572075a3b7aca042f9aeb948ae

commit_message:
On ubuntu break app logs into their own files

Currently on ubuntu we are sending all app logs to syslog which munges
them all together into /var/log/syslog. This makes debugging a somewhat
painful experience.

Change-Id: I89f9ddc168f08b90cece7cf5af2e032b2c4f5371

commit_message:
Initial translation setup

To start translation, we need to initially import the
translation file - and place it at the proper place so that
the usual CI scripts can handle it.

The proper place is for all python projects
$PROJECT/locale/$PROJECT.pot - see setup.cfg.

Further imports of the pot files and its translations
will be done by the OpenStack Proposal bot in a daily job.

Change-Id: Ic39a4cfe40ccdff4d6a299189fcfc0e6a9ec9c61

Awesome, was wondering if this was going to happen.

In the other patchset there's been some discussion about the risks associated with duplicated or missing data when group membership changes. Presumably those risks are somewhat increased in the alarming context. Does it matter?"}, {'account_id': 8052, 'date': '2014-08-19 11:23:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

If an alarm is evaluated twice, it doesn't matter, since the notification has already gone out and the state of the alarm probably won't change (if it does, well, then we just have more up-to-date info!).

Same as in central agent though, if we add another evaluator to the group, the evaluation of certain alarms can get delayed by up to one evaluation interval, since they get placed on a different evaluator."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-19 11:30:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

(2 comments)

Thanks for this Nejc, a couple of quick thoughts inline on an initial scan through the patch.

Maintaining an even cadence of evaluation for each alarm is another strong reason why the consistent hash ring approach would be preferred to the initial simple hashing used in the central agent patch.

So in the normal course of events, with a stable set of evaluators running on non-synchronized evaluation intervals, the stickiness of the alarm assignments will ensure that even cadence.

However it would be useful I think to explicitly state the worst case scenario in terms of the disruption to the evaluation cadence for re-assigned alarms when a new agent joins or an existing agent leaves.

Cheers,
Eoghan'}, {'account_id': 8052, 'date': '2014-08-29 10:25:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

commit_message:
Switch partitioned alarm evaluation to a hash-based approach

Short version: make use of the new distributed workload partitioning
utilities in Ceilometer to simplify the alarm evaluation
partitioning. Code is intentionally non-consolidated to enable
easy deletion of 'singleton' and 'partitioned' services in the Kilo
cycle.

Longer version:
The assignment of alarms to individual partitioned alarm evaluators
now follows the same pattern as the division of resources between
scaled-out central agents.

The evaluators each join a tooz group and emit a periodic heartbeat
to tooz. Tooz provides distributed group membership information.

Thus the set of evaluators share minimal knowledge, but this is
sufficient to guide a hash-based approach to determining whether
an individual alarm UUID falls under the responsibility of an
individual evaluator.

The current RPC-fanout-based presence reporting and the master/slave
division of responsibilities can be dropped in the next cycle.
Also the rebalancing logic when a certain threshold of alarm
deletion is crossed will no longer be required.

DocImpact
Change-Id: Ica8dae569f9ff1c2f8fe58be6ae2def66be0da54
Implements: blueprint hash-based-alarm-partitioning

commit_message:
Fix execution state ERROR if task_spec has on-finish

 * We shouldn't set execution state in ERROR if
   task has on-error or on-finish property
 * Fix wait_success method in functional tests

Change-Id: I48e452d5974dd854eb14dcaf23d13e81107a03dc

commit_message:
Remove docutils-pin

This was added to work around bug 1091333.  A new sphinx has been
released and so this is no longer necessary.

The docutils-pin has been removed from all projects listed
in projects.txt.
The patches removing the pin have used the IDs
I99ae8f8be1aa19508af05f2f72dea89537478f2f and
I6ea61a3cc441dd1ca2ced7e2fd837a55b917f76d .

There are a some projects not listed in projects.txt that still have the
docutils-pin, patches for these are under review.

Change-Id: Ic3208d181c0bdb4521ee2b062d8414ef7ac33230
Co-Authored-By: James E. Blair <jeblair@hp.com>

commit_message:
ML2: Make get_device_details report mac address as well

This will be used by ofagent to route packets to local VMs.

Partially-implements: blueprint ofagent-merge-bridges

commit_message:
Remove unneeded device_owner field from l2pop tuple

The DVR development added this device_owner to the middle of this
tuple during early development because it was thought to be needed.
Over the course of development, it was found to be unnecessary and
much of the code that read it from this value was removed or
obsoleted.  That job went unfinished and so this commit completes it.
This essentially restores the code to what it was before and fixes the
regression that was caused.

Change-Id: Ia901f925883b53e9880dd25688e16e0ffe402bf4
Partial-bug: #1352801

commit_message:
Remove install guide dashboard session section

After another bug report about configuring dashboard sessions
using the installation guide, I decided to update the Icehouse
version to reference the Cloud Administrator Guide similar to the
Juno version.

Change-Id: I0d20720e527504b5c9a30d113e5591b486d9cb5b
Closes-Bug: #1354896

commit_message:
Use openstack.common.lockutils module for locks in tox functional tests.

Tox test has been switched to use openstack.common.lockutils module
for interprocess locks. However neutron tox functional tests was
left behind probably because locking is not required by the existing
functional test cases. This change makes neutron tox functional tests
adopt openstack.common.lockutils for locking.

Closes-Bug: 1332380
Change-Id: I4d6076e5f7586a11ea5381f18774d4bab57b0081

commit_message:
Proper validation for inserting firewall rule

Say rule r2 is associated with policy p2. If user tries to insert rule r1
into a policy p1 before/after r2, error should be thrown saying that rule
r2 is not associated with policy p1.

Change-Id: Ifa415acc9533b7a323f966ee42d476460e68c9d3
Closes-bug: 1330898

commit_message:
Adding new methods to DB API v2 (load_xxx and create_or_update_xxx)

* Methods load_xxx() which can return None unlike get_xxx()
* Methods create_or_update_xxx()
* Unit tests for new methods
* Refactoring DB tests

(1 comment)

Hi Stuart,

we have found out that some of the tests were failing because 'greenthreads' are not released back to the eventlet green pool (client socket connection is not closed) due to which the glance api service doesn't shutdown gracefully.

To address this issue, we have separated out the request call in _get_response_from_http_request() method, so that after the execution of that method the object should be garbage collected automatically."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-27 14:21:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Just some further thoughts...

If I start up the glance api (with this patch), eg with:

$.tox/py27/bin/python -m glance.cmd.api --config-file /etc/glance/glance-api.conf

Then run the following client script to connect:

 import httplib2
 import time

 path = 'http://%s:%d' % ('127.0.0.1', 9292)
 http = httplib2.Http()
 response, content = http.request(path, 'GET')

 time.sleep(1000000)

And then do

$ kill -HUP <parent_process_id>

The server waits indefinitely:

 2014-08-29 13:58:46.629 20381 INFO glance.openstack.common.service [-] Caught SIGHUP, stopping children
 2014-08-29 13:58:46.629 20381 INFO glance.openstack.common.service [-] Waiting on 1 children to exit
 2014-08-29 13:58:46.629 20389 INFO glance.openstack.common.service [-] Child caught SIGTERM, exiting
 2014-08-29 13:58:46.630 20389 INFO glance.wsgi.server [-] Stopping WSGI server.

It's only when I kill the client script that the server exits:

 2014-08-29 13:59:34.691 20389 INFO glance.wsgi.server [-] WSGI server has stopped.
 2014-08-29 13:59:34.693 20381 INFO glance.openstack.common.service [-] Child 20389 exited with status 1

We probably need to think about the behaviour we want here. Does it really make sense for a single open
client connection to prevent the server restarting indefinitely?

I tried the above with cinder and the server seemed to exit straight away.

For comparison this is what swift does:

 http://docs.openstack.org/developer/swift/admin_guide.html#swift-orphans"}, {'account_id': 1011, 'date': '2014-08-29 18:28:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Stuart:
You are right, because in cinder it doesn't wait until all requests are processed completely. If you call _server.wait after _server.kill is called , then it raises GreenletExit exception, it doesn't wait until the requests in hand are processed completely.

The intention of this patch is to process all requests that are in hand (it won't accepts new requests) before restarting it again to give nice experience to the users. Take an example of user downloading or uploading big image and in between administrator restarts the service. It might be frustrating for the user to repeat the same action again."}, {'account_id': 2835, 'date': '2014-09-02 19:39:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review-1

Duplicate of: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/117988/'}, {'account_id': 1011, 'date': '2014-09-02 22:08:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

commit_message:
Made provision for glance service to use Launcher

After sending SIGHUP signal to glance-service parent process,
it will call SIGHUP callback handler and then throws OSError.
The OSError is thrown because os.wait system call was
interrupted due to SIGHUP callback handler. As a result of
this parent process closes the server socket.
All child processes also gets terminated without completing
existing api requests because the server socket is already
closed and the service doesn't restart.

Added service module, launcher and common service module with
its dependencies from oslo-incubator in glance service.

After modifying the implemenatation, glance-service is able to
restart on sending SIGHUP signal to parent process and also
completing existing api requests.

Made provision to pass default hub to eventlet.hubs.use_hub()
in oslo-incubator common service framework. Defined new configuration
parameter 'eventlet_hub' with default value as 'poll' in glance.cmd.api
and glance.cmd.registry  and leveraged same to service framework of
oslo-incubator.

Change-Id: I8fe08d2ee3fb2f29e7cffe04514866f8e9bb1933
blueprint:use-common-service-framework

commit_message:
Fix "mutable" object as default value

This patch fix the coding issue where "mutable" objects like list, dict
are being used as default value of param.

Current functions with mutable object as default value can create issues
if they will be called in more random order.
For example - first call with non default value and then with default
value. In this case original default will be overridden by the first
function call (as mutable object keep their state among function calls).

This commit also add the hacking check for the same and its
corresponding test.

Closes-Bug: #1330322

Change-Id: I251b316ef6d37f4b95c5e8d73a20a39005c22870

commit_message:
Increase cinder volumes hard disk size

Increases cinder volumes hard disk size to 4GB. 2GB was not sufficient
for creating multiple volumes at once.

Change-Id: Iae9a8a4f71a297f0bbf017b80011cb9cc6d517cb

commit_message:
Updates cinder to support additional image types

Only raw images can be converted to bootable volumes by cinder. For
converting additional image types, cinder needs 'qemu-img' which is
installed via 'qemu-utils' package. This patch adds the required
package to the cinder controller node.

Change-Id: I296649827165989381ac7ce623e7babd62f7063a

[{'created': '2014-05-22 14:46:04.000000000', 'message': 'MLNX Agent: ensure removed devices get treated on resyncs

Closes-Bug: #1287648

Signed-off-by: Roey Chen <roeyc@mellanox.com>
'}, {'created': '2014-06-01 14:54:22.000000000', 'message': "MLNX Agent: ensure removed ports get treated on resyncs

This patch ensures that removed ports will be cleaned up properly if exception
occurs in the daemon_loop.
It does the same for the mlnx-agent as was done for the lb-agent in
Ieada34ad315c0c29aa8462ebf041a448fde007b8.

Refactoring the daemon_loop and scan_ports in a way that -
If there's an exception, the ports that were flagged for cleaning will
be retreated in the following iteration,
unlike previous exception handling, where only existing ports
were treated in the following iteration.

Closes-Bug: #1287648
Change-Id: I3af505773aa3fdc0d17f2079ac1f1b3e93bb64a3
Signed-off-by: Roey Chen <roeyc@mellanox.com>

commit_message:
MLNX Agent: ensure removed ports get treated on resyncs

This patch ensures that removed ports will be cleaned up properly if exception
occurs in the daemon_loop.
It does the same for the mlnx-agent as was done for the lb-agent in
Ieada34ad315c0c29aa8462ebf041a448fde007b8.

Refactoring the daemon_loop and scan_ports in a way that -
If there's an exception, the ports that were flagged for cleaning will
be retreated in the following iteration,
unlike previous exception handling, where only existing ports
were treated in the following iteration.

Closes-Bug: 1287648
Change-Id: I3af505773aa3fdc0d17f2079ac1f1b3e93bb64a3
Signed-off-by: Roey Chen <roeyc@mellanox.com>

'}, {'created': '2014-06-01 13:37:06.000000000', 'message': 'MLNX Agent: Process port_update notifications in the main agent loop

This patch changes the way mlnx agent process port_update notifications.
It does the same for the mlnx agent as was done for the ovs-agent in
I219c6bdf63b0b5e945b655677f9e28fa591f03cd.
Processing a port_update notification directly in the RPC
call may cause competition with the main RPC loop.
To prevent this problem, the actual process of ports updates is done
in the main RPC loop, whereas the RPC call merely adds the updated
port MAC address to a set of updated ports.
port_update notifications received within a single main loop iteration
will be coalesced and processed only once.

Closes-Bug: 1279655
Change-Id: I63dda60cb3cf171e5e9111a1ecf95e45e1d86362
Signed-off-by: Roey Chen <roeyc@mellanox.com>

commit_message:
MLNX Agent: Process port_update notifications in the main agent loop

This patch changes the way mlnx agent process port_update notifications.
It does the same for the mlnx agent as was done for the ovs-agent in
I219c6bdf63b0b5e945b655677f9e28fa591f03cd.
Processing a port_update notification directly in the RPC
call may cause competition with the main RPC loop.
To prevent this problem, the actual process of ports updates is done
in the main RPC loop, whereas the RPC call merely adds the updated
port MAC address to a set of updated ports.
port_update notifications received within a single main loop iteration
will be coalesced and processed only once.

Closes-Bug: 1279655
Change-Id: I63dda60cb3cf171e5e9111a1ecf95e45e1d86362
Signed-off-by: Roey Chen <roeyc@mellanox.com>

I'm OK with this breakout. I think over time, instead of making these mixins, it would be better to make them instead fixture objects (i.e. inherit from fixtures.Fixture) and then have the base class that tests any plugin-level API instantiate the fixture with the base test case class inheriting from testtools.TestWithFixtures. That would enable an encapsulation technique instead of a mixin technique and allow the subclassing to be a little less verbose (less mixins) :)"}, {'account_id': 2035, 'date': '2014-03-25 17:32:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Refactor plugin setup helpers out of test.base

Helper methods for plugin and notification setup were previously
defined on neutron.tests.base.BaseTestCase.  The imports required to
support these helpers were preventing the api tests from consuming
tempest due to configuration conflicts that resulted between neutron
and tempest.  This change moves the helpers to a new module in
tests/unit so that BaseTestCase can be safely used across all types of
tests.

Partially-Implements: blueprint retargetable-functional-testing

Change-Id: I44251db399cd73390a9d1931a7f253662002ba10

commit_message:
InstanceNUMAToplogy object create remove uuid param

We can get this from the object attribute so no need to pass it in
explicitly.

We do not need to bump the version of the object as there is no code
calling it as of yet, so we do not have to support the broken method
interface until the next major version bump.

Change-Id: I96e1d958e907272d94d7ca6481592b79ea6b6397
Blueprint: virt-driver-numa-placement

Thanks for this xuhaiwei

I'd like to note that this breaks backwards compatibility for any existing devs who are used to running the scripts from a particular location and have the password files in that location. That's not neccessarily a bad thing - I think we need to break that at some point, and maybe doing it near the start of the Juno cycle is a sensible place. My preference would be to keep this in place for at least another cycle, but I'm not sure if that's because I'm being sensible or if it's because I wrote some of the code being removed. I'll leave that call for others to make.

However, even if it's going to be removed, the proposed change leaves an if/else block where both code paths are identical - I'd prefer to see the if/else structure removed and just run the code, since it's going to be the same code that gets executed either way"}, {'account_id': 6348, 'date': '2014-06-23 09:16:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I think the change is good and it is also very nice that the script can append new passwords without changing what is in the file already.

It is so nice, that I think this should be exposed as an actual feature because users may want to customize some passwords.

I would make the file path customizable, default to $TRIPLEO_ROOT and keep the change.'}, {'account_id': 8449, 'date': '2014-06-24 07:48:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1

(1 comment)

@Ben - I hadn't realised this was the case. I think it is a bit confusing and as pointed out by Xu it isn't clear that this feature exists.

Some inline suggestion that will retain this behaviour, however I'm with Guilio, we should really make this explicit by allowing user to set a parameter for the location of the password file, if that is their intent."}, {'account_id': 9453, 'date': '2014-06-25 00:39:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

I don't think we need to worry about anyone coming fresh to tripleo at this point - from the first time they generate passwords, the passwords will always be in $TRIPLEO_ROOT, they'll never have multiple password files created - unless they have multipleo $TRIPLEO_ROOTs, in which case they'd probably expect to see a different set of passwords in each.

It sounds as though the people who may get confused are people who ran devtest*.sh prior to March, as they would have one or more (I personally had several) sets of password files.

If our goal is to alert these people to potential confusion, maybe changing the message printed out when password files are found in . would suffice? Currently it does say that we're "Re-using existing passwords", but that doesn't make it clear that "This is deprecated, you should move these files to $TRIPLEO_ROOT". Perhaps a more explicit warning along those lines would help?'}, {'account_id': 6348, 'date': '2014-06-25 02:27:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

@James Polley

Since the original source is always saving passwords at $TRIPLEO_ROOT, there is no need to do the IF clause. The original source is same with this fix. But I think setup-overcloud-passwords really confuses people, because it doesn't overwrite passwords but just add new ones. I think we should add some comments about it.

Giulio and Marios want to make it customized, what do you think?"}, {'account_id': 9453, 'date': '2014-06-25 04:52:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

I'm happy with Marios'/Giulo's suggestion as well"}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2014-06-25 16:41:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Comments explaining why the if is there should clear up any developer confusion as to what is going on, so I'd be fine with that.

Regarding making it configurable, I have no strong opinion.  I wasn't the one who used this functionality in the first place, so I'm not sure whether that would address the needs of the people who did or not."}, {'account_id': 8449, 'date': '2014-06-26 06:53:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Xu, I can't speak for lifeless but I oppose new env vars for two main reasons. One, they're a largely undocumented interface. At least with command line options there's the --help (although in this case I don't think an option is needed either).

Two, it's unclear how they propagate. If you're not careful about your use of exports and subshells, it's easy for a variable to be set or unset inappropriately. This can cause subtle bugs.

If you want to debate this policy please take it to the mailing list, you need to convince lifeless not me :)"}, {'account_id': 10035, 'date': '2014-07-28 17:36:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

I spoke to xu haiwei about this change a few days ago and agreed to have a stab at switching from using environment variables to command-line flags, in line with the comments above. The best way i could see to do this was to store the password file location in $TE_DATAFILE. I wanted to check if this was a sensible idea so I jumped into #tripleo

This led to some discussion in-channel where we (bnemec, lifeless, myself) tried to step back, look at what problem we're trying to solve, and look for a good way to solve it.

We think, if our understanding is correct, that we're trying to do a few different things here:

1) The current logic (look in $CWD for passwords first, then look in $TRIPLEO_ROOT) is confusing, especially for someone reading the code - we think it's not particularly clear what's happening or why
2) We (who were discussing it at the time) think that we (the broader TripleO team) want to make sure that users can drive multiple stacks - eg, running multiple overclouds out of one undercloud - and have different credentials for each. We (who were discussing it at the time) don't actually know of anyone who does this, so we're only speculating that this something that some people *might* find useful - if we could talk to someone who needs this functionality, it would help us make sure we're doing something useful for them
3) Looking to the future, these passwords should eventually be stored in Barbican or something similar. In the shorter term, it would probably be a good idea to move the passwords into $TE_DATAFILE. However, the work required to do that today is non-trivial as we'd need to find all the places the passwords are currently used and change the way the password is looked up.

Looking at the history of this change, it seems that it was originally trying to solve (1) by making the logic for finding passwords simpler and cleaner. However, that broke (2); in trying to make (2) work again, this change got made more complex, even though we haven't found anyone who actually relies on this functionality working. We seem to have a solution (put the filenames into $TE_DATAFILE) which achieves (1) and preserves the ability to do (2) - but any work we do on it will have to be tweaked again (probably soon) when we work on (3)

So, assuming I've understood the motivations of this change correctly, here's what I plan to do:

1) Wait for people to tell me I've misunderstood the intent of this change (this is a non-blocking step, other steps will proceed in parallel with waiting)
2) Raise https://bugs.launchpad.net/tripleo/+bug/1358600 about getting a solution for (3) (which will enable (2) and help with (1) )
3) Raise a new CR (I12d013196b0c533a0550167b9b8209e590e3bd49) which attempts to add some docs into the scripts to clarify the existing logic

I'll copy this message onto the mailing list as well - if we've misunderstood what's needed here, or these plans don't meet your needs, please follow up there with some more details."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2014-08-22 06:04:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: Code-Review-1

I think this really needs to keep looking in cwd. There's no reason to stop that, and its incompatible to change it."}, {'account_id': 6348, 'date': '2014-09-03 03:47:05.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]
