commit_message:
Make location of saved credentials files customizable

Save undercloud/overcloud-passwords in $TRIPLEO_ROOT by default.
User can also specify the path by changing the parameters in
devtest_variables.

Change-Id: Ifca80a1d9bc9aff61aee8c70e67f59451d1bb55b

Setup the tcp chardevice in the libvirt driver based on the
configuration (if the serial consoles are enabled) and disable the
logging to a file since we have an interactive console.
The patch also contains the port allocator module that tests for
free tcp ports and assigns them to the serial tcp chardevice.

Author: Ian Wells
Co-autherd by: Vladan Popovic, Sushma Korati

partialy implements blueprint serial-ports

commit_message:
virt: setup TCP chardevice in libvirt driver

Setup the tcp chardevice in the libvirt driver based on the
configuration (if the serial consoles are enabled) and disable the
logging to a file since we have an interactive console.

A new image property is introduced: hw_serial_port_count
A new flavor extra spec is introduced: hw:serial_port_count

Co-Authored-By: Vladan Popovic <vpopovic@redhat.com>
Co-Authored-By: Ian Wells <iawells@cisco.com>
Co-Authored-By: Sushma Korati <sushma_korati@persistent.co.in>

DocImpact
Partial-Implements: blueprint serial-ports
Change-Id: Ic6d24e27d61f600a90ed8fccb525d8b82725903e

commit_message:
Change v3 version API to v2.1

This patch changes v3 version API to v2.1 and makes v2 unit tests
share between v2 and v2.1.
v2.1 API does not support XML format. Unit tests related to XML
don't work against v2.1.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I7abadb0c9082b9e90a98938967f0e27d1a2fa766

subject: Use v2.1 URLs instead of v3 ones in API unit tests

commit_message:
Use v2.1 URLs instead of v3 ones in API unit tests

Now v2.1 API unit tests use fake.wsgi_app_v3() and they specify v3 URLs.
This patch adds wsgi_app_v21() for using v2 URLs in v2.1 API tests and
changes URLs in unit tests.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I5cdd7dd1d435ab0e4e093168f01e96f8dac52e8c

commit_message:
Fix string concatenation

Translated strings should not be added with normal strings. This makes
translations harder and will be an error with oslo.i18n.

Change-Id: I1f0bdd022ff155ed85e98f27f21ec9eed870aa1c

commit_message:
Add API schema for v2.1 "create a server" API

By defining the API schema, it is possible to separate the validation
code from the API method. The API method can be more simple.
In addition, a response of API validation error can be consistent for
the whole Nova API.

Partially implements blueprint v3-api-schema

Change-Id: Ic17d2227909c9180ca86c9d578dad4c73ec57dfc

commit_message:
Expose blacklisting scaled items via merge.py.

I don't like putting these in as environment variables, but I
suspect the consistency with the matching scale variables outweighs
the rationalise-ui needs in the short term.

Change-Id: Ib11c9ab767a7632717cb0fb277dbbba7c98bd4ee

commit_message:
Adding firewall logging for instances.

Adding a new configuration switch that would allow, if set to true,
to log DROPped packet aimed at any instances by setting
the following boolean: log_dropped_traffic.

Change-Id: Id74e15788a14b08934c1ec2a19a29a492ccb970c

commit_message:
Convert multiple-create v3 plugin to v2.1

Changes required to have the multiple create v3 plugin natively
support the v2.1 API. The following Server creation parameters
are reverted:

os-multiple-create:min_count -> min_count
os-multiple-create:max_count -> max_count
os-multiple-create:return_reservation_id -> return_reservation_id

Removes min_count parameter for a test which should never have
been included but due to a gap in input validation was ignored.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: Ie435c357958066e9fde40eab54826261ee9d4226

[{'created': '2014-09-02 16:14:18.000000000', 'message': 'Fix Redis message controller getting stuck in while loop

The Redis driver was getting stuck in a loop while trying to create
a claim. The root cause turned out to be some logic that was trying
to skip past all the claimed messages at the head of the queue, but
did not advance the offset if no unclaimed messages were found,
leading to a neverending loop.

Change-Id: I8d2e1a7820c30e92a63ed938013f0e69dff83b2f
Partially-Implements: blueprint redis-storage-driver
'}]
commit_message:
Fix Redis message controller getting stuck in while loop

The Redis driver was getting stuck in a loop while trying to create
a claim. The root cause turned out to be some logic that was trying
to skip past all the claimed messages at the head of the queue, but
did not advance the offset if no unclaimed messages were found,
leading to a neverending loop.

Change-Id: I8d2e1a7820c30e92a63ed938013f0e69dff83b2f
Partially-Implements: blueprint redis-storage-driver

I have general design concerns about this patch:
1) Currently we only use agent for haproxy and process-on-host. Looking at the code I see that the patch is no-op for this case.

2) I don't think we're going to use agents for accessing devices the same we we do for processes, that's why we will not need pool-agent binding for such case, so rescheduling such balancers also seems to be unneeded.

3) Migrating processes is more complex, but might be more beneficial."}, {'account_id': 7317, 'date': '2013-12-23 05:55:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12: (1 inline comment)

However the initial idea was raised by Stephen Gran who writes agent based lbaas driver and was concerned about HA of agents. commit_message:
LBaaS: agent monitoring and instance rescheduling

For those lbaas drivers that manage physical loadbalancer devices
rather than processes (like HAProxy) it doesn't matter which exact agent
will perform actual managing. So in case one agent fails such
loadbalancer instances may be simply rescheduled to another agent.

Implements blueprint lbaas-ha-agent

Change-Id: I87d5f608b74ab4f1875b1a44108ba817daeb828a

commit_message:
Fix Permissions on Postgresql Elements

permissions need to be 0755 to be discoverable by the
diskimage-builder, otherwise they're skipped outright.

Change-Id: I3ba357559d3f7f9f1fdad830bab47fd805d50c7f
Closes-Bug: #1364679

commit_message:
Make a whole host of modules hacking 0.9.2 compliant

Global requirements has updating the version of hacking to a minimum of
0.9.2 and it has brought a whole slew of changes. This CR is to tackle a
bunch of small hacking violations.

Change-Id: Iae1d0f40d2a13bc31cf4e688bda85c0cfd36847b

commit_message:
Make Client-ID a required header

It was decided to make Client-ID a required header. This patch adds a
new `before hook` that enforces this new rule.

Partially-Implements blueprint: api-v1.1-header-changes

Change-Id: I7b20d56812a0dff4f8ed3e6da75b62ef7c0f307e

commit_message:
Add --exclude-dirs option

In some situations it may be desirable to rely on file discovery but
exclude files within some subdirectories (such as .tox/).

Change-Id: Ibe989d0c96e7827631201d88f024e3e3414254cf

commit_message:
Adds nova-idmapshift cli utility

nova-idmapshift will be used by the libvirt-lxc driver to
correctly shift ownership of instance rootfs for use with
user namespaces.

Partially implements: bp libvirt-lxc-user-namespaces

Change-Id: I9aee622cca4578149201f02d02231a7bd0cbe912

commit_message:
Windows Server image creation

This patch prepends a guide for building Windows images for KVM OpenStack
to the guide and retains the previous notes at the bottom of the doc.

Change-Id: I029a428055dab59ec0a09b12933d38cd4d209bc1

commit_message:
Fix setup.cfg so setup could succeed

Setup.cfg refers to one of the cisco config files which are missing
in the repository. Remove missing file from setup.cfg

Change-Id: I7e2b582437ba708c2e983bf9fb3d89c80dbafb78
Closes-Bug: #1364048

[{'created': '2014-08-02 04:16:45.000000000', 'message': "Glance Metadata Definitions Catalog

Implements: blueprint metadata-schema-catalog

A common API hosted by the Glance service for vendors, admins,
services, and users to meaningfully define available key / value
pair and tag metadata. The intent is to enable better metadata
collaboration across artifacts, services, and projects for
OpenStack users.
This is about the definition of the available metadata that can
be used on different types of resources (images, artifacts,
volumes, flavors, aggregates, etc). A definition includes the
properties type, its key, it's description, and it's constraints.
This catalogue will not store the values for specific instance
properties.

WORK IN PROGRESS

Currently committed:
 - DB migrate repo version script for metadef tables
 - DB CRUD: namespaces, objects, tags, properties, resource_types.
 - DB functional tests: namespaces(CRUD)
 - In progress: namespaces query pagination

Change-Id: I01cc63df3d3abe383c94cfb54598868b4bb729bb

"}, {'created': '2014-08-06 03:40:40.000000000', 'message': "Glance Metadata Definitions Catalog - DB

Implements: blueprint metadata-schema-catalog

A common API hosted by the Glance service for vendors, admins,
services, and users to meaningfully define available key / value
pair and tag metadata. The intent is to enable better metadata
collaboration across artifacts, services, and projects for
OpenStack users.
This is about the definition of the available metadata that can
be used on different types of resources (images, artifacts,
volumes, flavors, aggregates, etc). A definition includes the
properties type, its key, it's description, and it's constraints.
This catalogue will not store the values for specific instance
properties.

WORK IN PROGRESS

Currently committed:
 - DB migrate repo version script for metadef tables
 - DB CRUD: namespaces, objects, tags, properties, resource_types.
 - DB functional tests: namespaces(CRUD)
 - In progress: namespaces query pagination

commit_message:
Glance Metadata Definitions Catalog - DB

Implements: blueprint metadata-schema-catalog

A common API hosted by the Glance service for vendors, admins,
services, and users to meaningfully define available key / value
pair and tag metadata. The intent is to enable better metadata
collaboration across artifacts, services, and projects for
OpenStack users.

This is about the definition of the available metadata that can
be used on different types of resources (images, artifacts,
volumes, flavors, aggregates, etc). A definition includes the
properties type, its key, it's description, and it's constraints.
This catalogue will not store the values for specific instance
properties.

a wrapper class that wraps a green thread for async network
allocation. Accessing network_info forces a wait on the wrapped
thread (if the network allocation has not completed), which can lead
to a deadlock as follows:

Thread 1 (periodic task in Nova) has grabbed the COMPUTE_RESOURCE_SEMAPHORE
in update_available_resource, and is waiting for the IO thread lock in the
logging handle routine

Thread 2 (in the ironic driver) has grabbed the IO thread lock in the logging

_str_ can be called to finish formatting the log message

Thread 3 (which is doing the async network object allocation) wants to call
update_usage in the resource tracker, but that needs the
COMPUTE_RESOURCE_SEMAPHORE which is held by the first thread

The problem is similar to https://review.openstack.org/#/c/71409
and the fix is simply to covert network info to a string before the call
to LOG()

commit_message:
Avoid deadlock when logging network_info

_plug_vifs() and _unplug_vifs() in driver.py both log network_info

However network_info is not a simple structure, its a reference to
a wrapper class that wraps a green thread for async network
allocation. Accessing network_info forces a wait on the wrapped
thread (if the network allocation has not completed), which can lead
to a deadlock as follows:

Thread 1 (periodic task in Nova) has grabbed the COMPUTE_RESOURCE_SEMAPHORE
in update_available_resource, and is waiting for the IO thread lock in the
logging handle routine

Thread 2 (in the ironic driver) has grabbed the IO thread lock in the logging
handle routine and is waiting for the async network object to be ready so
_str_ can be called to finish formatting the log message

Thread 3 (which is doing the async network object allocation) wants to call
update_usage in the resource tracker, but that needs the
COMPUTE_RESOURCE_SEMAPHORE which is held by the first thread

The problem is similar to https://review.openstack.org/#/c/71409
and the fix is simply to covert network info to a string before the call
to LOG()

Closes-Bug: 1364059
Co-authored-by: Michey Mehta michey.mehta@hp.com

Change-Id: I3b750ac386588d9235ff10a972b3ab1d8f45cf38

This patch adds an xstatic-packaged font awesome icon font to Horizon.
We need it, because the font icons included in Bootstrap 3 are non-free
and are likely to be excluded from some distributions. It also has a much
richer set of icons to choose from.

Change-Id: I725e0d77d230c16c01971f9af0dc02eb5662154d

commit_message:
Add Font Awesome icons

This patch adds an xstatic-packaged font awesome icon font to Horizon.
We need it, because the font icons included in Bootstrap 3 are non-free
and are likely to be excluded from some distributions. It also has a much
richer set of icons to choose from.

Change-Id: I725e0d77d230c16c01971f9af0dc02eb5662154d
Partial-implements: blueprint bp/font-icons

commit_message:
Change v3 availability-zone API to v2.1

This patch changes v3 availability-zone API to v2.1 and makes v2
unit tests share between v2 and v2.1.

The differences between v2 and v3 are described on the wiki page
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/NovaAPIv2tov3.

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: Ifbd152e431d182a5ccabac7fcc84fcc8a2fc6e5a

commit_message:
Bypass vCenter when uploading to datastores

The current implementation requires all the bits to go through
vCenter when uploading an image to the datastore: this is highly
inefficient, since it adds load to vCenter and makes the transfer
much slower.

This patch gives an alternative which consists in bypassing vCenter
by acquiring a ticket to directly http PUT to the ESX host.
If somehow it is not possible to get the ticket (for example if
vCenter version is less than 5.5), we fallback to the previous
implementation.

This code is used by Glance and Nova.

Change-Id: I3cab23736ee5da99917a6a9b80ad5bc3754b5216

commit_message:
Zaqar configuration reference docs

This change adds the basic configuration reference
in the user guide.

It includes the document structure outline according
the OpenStack configuration reference standard and
a list of configuration options present in zaqar.conf
with a description of default values and value types.

Configuration option tables has been generated using
the autogenerate_config_docs tool in openstack-doc-tools
repo. Needed files to easier update this tables in the
near future are located in the autogen folder.

blueprint document-config-options

Change-Id: I17884400f711f6d2723b0774c20e7df4ffb0e812

commit_message:
Fix missing trailing commas for modal dialogs

Trailing commas were accidentally removed from the 'classes' attribute
of the table actions for the Create Property and the Create Volume Type
Extra Spec dialogs. This caused the dialogs to lose their modality.

This submit fixes the problem on the two dialogs. Also there're fixes
to correct the Cancel button on the Create Property and Edit Property
dialogs which were missing the border.

Change-Id: If851732656d883fe2e26f4d4011337dac356cd25
Closes-Bug: #1362704

commit_message:
Faster nova fixed key generation

Using bc 64 times in loop is too verbose and slow,
replacing the echo/bc loop with hexdump and urandom.

The hexdump approach is 75 times faster and
does not floods the debug logs.

Using the common function for generating,
this kind of string with lib/heat and by the read_password.

Change-Id: If6a86dfaf0c21e2635c6de0a7b96a8ed7ec5b507

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be

    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others

'}, {'created': '2014-08-11 00:39:24.000000000', 'message': 'Make turning debug on globally easy.

We can obviously use passthrough for this, but I rather suspect that

commit_message:
Make turning debug on globally easy.

We can obviously use passthrough for this, but I rather suspect that
OMFG something is broken get me debug will be a common phrase.

Change-Id: I62539630a4737bbbe6883ed71929f38c819ceed4

commit_message:
Make X-Project-ID a required header

We decided to make X-Project-ID a required header for every request. If
not present, a 400 error should be raised.

Partially-Implements: blueprint api-v1.1-header-changes
Change-Id: I6c6c21585e9a738ff7c0f74ce6a284229ebec2aa

commit_message:
Updated Module File Dependencies

Previously, the Modulefile did not include Keystone.
This would cause the module to not install all necessary
dependencies for Heat services.  This patch allows Heat to have
consistent dependencies with other OpenStack services.

Change-Id: I1e34f88701523971d093c621748e974ef30843c6

commit_message:
Let update_available_resource hit slave

Deployments that have a slave_connection configured can offload
read queries generated by this periodic task there. For
deployments with no slave, behavior remains the same.

Change-Id: Ie663ccc4e3e4334af4bdf75a95689c41ecc959b9
Blueprint: juno-slaveification

commit_message:
Don't create _member_ role from puppet

The _member_ role is provided by db migration or is created
automatically when user is created. Creating role _member_ from
puppet causes it to have different id than the one specified in
member_role_id keystone config option.

Change-Id: I3f0102b184a484f5e5a85cadf26ed651829fbf8c
Closes-Bug: rhbz#1129760

> good thing to support such new version.

Jessie: /usr/lib/EXTLINUX/mbr.bin
Utopic: /usr/lib/EXTLINUX/mbr.bin

Can you tell me where you found the reference to /usr/lib/syslinux/mbr/mbr.bin?"}, {'account_id': 12320, 'date': '2014-08-06 13:57:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

> Jessie: /usr/lib/EXTLINUX/mbr.bin

That's in "extlinux", while /usr/lib/syslinux/mbr/mbr.bin is in syslinux-common (arch:all package used by syslinux, extlinux, pxelinux, and isolinux).

> Can you tell me where you found the reference to /usr/lib/syslinux/mbr/mbr.bin?

For example https://bugs.debian.org/746747, opened by the Debian maintainer of syslinux.

Thus, IMHO just searching for mbr.bin /usr/share/syslinux/mbr.bin, /usr/lib/syslinux/mbr.bin, or /usr/lib/syslinux/mbr/mbr.bin should do the job in a more general way with less places to look at.'}, {'account_id': 2036, 'date': '2014-08-07 08:51:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

> That's in "extlinux", while /usr/lib/syslinux/mbr/mbr.bin is in syslinux-common (arch:all package used by syslinux, extlinux, pxelinux, and isolinux).

But we're installing extlinux in the element so I want to pull mbr.bin from that package and not a different copy from a different package that might (or not) get installed as a dependency.'}, {'account_id': 12320, 'date': '2014-08-07 08:59:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

extlinux (and so syslinux, etc) depends on syslinux-common, and the copies of mbr.bin are the very same.

Also, going into the "might/might not" area, one could also imagine that the copies in extlinux and syslinux binaries might go away because they are provided by syslinux-common already.'}, {'account_id': 6928, 'date': '2014-08-13 20:27:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-02 10:47:32.000000000', 'message': 'Extend/fix support for extlinux bootloader

Some extlinux packages install mbr.bin under /usr/lib/extlinux so
that directory needs to be checked as well. Also, there are packages
that create a /boot/extlinux directory which needs to be taken into
account. Finally, commit bccffc8bfdfea4c452a5558a27f4d16da9cab6c7
dropped the /boot prefix from the kernel and initrd references in
the ext/syslinux config file which is simply a bug that needs fixing.

Change-Id: Idb071c9b18ff557b0f0f76d0d754536f2deca904
Closes-Bug: 1335042
'}, {'created': '2014-07-02 11:35:50.000000000', 'message': 'Extend/fix support for extlinux bootloader

'}, {'created': '2014-07-30 07:50:25.000000000', 'message': 'Extend/fix support for extlinux bootloader

Some extlinux packages install mbr.bin under /usr/lib/extlinux or

commit_message:
Extend/fix support for extlinux bootloader

Some extlinux packages install mbr.bin under /usr/lib/extlinux or
/usr/lib/EXTLINUX so tese directories need to be checked as well.
Also, there are packages that create a /boot/extlinux directory
which needs to be taken into account. Finally, commit
bccffc8bfdfea4c452a5558a27f4d16da9cab6c7 dropped the /boot prefix
from the kernel and initrd references in the ext/syslinux config
file which is simply a bug that needs fixing.

Change-Id: Idb071c9b18ff557b0f0f76d0d754536f2deca904
Closes-Bug: 1335042

commit_message:
Run cinder-volume in active/passive mode for NFS backend

Running multiple cinder-volume instances which access the same storage
is currently not supported and may cause data inconsistency.
This issue is discussed here:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/cinder/+bug/1322190

Running cinder-volume service in active/passive mode seems to be
the only safe way when shared backend storage is used. Also
workaround with setting shared host is needed.

Of course in default no-HA setup each cinder-volume manages its
local volumes and none of the above is needed.

Change-Id: Id8f5c33f63538a9be85a1434f36b0a840e0b8db9

Why would this need to submit the token id as part of a post request? Why wouldn't it just use the token value from X-Auth-Token?"}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2014-09-02 07:12:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

So I guess the question is whether we think the action we are taking here is an "authorization" step?  If we do, then this is akin to exchanging one keystone token for another of different scope (when we do use token_id in the body in place of, say, password method).  If we don't consider this authorization (and this step will happen in the foreign keystone), then maybe this shouldn't be /auth at all.  My fear is that perhaps both my statements are true!'}, {'account_id': 6482, 'date': '2014-09-02 07:24:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

This step should be happening on a local keystone. So "I want my local keystone to give me a SAML assertion (based on token) that will work on some other cloud's service provider (based on region)"'}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2014-09-02 07:37:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

Steve - sure, understand where there are taking place...but my point was what the conceptual model was of what was happening in each place (i.e. Authentication vs Authorization)....as a way of determining whether using token_id in the body is appropriate vs in the header'}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2014-09-02 08:02:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

Authorisation is a two step process in federation. In terms of the RBAC model, it comprises

1. Assigning roles (or attributes) to users. This is done by the IDP

2. Assigning privileges to roles (or attributes). This is done by the SP

So in Keystone - Keystone federation, both Keystones are participating in the authorisation. The sending Keystone assigns the attributes when creating the SAML assertion, and the receiving Keystone will map them into local attributes ready for the service to assign privileges to them'}, {'account_id': 4, 'date': '2014-09-02 16:13:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11: Code-Review+2

Token ID in the request body vs X-Auth-Token is an interesting question, but I don't see it as a blocking issue. If anything, this falls inline with how we rescope tokens (also effectively an authZ-only operation); if that's a design mistake, then it's not new here."}, {'account_id': 7725, 'date': '2014-09-02 16:16:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Code-Review+2

I talked to Steve about this in IRC and agree with the API. It matches existing APIs: http://docs.openstack.org/developer/keystone/api_curl_examples.html#getting-a-token-from-a-token'}, {'account_id': 7191, 'date': '2014-09-02 18:15:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: -Code-Review

So i disagree with this being an authorization step. Essentially you are asking for a new representation of the token that you already have - when you rescope you are typically asking for a change in some way.

However I am think I am way too late to this party to start blocking things now.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-02 18:19:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: -Verified

Starting gate jobs.
http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 4, 'date': '2014-09-02 18:19:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11: Workflow+1

jamie's concern is certainly valid. another way to think about scope is that the region / service provider that the token is valid within is being mutated (so a new representation is issued)."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-02 18:27:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Verified+2

Conceptually the user is asking for a set of identity attributes to be packaged up to send to a remote SP (in this case a keystone/openstack cloud). The fact that the returned token is in SAML format is irrelevant. It could be in any format that the remote Keystone can understand.

The user should be able to control and consent to the set of attributes that are packaged up in the token. He may want all his current set of attributes or just a subset of them (for least privileges). This should be his choice. 

So it is an authorisation step. Not only that, but I think you may currently be missing giving the user fine control over which attributes should be packaged up in the SAML assertion'}]

Add SAML generation route to OS-FEDERATION

Create the specification for SAML generation in the OS-FEDERATION
api spec.

Co-Authored-By: Marek Denis <marek.denis@cern.ch>

Implements: bp keystone-to-keystone-federation

commit_message:
Implement GroupSet updatable for AWS::EC2::NetworkInterface

Implement the 'GroupSet' updatable for
AWS::EC2::NetworkInterface resource to be compatible
with AWSCloudFormation.

Change-Id: Ia92c6d2732fdafc659d1a9a1db01cb66be9a9bc0
Closes-Bug: #1334212

commit_message:
Match tenant_id when name ambiguity in get_secgroup_uuids()

Neutron allows securityGroup creation with same name
between one/more users, and the admin roles can get/use
the other users' securityGroup. So if there are several
securityGroups return, we should match the one which is
belongs to the stack owner, and then to raise
'PhysicalResourceNameAmbiguity' exception if can't match.

Change-Id: Icb7eae35ba40a142a4d398b7c9d58c8483b9588e
Closes-Bug: #1348064

commit_message:
Fix rhel image can not boot issue

syslinux can not find kernel to boot if we just speicify kernel's base.

Change-Id: I6ee1d37e91e53163b11845ea4c75659f009a2f3c
Closes-Bug: #1353800

commit_message:
Making a few modules hacking 0.9.2 compliant

Global requirements has updating the version of hacking to a minimum of
0.9.2 and it has brought a whole slew of changes. This is tackling five
modules which contain new violations.

commit_message:
Change | to > in templates.

Clint pointed out that | prevents things rendering properly on
arbitrarily wide screens. For most things that makes sense but it
doesn't for the JSON examples IMO so I didn't alter those.

Change-Id: Ifb7dcc265c225b000bd5d26500212d41ea0233c8

Hi, Deepak.  Is cert-based access synonymous with the native gluster protocol?  That is, would you also support certs with the glusterfs.py driver?

Regarding access groups:  I see no issue with this WIP and what we are doing with access groups, although you will have work to do in the gluster drivers to support access groups.  We are thinking we will have to enhance the driver interface with a method that specifies the entire, exclusive set of accesses that apply to a share (any change to a group may result in one or more access additions or revocations); drivers can then apply the access rule set as they see fit.  Also, an access group will consist of access rules of a single type, i.e. IP or user or cert; you will have to decide if it makes sense to allow groups of type cert.'}, {'account_id': 10796, 'date': '2014-08-26 06:05:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Clinton Knight, 
    Currently 'cert' based access is only supported by glusterfs native protocol (implemented in glusterfs_native.py). glusterfs.py supports NFS (and in future maybe CIFS) and doesn't support cert access type.

Thanks for the elaborate info on access groups."}, {'account_id': 10796, 'date': '2014-08-26 08:26:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/manila/2014/manila.2014-07-24-15.01.log.html
(15:27:19 onwards)

This patch does 2 things:
* Add support for cert access-type in access-allow API
* Add glusterfs native driver that uses cert based access type

TODOs:

* Separate this into 2 patches (one for manila access-allow and
  other for for glusterfs backend implementation)

Partially-implements blueprint cert-based-access-type

'}, {'created': '2014-08-26 11:35:36.000000000', 'message': "Add support for cert based access type

This patch adds support for cert based access type in Manila.
It introduces a new access-type called 'cert' in access-allow API.

Per the Manila IRC discussions, the cert based trust setup between
instances and backend is out-of-band to Manila. See the log @
http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/manila/2014/manila.2014-07-24-15.01.log.html
(15:27:19 onwards)

TODOs:
* Add testcases

commit_message:
Add support for cert based access type

This patch adds support for cert based access type in Manila.
It introduces a new 'access_type' called 'cert' in access-allow API.
'access_to' argument passed by the user is the certificate's CN
(common name) to which access is allowed by the backend.

Per the Manila IRC discussions, the cert based trust setup between
instances and backend is out-of-band to Manila. See the log @
http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/manila/2014/manila.2014-07-24-15.01.log.html
(15:27:19 onwards)

Partially-implements blueprint cert-based-access-type

Change-Id: Ib48430deccece66a740ce05471db70eaadf634b3

Hi Edgar,

This DFA CI testbed is doing real tests with real devices and proposed DFA code patches (total of 5 BPs).

Since our code pieces are under review and not merged yet, it is impossible to automate the patches for each Gerrit trigger as it just creates so many merge conflicts that require manual resolutions  a job impossible for anyone to do after we initially did this.  It will be fully patched automatically once our software is in the master branch.

(If you have a mechanism that can automatically resolve all the merge conflicts during patching, we would love to try.)

So what we have in our CI is all the DFA code pieces based on a recent master code base.  Triggered by each patch in Neutron, it does all the tests as shown in the CI report.

We see this is a perfect combination until our code is merged in (and it makes good technical sense too):

-	The community Jenkins will keep everything clean with our code patches for the default (no DFA configured)

-	DFA tempest will make sure DFA functions as expected, as our DFA CI report is showing.


To prove this, we can manually patch 114629 code into our code base and we should expect to see failures when we add "recheck cisco" comment in 114629.  Please advise if that's what you want to see.

Please let me know if you want to review the DFA CI testbed topology and the details of the test again (this was sent to you when addressing one of your earlier CI comments to our testbed)



Thanks'}, {'account_id': 704, 'date': '2014-08-15 22:47:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 17:

commit_message:
Cisco DFA ML2 Mechanism Driver

Part 1:
This commit contains changes to support ML2 mechanism driver for Cisco
DFA. For more details please see the blueprint which has more description and
link to document with requirements.

Part 2: Changes in OVS neutron agent.
(http://review.openstack.org/110065)

Part 3: DFA extension driver.
(http://review.openstack.org/111761)

Part 4: DFA config profile service plugin.
(http://review.openstack.org/111863)

Change-Id: Ib53b6705948e1ed75059b85d8809562d9bb63f65
Partially Implements: blueprint ml2-mechanism-driver-for-cisco-dfa

After discussion with flaper87 in irc, I think this change is a quick fix to unblock glance.store adoption progress, even this issue could be resolved by devlop-install for glance by tox after issue19352 fixed. I'm OK on this change currently since anyway I see it's a harmless change and oslo already moved it out.

Due to j3 timeline is tight so cast my vote here, but if I miss anything pls let me know."}, {'account_id': 616, 'date': '2014-08-26 17:02:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: Code-Review-1

I remember but cannot find the mailing list discussion we had about this approach ages ago. As I recall there were some strong arguments on the other side of this proposal. Have we already floated this idea on the mailing list recently?

I'm okay accepting the change if there has been an opportunity for infra folks to point out undesirable consequences of this change.

Thanks"}, {'account_id': 616, 'date': '2014-08-26 17:03:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: -Code-Review'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2014-08-27 06:25:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

@Mark, we had this discussion on IRC, in a meeting.

The only concern I can recall was that it is sometimes nice to ship tests along with projects. FWIW, we keep all tests outside our oslo packages because of the same reason.

I asked Doug about this, since we do it in Oslo, and AFAICT there are no red lights from an infra perspective. Oslo and Zaqar are the current projects doing this right now, AFAIK.'}, {'account_id': 12395, 'date': '2014-08-27 11:55:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 5263, 'date': '2014-08-27 13:30:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

If you're worried about whether this will affect the unit test jobs, note that changes to glance are self-tested so you should just be able to review the logs from the latest test run on this patch to determine whether you believe it did the right thing before approving."}, {'account_id': 5202, 'date': '2014-08-27 13:52:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 1, 'date': '2014-08-27 14:25:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

I believe Monty Taylor feels very strongly that tests should be within the package.  Perhaps among other reasons, so that other projects that use/wrap/extend/whatever a given project can still validate the whole using the supplied tests.

You might consider waiting until next week to give him an opportunity to weigh in.'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2014-08-27 15:31:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

@James Yeah, I remember that being his feeling about tests. However, if we stick with namespaces, we will have to make this change happen regardless due to the issues mentioned in the commit message.

A new discussion has been started on the mailing list w.r.t the namespace thing so, I'd probably wait on this thread instead:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-August/044194.html

TBH, I think tests living in or outside the project namespace depends on what the project itself does. My personal taste is that tests should not live in the project, although this patch has nothing to do with my personal taste."}, {'account_id': 8127, 'date': '2014-08-27 18:05:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-30 09:40:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2014-09-02 19:59:21.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

This patch is not needed anymore. glance.store has been renamed to glance_store'}]

commit_message:
Move tests out of glance's package

In order for Glance to adopt glance.store, it is necessary to move the
tests out of the server. This is due to a tests discovery issue where it
finds in the local working copy but loads them from the installed
glance. Unfortunately, we can't use develop installs to test
Glance+glance.store due a bug in Python/setuptools where all packages in
a namespace have to be installed using the same method (either install
or develop).

Unittests loader issue: http://bugs.python.org/issue19352

Partially-Implements blueprint: create-store-package

Change-Id: I1e5de93709c3654b0c21957052df88430802ff8c

commit_message:
Make minor typo correction

from: openstack-config --set /etc/glance/glance-api.conf keystone_authtoken \
  auth_uri http://controller:5000

=>
openstack-config --set /etc/glance/glance-api.conf keystone_authtoken \
  auth_url http://controller:5000

Close-Bug: #1353635

Change-Id: I7c97b805695b011ce800c171d312b2a612bb4a9b

commit_message:
Fix dib-lint failures

As part of an ongoing effort to apply more testing against
elements, this patch provides fixes for most dib-lint
failures outside of the set -o pipefail patch[1] including
set options, indention, and file permissions.  There are
still a few indention errors left after this patch, but
they should be ignored in a dib-lint patch soon to add
additional exclusions.

[1] Ib97e3a35dd0ee653f1298c9ffe6ea99cea9dfd55

Change-Id: Ibf3dfc5735752900598466b0a54342692ef77284

commit_message:
First attempt at an angularJS workflow for launching heat stacks

  - replaces django multi-step form view with angular wizard
  - allows for multiple file uploads, client side file downloads
    (for file URLs), etc
  - requires a custom heatclient from here:
      o https://github.com/jsomara/python-heatclient/tree/envfiles
    if this becomes a blocking issue, we can add that method to horizon
    temporarily. The other possibility is that it is extended to support
    nested stacks as well (a Juno goal). This patch includes this code
    inside horizon, with the intention of removing it when support becomes
    available in upstream python-heatclient
  - there are outstanding messaging improvements (error messages, etc) that
    this patch could take advantage of for better message dialogs

To test this, check out sample environment & template files here. You'll
notice that the referenced file in the environment will get added in
stage2 of the wizard. If you don't have any file references to resolve,
it will go straight to stage3.
- https://github.com/hardys/demo_templates/blob/master/juno_summit_intro_to_heat/example2_server_with_volume_nested/server_with_volume.yaml
- https://github.com/hardys/demo_templates/blob/master/juno_summit_intro_to_heat/example4_provider_environment/env_server_with_volume.yaml
- https://github.com/hardys/demo_templates/blob/master/juno_summit_intro_to_heat/example4_provider_environment/server_with_volume_env.yaml

Fixes-Bug: #1322258
Partial-Implements:
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/horizon/+spec/heat-nested-stack
Change-Id: If94430491955c3b0450d9c282d9899dda2568e92

[{'created': '2014-09-02 18:30:25.000000000', 'message': 'Error trapping for ldap2py

Closes-Bug: #1364521

I've recently come across a condition where the ldap driver will
return values from Active Directory which cannot be utf8 encoded.

Network captures show a clean attribute and value list, whereas if
I put in a debug statement to write out the values as
returned by the driver I can see a value like this:
?"?gZK??[J????

I propose that we drop values which cannot be encoded.

Change-Id: I81622f3f6e6d78d714fad05d22a75261aefc27f5
'}]
commit_message:
Error trapping for ldap2py

Closes-Bug: #1364521

I've recently come across a condition where the ldap driver will
return values from Active Directory which cannot be utf8 encoded.

Network captures show a clean attribute and value list, whereas if
I put in a debug statement to write out the values as
returned by the driver I can see a value like this:
?"?gZK??[J????

I propose that we drop values which cannot be encoded.

Change-Id: I81622f3f6e6d78d714fad05d22a75261aefc27f5

Add hasrestart to some services

(5.0.X backport)
Hasrestart makes Puppet use restart instead of stop
and start to manage a service and many init scripts
would work better if used like this.

commit_message:
labs: fix libguestfs-tools installation

Supply an answer for the debconf prompt during libguestfs-tools
installation. The current lack of such an answer results in warnings
about "Use of uninitialized value" or a hanging script.

Change-Id: I23888737f24c5f4cd3c8e88ebba0701be85c1d87

commit_message:
Update installation guide for syslinux 6

Fedora 21 and the next Ubuntu will have syslinux 6 in them. In syslinux
6 modules are not "stand alone" as it was in versions prior to 4, see:
http://www.syslinux.org/wiki/index.php/Library_modules

Partial-Bug: #1351010
Change-Id: Ie6bb031c10a9f8cf978e2c5dbd643b4a19cc93d0

commit_message:
Doc: don't generate empty properties fields

Don't create empty properties fields in the resources samples.

This patch will help resolve niceness gates failures when generating the
docbook HOT reference.

Change-Id: I3c74fa583ac55dc0a23520ec07f5d07e3d1b6fab
Closes-Bug: #1360558

[{'created': '2014-09-01 15:34:53.000000000', 'message': "correctly implement volumes_from property

The Docker plugin incorrectly implements the 'volumes_from' option:

- The property is marked as a string when it should be a list, and
- The property needs to be passed to start_container rather than
  create_container.

Change-Id: I617a4d29a9edbb45d80c7b8abb8f87eeaf795a8b
closes-bug: #1364041
closes-bug: #1364039
"}]
commit_message:
correctly implement volumes_from property

The Docker plugin incorrectly implements the 'volumes_from' option:

- The property is marked as a string when it should be a list, and
- The property needs to be passed to start_container rather than
  create_container.

Change-Id: I617a4d29a9edbb45d80c7b8abb8f87eeaf795a8b
closes-bug: #1364041
closes-bug: #1364039

commit_message:
Temporarily pin requests<2.4.0

Today's release of requests 2.4.0 has resulted in unit test issues
for horizon and python-keystoneclient, but the problem may be more
widespread. Since we're nearing an integrated release milestone,
it's pragmatic to pin this now and allow projects to work out their
compatibility bugs after the milestone.

Change-Id: Id5180803402d207d6e59610474c11c61622f6b5a

commit_message:
Remove reference to cisco_cfg_agent.ini from setup.cfg again

No sample .ini file is included, causing install to fail.
Remove the reference again.

Change-Id: I97ffe464e4eb9689ee290c3c95ac19d4e09029e2
Closes-bug: #1351466

commit_message:
Deprecate cinder_* configuration settings

Create a new section in the configuration file called 'cinder'.
Move all of the cinder_* configuration settings to this section.

DocImpact

The table below has the changes:

+---------------------------------+----------------------------+
| 'DEFAULT' Section               | 'cinder' Section           |
|---------------------------------|----------------------------|
| cinder_catalog_info             | catalog_info               |
| cinder_endpoint_template        | endpoint_template          |
| os_region_name                  | os_region_name             |
| cinder_ca_certificates_file     | ca_certificates_file       |
| cinder_http_retries             | http_retries               |
| cinder_http_timeout             | http_timeout               |
| cinder_api_insecure             | api_insecure               |
| cinder_cross_az_attach          | cross_az_attach            |
+---------------------------------+----------------------------+

UpgradeImpact
The changes are backward compatible.

Change-Id: Ie6b3f9d60b5e149375ff3039be444538f5f50756

commit_message:
Update apt_pre-download script

Refactor apt_pre-download script to classify the packages as per the
services and nodes for better debugging. This change makes it much
more convinent to go through the apt_pre-download.sh for adding,
debugging the issues.

Change-Id: I49f16953805a5895b813abfda2a33775c54236fc

commit_message:
Squash Icehouse DB Migrations

MySQL: Produces an identical database, with one bug fixed in migration 40.
SQLite: Produces a "better" database, with some lost constraints restored.
PostgreSQL: Produces an identical database, with a bug in migration 39 fixed.

Change-Id: I8c8397ad38cc2d6344aa169c766e3adf18043ee1

commit_message:
ML2: Fix release of network segments to allocation pools

The recent merge of https://review.openstack.org/#/c/115025/ broke the
release of network segments to allocation pools on network delete,
resulting in network creates eventually failing with
NoNetworkAvailable exceptions. The network_delete() code is rearranged
to properly release the network segments, and a unit test is updated
to verify that the type drivers' release_segment() method is called.

Partially implements: Blueprint ml2-type-driver-refactor

Change-Id: Ica5f11b2012dedfcc097f34f1515f5f3ca208fd2

commit_message:
report missing containers as deleted

The docker plugin will fail to delete a container resource if the
specified container is missing:

    APIError: 404 Client Error: Not Found ("No such container: None")

This patch modifies check_delete_complete to return 'true' if the docker
module raises an error for a 404 response from Docker.

closes-bug: #1364017
Change-Id: I33373ea0c010a5809454a5065e13c724731a21ce

commit_message:
Add openstack_version_prev key to deployment info

We should send to Astute information about previous openstack versions,
since it's needed by our puppet manifests.

It seems your tests fail due to combination of the following two issues:

* leveldb seems to be available from the ceph-ext-<release> in RedHat based systems
* in all the other tests leveldb gets installed as a dependency, but never uninstalled

The following things would resolve this:

* test for a package that is ONLY available from ceph-extras on Debian family systens and ext-ceph-extras in RedHat family systems
* add leveldb (well actually the package name of the package you select above) to the list of packages to remove in all the other tests

NB: there might be a real issue on RedHat family systems, as packages from ext-ceph-<release> and ext-ceph-extras seem to overlap. You might need to fix this by adding different priorities to the extras package.'}, {'account_id': 9995, 'date': '2014-06-23 00:04:41.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 10.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-23 00:04:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

add ceph-extras and fast-cgi repositories.

adds ceph-extras and mod_fastcgi repositories, with newer versions for
required dependencies.

both off by default. includes rspec and rspec system tests.

commit_message:
Add boot_device support for vbox

In the Ironic ssh driver,
command set of 'set_boot_device' and 'get_boot_device' were not implemented
on VirualBox. This fixes it.

Change-Id: Icd19c7d1b5c11109cb6b400e99a6e7f2baa73d22
Closes-Bug: #1360017

We have tests that import fakes from the python-novaclient. For example,
in congresss/datasources/tests/unit/fakes.py. We should not be doing this
as the novaclients tests are not intended to be a stable interface thus
because additional imports were added to the novaclient file here this
broke us since we don't require these imports. This patch is a quick
hack to get the unit tests working though we need to fix this otherwise
our tests will mostly break again in the future when the novaclient changes.

Change-Id: Iafceea05a3989012b460e48ebfa2021e8d4e74c5
Closes-bug: 1364136
"}]
commit_message:
Fix missing imports causing gate failures

We have tests that import fakes from the python-novaclient. For example,
in congresss/datasources/tests/unit/fakes.py. We should not be doing this
as the novaclients tests are not intended to be a stable interface thus
because additional imports were added to the novaclient file here this
broke us since we don't require these imports. This patch is a quick
hack to get the unit tests working though we need to fix this otherwise
our tests will mostly break again in the future when the novaclient changes.

Change-Id: Iafceea05a3989012b460e48ebfa2021e8d4e74c5
Closes-bug: 1364136

Allow list_limit to be configured

Add list_limit for default, assignment, catalog, identity and policy
sections.

commit_message:
Implements the DRAC ManagementInterface for get/set boot device

What it says. The get_sensors_data() won't be implemented as part of
this patch because it's outside the scope of the blueprint.

Co-Authored-By: Imre Farkas <ifarkas@redhat.com>
Implements blueprint drac-management-driver
Change-Id: I9cae3156b6af016bfbf64cb3c117fdec8536f714

commit_message:
Add public key API for Identity provider

Keystone to Keystone federation requires Identity service
to validate tokens issued by a federated peers.
Remote Identity Providers should now have public keys added
during federation configuration in order to check tokens signatures.

Implements blueprint: keystone-to-keystone-federation

Change-Id: Ieb66c6c8ca26d1b1b380270375cabd3d6502dc81

Set permissions for Murano dashboard

Without the 'orchestration' role, no user can create a heat stack,
so the Murano Dashboard panels should also require the same role.

Change-Id: I731474e3481b4be45392186ea41e9cea8ee9399c
Closes-bug: #1361837

Just discussed this with garyk on IRC. I believe the point he's making is that the function is easier to test when split out. The change in question modifies this function, making it marginally less trivial.

I disagree that the function needs unit testing at all, because it does not constitute a unit by any reasonable definition. The most appropriate unit here would seem to be VCState. commit_message:
VMware: inline _get_ds_capacity_and_freespace()

This trivial utility function was only split out because it was used in both
HostState and VCState. HostState no longer exists, and this code is more
readable inline.

Change-Id: I1dec31c78e6058b507f857b1e845b2c8dbbb8f92

I like it...

And I have related question.
CrudManager uses self.collection_key and self.key in its wrapper method around as response_key for _get(), _list() and other methods from BaseManager.

This prevents use of CrudManager with API that returns json without response_key.

In addition, it uses these keys both for url building and for json parsing. Some APIs uses different strings in url and json, ie. Volume Types in http://api.openstack.org/api-ref-blockstorage.html (GET v2/?{tenant_id}?/types returns json with "volume_types" response_key).'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-02-26 19:09:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: No score

commit_message:
Fix response_key parameter usage in BaseManager

Methods _get() _list() and _post() in BaseManager class requires
mandatory parameter `response_key`. This parameter is the key to be
looked up in response dictionary. But in such case we have no possibility
to proceed another response format.

Made response_key parameter optional. So if this parameter missed,
method will use all response, instead of response[response_key] if
client will have no possibility to provide required response dictionary.

related to blueprint common-client-library-2

Change-Id: I157c4bdea6243dd286ec6103494ede0d69ae4268

commit_message:
Add test for ResourceDefinition equality

ResourceDefinition objects compare equal if they are generated from
equivalent templates. Only the MRO stands between us and disaster (since
both superclasses - ResourceDefinitionCore and collections.Mapping - define
__eq__ methods), so add a test to confirm that we are getting the correct
one.

Change-Id: I8181f91f08fd81104fe493539511d6fd129522c8

commit_message:
Don't stop creates/updates immediately on error

When an error occurs during a stack create or update operation, don't
immediately stop the operation. Instead, wait up to 4 minutes for resoures
already in progress to complete before forcibly cancelling them. This
minimises the number of resources that will need to be replaced when using
the features from the blueprint update-failure-recovery to recover after
such a failed operation.

Change-Id: Ib08f3d8faea31f251a46fc0537983127f8ba2783

"}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2014-01-22 20:34:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Hi Sylvain,

I'm -1 on this because I do not believe this kind of thing belongs in the Neutron source tree. It's the same review I would give if you had a used a different resource manager, for example ZooKeeper. I firmly believe that this kind of thing should be the domain of configuration management and deploying automation tools, not something baked into Neutron (or any other OpenStack project).

To implement HA for the L3 agent in Neutron, we should be focusing on removing stored state or redesigning how state in the L3 router agent is handled. We should not be implementing resource manager callbacks/wrappers in the project itself.

Best,

-jay"}, {'account_id': 7141, 'date': '2014-01-22 21:36:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Hi Jay,

If you look at the blueprint, discussed in HK, you will see that keepalived will not handle the network node but each virtual router. So for each router a keepalived configuration will be generated in order to manage virtual router interfaces(public, private, floating-ip). Exactly the same way as the dhcp agent manages dhcp by writing a specific configuration file per network. It is not here a matter of deployment, but a HA backend like dnsmasq for dns/dhcp. Other components could leverage this wrapper, I know this BP https://blueprints.launchpad.net/neutron/+spec/lbaas-ha-haproxy, even if I don't know how they plan to use keepalived.

Regards,

-Sylvain"}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2014-01-22 21:47:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: No score

Apologies, Sylvain :( I definitely misunderstood the patch's purpose. I will do an in-depth review in a bit. Sorry!"}, {'account_id': 5948, 'date': '2014-01-23 08:41:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

commit_message:
Introduces a keepalived manager for HA

This patch introduces a keepalived manager
which will be used for the blueprint
blueprint l3-high-availability.

The manager can create a keepalived.conf compliant configuration,
start, stop and restart the service, as well as create keepalived
notification scripts.

Implements: blueprint l3-high-availability
Change-Id: I1ba9f332778f27de950d9e97d4fb4a337f6f26da
Co-Authored-By: Assaf Muller <amuller@redhat.com>

subject: Adding timeout parameters to init-keystone

A week or 2 back we did have quite a few CI jobs fail around init-keystone, but that was a different keystone bug as I recall that has since been fixed."}, {'account_id': 4220, 'date': '2014-08-20 18:03:04.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 4220, 'date': '2014-08-20 18:05:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

commit_message:
Adding timeout parameters to init-keystone

Adding params + documentation to make wait time configurable
because this seems like a sensible and useful thing to have available.

Defaults and behavior remain unchanged if one does not use the new
params.

Change-Id: I1da6a2838397b21229f1e48e98ae47eda49470c2

(3 inline comments)

This is a good first approach, but I agree with Eugene.

Moreover I don't think a new network descriptor should be used in driver context, the "current" should be enhanced to have extension informations. I think this should be targeted by a bug report, since the description of driverContext.current() mentionned that extension's informations should be returned.'}, {'account_id': 6072, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Hi,

This is a desirable feature that we've discussed at Icehouse summit.

However, the approach should be more generic, API layer should not depend on particular plugin.
Instead, extension framework should be amended in such way that it could embed additional attributes/resources into API layer which it gathered from plugin (which, in turn, collects them from drivers)

In such way API code remains mostly untouched. I'd like to see this approach applied to implementing this feature."}, {'account_id': 10393, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: (3 inline comments)

Thanks a lot for taking time and reviewing this.

> This is a good first approach, but I agree with Eugene.

I also agree with Eugene and talking to him to understand his proposal. But in the meantime this could be an alternative solution.


> Moreover I don't think a new network descriptor should be used in driver  
> context, the "current" should be enhanced to have extension informations. I  
> think this should be targeted by a bug report, since the description of  
> driverContext.current() mentionned that extension's informations should be  
> returned.

I believe source of the problems is in Bug 1201957 where is sets the 
process_extensions to False for all create_<resource>. 
Then we can set the driverContext.original() to the values that for the first time passed to the create_<resource>. So mechanism driver can use extension when they need.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

can you put this path as "Work In Progress". You will need Unit test before proposing it under review.

my understanding is that the patch from salvatore was needed to reduce DB call, by using sqlachemy backref instead :
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/39093/3/neutron/db/portsecurity_db.py

As salvatore said (https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1201957), backref are used by other extensions.

we could potentially use those backref. We could build the network dict with every information added by extension to the network db object through a backref.'}, {'account_id': 2888, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: (1 inline comment)

Thanks for the review and comments.

* Sure Update the "Work In Progress". 
* Will add unit test code.


* Regarding using backref for port security: it works in that specific case. Because the db is getting created with extensions attributes. Here is part of code that calls _process_network_port_security_create ( method in PortSecurityDbMixin) in create_network in vmware/plugins/base.py.

As you can see net_data (line 950) has all the network attributes. However, new_net (line 982) does not have extensions attribute. But when _process_network_port_security is called (line 985) the parameter passed to this method are net_data (which has original network parameters - including extension) and new_net (which is network object from create_network). So DB can be created with all the network attributes including port_security_enabled extension attribute. 
 
 /neutron/plugins/vmware/plugins/base.py
950    def create_network(self, context, network):
951        net_data = network['network']
952        tenant_id = self._get_tenant_id_for_create(context, net_data)


968        external = net_data.get(ext_net_extn.EXTERNAL)
969        # NOTE(salv-orlando): Pre-generating uuid for Neutron
970        # network. This will be removed once the network create operation
971        # becomes an asynchronous task
972        net_data['id'] = str(uuid.uuid4())


981        with context.session.begin(subtransactions=True):
982            new_net = super(NsxPluginV2, self).create_network(context,
983                                                              network)
984            # Process port security extension
985            self._process_network_port_security_create(
986                context, net_data, new_net)
================
This won't work for the ML2 Plugin as the network attributes passed to the mechanism driver does not have extensions attribute.
As long as we don't have all network attributes in the mechanism driver, how can we create DB with extensions and use backref when needed.'}, {'account_id': 10393, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(3 comments)

It seems to me the specification for this work should have been discussed more as it did not have an appropriate level of detail.

I agree that we want ml2 to support non-standard extension, and therefore I'd like to find a way forward before the juno-3 deadline. However, if we have a framework with no user, I would prefer to defer it to kilo. Basically we need to validate the proposed approach with an actual extension.

I've seen you've exposed a mechanism for allowing extension drivers to declare supported extension aliases - but I could not find the code where the ml2 plugin leverages it.

It also seems you would like to allow drivers to extend core objects in any possible way. I'm assuming that however these would be extensions registered in the neutron/api/extensions otherwise that would not be good.

Furthermore, I don't understand why we need to specify the extension drivers. First, they're not driver - they seem processors to me. I think it will be way easier if a mechanism driver declares which extension supports, thus triggering the appropriate processor in the ml2 plugin.

Finally, I have no idea at the moment of whether this will work with multiple mech drivers exposing different extensions, or if that could be a source of additional problems. It seems this approach is based on the assumption that only a single mech driver for building networks is used at any time. Otherwise we'd need to deal with situations where one mech drivers supports a given extension and the other doesn't.

As a side note, I think many drivers rather than extending resources would like to declare new ones. I wonder if this framework can address this problem."}, {'account_id': 1689, 'date': '2014-08-13 19:46:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 15: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

A few comments in-line. As a core reviewer heavily involved in the review of the design spec for this BP, my responses to Salvatore's concerns:

Salvatore - It seems to me the specification for this work should have been discussed more as it did not have an appropriate level of detail.

Bob - It was discussed extensively. The initial draft spec didn't have much detail, and took a very different approach, but the final approved spec describes the proposed extension driver API in reasonable detail. This was the agreed approach.

Salvatore - I agree that we want ml2 to support non-standard extension, and therefore I'd like to find a way forward before the juno-3 deadline. However, if we have a framework with no user, I would prefer to defer it to kilo. Basically we need to validate the proposed approach with an actual extension.

Bob - I believe Nader is working on another Juno BP that implements an extension driver. This patch also includes a test extension driver that is functional.

Salvatore - I've seen you've exposed a mechanism for allowing extension drivers to declare supported extension aliases - but I could not find the code where the ml2 plugin leverages it.

Bob - These aliases are included in the ML2 plugin's supported_extension_aliases (abstract) property, causing the extensions themselves to be loaded by the WSGI framework.

Salvatore - It also seems you would like to allow drivers to extend core objects in any possible way. I'm assuming that however these would be extensions registered in the neutron/api/extensions otherwise that would not be good.

Bob - See above regarding supported_extension_aliases. The extension module itself can be in neutron/api/extensions, or another location added to extension-path.

Salvatore - Furthermore, I don't understand why we need to specify the extension drivers. First, they're not driver - they seem processors to me. I think it will be way easier if a mechanism driver declares which extension supports, thus triggering the appropriate processor in the ml2 plugin.

Bob - This agreed approach is consistent with the overall ML2 driver model, where we already have type drivers and mechanism drivers. Type drivers also do not interact directly with back-end devices. The idea of having mechanism drivers directly support extensions was initially proposed, but was rejected for several reasons. For one, making the extensions orthogonal allows the same extension to easily be utilized by more than one mechanism driver. Second, making extension drivers explicitly configured ensures the operator is aware they are enabling an API extension. Third, just because a mechanism driver is enabled that might know something about an extension doesn't mean that mechanism driver is always able to enforce the semantics of that extension. If some other mechanism driver not supporting the extension binds the port, then extended attribute values would be completely ignored. Instead, semantic enforcement has to be done through followup work on port binding that will be proposed for Kilo. What's being done in Juno is an initial step that is sufficient for the needs of the Juno-targeted BP that depends on it. This has all been discussed in depth during the spec review.

Salvatore - Finally, I have no idea at the moment of whether this will work with multiple mech drivers exposing different extensions, or if that could be a source of additional problems. It seems this approach is based on the assumption that only a single mech driver for building networks is used at any time. Otherwise we'd need to deal with situations where one mech drivers supports a given extension and the other doesn't.

Bob - Valid point, related to what I mentioned above. I completely agree we eventually need to address the enforcement of the semantics implied by the specific values of the extended attributes. I have discussed a scheme for this with Nader and a couple other people, which we think should be implemented in Kilo. This will involve both the extension drivers and the mechanism drivers, and will ensure that if the value of an extended attribute requires support in the binding, no binding not supporting this will be allowed. But remember a binding often involves multiple mechanism drivers. The conclusion during the spec review was that this first step in Juno was sufficient for a vendor-specific extension where the vendor documents exactly what mechanism drivers to configure.

Salvatore - As a side note, I think many drivers rather than extending resources would like to declare new ones. I wonder if this framework can address this problem.

Bob - This was discussed, and it was realized that this is best accomplished through the existing service plugin support. In fact, Nader's DFA BP implementation includes both an extension driver that extends network, and a service plugin that adds a new resource."}, {'account_id': 10393, 'date': '2014-08-13 19:48:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 15:

Hi Salvatore,

Thanks for the review and here is my reply to your comments:

> It seems to me the specification for this work should have been discussed more as it did not have an appropriate level of detail.

The BP submitted long time ago and there were lots of discussion about it and put what's need to be done to support such a feature in the BP.

> I agree that we want ml2 to support non-standard extension, and therefore I'd like to find a way forward before the juno-3 deadline. However, if we have a framework with > no user, I would prefer to defer it to kilo. Basically we need to validate the proposed approach with an actual extension.

Actually there is user for that. The MD cisco DFA heavily depends on it BP is approved for juno-3.
 So it is needed and also I was contacted for this work that could be used for port security feature.


> I've seen you've exposed a mechanism for allowing extension drivers to declare supported extension aliases - but I could not find > the code where the ml2 plugin leverages it.

It should be used in an extension driver that is supported by a mechanism driver. For instance the code in 
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/111761 shows how it is used.


> It also seems you would like to allow drivers to extend core objects in any possible way. I'm assuming that however these would be > extensions registered in the neutron/api/extensions otherwise that would not be good.

That's correct. The extensions are registered in the neutron/api/extensions.


> Furthermore, I don't understand why we need to specify the extension drivers. First, they're not driver - they seem processors to
> me. I think it will be way easier if a mechanism driver declares which extension supports, thus triggering the appropriate processor > in the ml2 plugin.

The nature of this work is similar to the mechanism driver. An extension driver supported by a mechanism driver is added to config/entry point and will be loaded during ML2 initialization. With that the extension driver methods/attributed can be easily triggered when a resource is created/updated/requested.


> Finally, I have no idea at the moment of whether this will work with multiple mech drivers exposing different extensions, or if that > could be a source of additional problems. It seems this approach is based on the assumption that only a single mech driver for
> building networks is used at any time. Otherwise we'd need to deal with situations where one mech drivers supports a given 
> extension and the other doesn't.

With multiple mechanism drivers I can think of following:
- mech driver vendor X, mech driver vendor Y, mech driver feature N, mech driver feature M, .
If X, Y, N, M, are adding their supported extensions to the core resources it would work as each of them can add their own attribute (as <namespace:attribute_name> to avoid collision) and process their own attribute when process_*_*  in the extension driver is called. With this framework each mech driver can have their own extended attributes.

> As a side note, I think many drivers rather than extending resources would like to declare new ones.
> I wonder if this framework can address this problem.

This framework addresses extending attribute to the core resources. If there is need to declare new resources it can be done through
other means such as services.


Hopefully it clarify your concerns and -2 can be removed.

Regards,
Nader."}, {'account_id': 10393, 'date': '2014-08-13 23:00:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 15:

Thanks for all the explanations.

For now, I would avoid going into the field of whether drivers should be freely allowed to add their own details into API responses. This is a good discussion to have, but probably not suitable for gerrit (ie: should be on the mailing list)

Assuming it is ok to do that, only extensions declared in neutron/extensions should be supported. I see for instance the DFA mech driver is adding an attribute to the response - but that attribute for what I gather belong to a new extension not defined in neutron/extension. I think this is probably either an oversight on my side or something missing in the DFA implementation, but I reckon it's important.

Second, I really would like to avoid deployers from specifying extensions managers. I understand your concerns around stuff that you need to add in Kilo and can't do know for having a proper way of doing extensions. However, I'd say that for the time being perhaps in the conf file you can just specify the extension aliases you expect ML2 to support, and fail at startup if no mech driver support them.

You might keep the "extension drivers", which as said in a previous review will then become processors.  the advantage is that deployers won't have to declare drivers, but merely expected extensions.

These are my concerns at the moment, with the pending items regarding whether we should allow drivers to expose "internals" and in which way - I would like that to see discussed on the ML, as I suspect more people want to have a say in that.

Finally, one more note - we're doing all of this because a single mech driver wants to expose an extension. If we realize this framework still needs improvement perhaps we can work at a solution for allowing that specific driver to expose an extension - and defer this framework to the next release.'}, {'account_id': 10393, 'date': '2014-08-20 15:38:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16:

Hi Salvatore,

Thanks for reviewing this. Here is my reply:


> Assuming it is ok to do that, only extensions declared in neutron/extensions should be supported. 
> I see for instance the 
> DFA mech driver is adding an attribute to the response - but that attribute for what I gather 
> belong to a new extension not defined in neutron/extension. 
> I think this is probably either an oversight on my side or something missing in the
> DFA implementation, but I reckon it's important.

Do you mean the file that defines the extended attribute should be in neutron/extensions tree? For the DFA, the extension file that defines the extended attribute is dfa_config_profile.py (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/103281/)  since it is DFA specific I didn't put it in the neutron/extensions. My understanding of extension API framework is that we need to provide the alias name and path to the extension and with those information the extension API will load the extension.

Also in DFA the extended attribute is used when creating the network. Basically the network attributes in addition to the common attributes, it contains DFA extended one.

> Second, I really would like to avoid deployers from specifying extensions managers. 

Do you mean to avoid defining 'extension_drivers' in the config file? Deployers already defining mech driver, services, what would be an issue defining extension_drivers in the config file.

> I understand your concerns around stuff that you need 
> to add in Kilo and can't do know for having a proper way of doing extensions. 
> However, I'd say that for the time being perhaps in the conf 
> file you can just specify the extension aliases you expect ML2 to support, 
> and fail at startup if no mech driver support them.

Your proposal, adding the aliases that needs to be supported in the config file, wouldn't be the same as extension_drivers that trying to avoid by deployers?

> You might keep the "extension drivers", which as said in a previous review will then become processors.
> the advantage is that deployers won't have to declare drivers, but merely expected extensions.

Do you mean calling process_x methods (for resources) in the Ml2Plugin (the same way it is done for _process_l3_x) ? If so, those methods has to be implemented by the mechanism driver (as extensions driver shouldn't be loaded, based on your proposal) and Ml2Plugin need to call those methods for all configured mechanism driver. 

> These are my concerns at the moment, with the pending items regarding whether we should allow drivers to 
> expose  "internals" and in which way 

By driver expose 'internals' do you mean the extended attributes defined by extensions? if so, how it is specific to the extension drivers?

> Finally, one more note - we're doing all of this because a single mech driver wants to expose an extension. 
> If we realize this framework still needs improvement perhaps we can work at a solution for allowing that 
> specific driver to expose an extension - and defer this framework to the next release.

I agree that for now only DFA is going to use this feature, but there could be other feature that can benefit of this work (such as port security feature in ml2: https://review.openstack.org/19279 and also recent opestack-dev thread on developing QoS in neutron-incubator, which would also potentially involve an extension driver). Can we take incremental approach and instead of deferring this to the next release improve it in the next release?

Thanks,
Nader.'}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2014-08-21 07:22:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16: Code-Review-1

I've found your extension module. Putting it in a drivers package doesn't help. anyway this does not matter.

I still reckon that while it might be useful to have modules for processing the various extension (the extensiondrivers) I find bad that deployers have to specify their extensions. I do not think that this represents a well established pattern which the users of ML2 love, but a complication deployers can do without.
Also, I still do not subscribe to the point that it's the extension manager and not the mechanism driver that needs to declare supported extensions. But even if we assume that was the right way to go, using stevedore to specify drivers names is an unnecessary extra aliasing, as the deployer would like (and should) use the extension alias instead.

I've read the paper on the extension manager master plan that has been prepared by Bob. Needless to say, I found it a lot more complicated that I wanted it to be. But I usually put this down to my lack of skills in learning and understanding.  My understanding is that it is known that there are gaps to be addressed and that they have been identified and will be solved in the future.

Frankly, I think we would be a lot better off for this release if we just made a provision for DFA to allow it to expose this "vital" extra attribute. And take some more time to discuss the ML2 extension framework.

However, I am not able to cope with the frequency of review the patch's author is (rightfully) expecting, so I am removing the hold on the -2, unless until the time of my next review round.'}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2014-08-21 07:22:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16:

commit_message:
Support for extensions in ML2

The current ML2 plugin supports only extensions defined in the plugin and it
does not support any extensions in the mechanism drivers. The changes in this
commit allows mechanism drivers to define new extensions.

Change-Id: I28da19fabf6de2e9f0d687f875aaaa24c8bbc4f0
Implements: blueprint extensions-in-ml2
