Let's get a few eyes on this early to see if we're going in the right direction!"}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2014-08-12 15:46:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

My first reaction when looking at this was "decorators, brilliant!" but then I thought about it a bit more and now I'm not sure, more on that a few lines down. I haven't had a super close look at the details of the code, but conceptually what's here seems in alignment with what I the spec predicted.

Three thoughts/concerns:

* On the decorator: Does using a decorator present issues for people who want to write their own Discovery plugins? If they fail to decorate their discovery method their expectations may be a bit upset. Would it be safer in some sense for the DiscoveryBase to have an attribute which is the global PartitionCoordinator object that all subclasses will inherit?

* On the spec there was some discussion about people wanting to have multiple central agents but not having them all polling the same set of resources. As things currently stand all the agents needs to share the same configuration, and thus the same set of resource candidates. Could this be resolved by allowing an optional prefix during hash generation? Each unique configuration would need its own unique prefix. In fact I suppose one could use a hash of the configuration, normalized in someway, as the prefix.

* I was surprised by the apparent need to write code to ensure heartbeats get sent. I was rather assuming that tooz would provide library support (mixin class X, magically get heartbeats!). Is that not the case, or is that still to come?

Anyway: very encouraging work, looking forward to seeing it happen.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-12 16:32:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

I'm not sure you want selection to be done like that :-/"}, {'account_id': 8052, 'date': '2014-08-15 06:27:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Hey Joshua!

Thanks a lot for reviewing this and providing useful comments and suggestions. Before I reply at length at your comment about consistent hashing (which has already been on the table for this), let me just reply to your code snippet:

Since we're using uniform hashing, the larger the sample, the more even the distribution. I don't think it matters how only 3 resources are partitioned, instead we're looking at hundreds or thousands. Adapted snippet, showing the number of assigned resources instead (and a bigger sample):

http://paste.openstack.org/show/95385/"}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2014-08-15 06:46:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Is it ok for agents to process the same resource? Even with a larger iterable group sizes still affect who gets what.'}, {'account_id': 8052, 'date': '2014-08-15 06:51:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I don't see multiple agents getting the same resource in your code snippet. If you're referring to your inline comments, I haven't replied to those yet :-)"}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2014-08-15 08:29:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Hi Joshua,

Thanks for taking the time to apply your domain expertise in critiquing this approach.

Let me just give a little of the background as to why after considering the consistent hashing approach, we decided it wasn't actually necessary for this particular problem-space.

IIUC the key goal of a consistent-hash function is to minimize of number of keys that need to be re-mapped when a change in the number of buckets occurs (i.e. on an agent arrival or departure event in our case).

This desire for stickiness would often be motivated by some form of statefulness or initialization cost - i.e. where you want to minimize the amount of disruption on a rebalance because it would be expensive for keys to be needlessly re-assigned to new owners.

However in our case, that concern didn't really exist. There's nothing much to be gained from ensuring that a particular central agent continues to poll a particular LBaaS VIP or SNMP daemon or whatever before and after a reblance.

Hence a standard hash function seems sufficient, as an essentially random rebalance seems just as useful in our special case, as a rebalance that strives to minimize the number of re-assigned keys.

On the question of whether it's OK for two agents to poll the same resource, our feeling was that limited over-sampling was acceptable, as long as these cases only occurred for at most a single polling cycle of churn around an agent arrival or departure event.

Cheers,
Eoghan"}, {'account_id': 8052, 'date': '2014-08-15 13:58:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)

@Joshua: so, as Eoghan said, we did consider using hash rings, but they didn't seem necessary.

In order to not just wave hands, I went in and prepared a script that simulates polling agents, partitioning, etc. to compare both basic hashing and consistent hashing in a bunch of different scenarios. The script/data also serve as a nice PoC that this approach works in different scenarios.

data: https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1bwilTaMUJ76_bWYC6xiyyZZ-obq7Isd50fV9YSF4vKI/edit?usp=sharing
script: https://gist.github.com/nsaje/0ba636e6fe98c2be2039

It turns out both approaches perform similarly most of the time. The exception is a pathological case when in each polling cycle an agent joins the group (normally, all the agents would join within one or two polling cycles). In that case hash ring has indeed the smallest percentage of resources that get bounced around to the new agents.

I'll probably switch basic hashing out for hash_ring (it's a pretty minor change) to narrow the impact of this edge case.

Thanks again for the review!"}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2014-08-15 15:17:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: -Code-Review

Great, thanks for the explanations guys and the nice little simulation, very glad that was done to ensure everyone is ok with the effects of this.

As for using a hash_ring, I think it makes sense, it will cause less duplication of work & overlap when new agents join the group and will cause less disruption to existing agents selection of work when that happens as well.

As for https://pypi.python.org/pypi/hash_ring u might have to contact the author on that one, looking at the pypi page it seems like its only for python 2.7, maybe there is a better library on pypi that is more supported (not sure).

The one thing I didn't see when looking at the google doc was the percentage of overlap that happens when a new agent joins and the hash is 'destabilized', that'd be a useful thing to see I think also (and would likely show that regular hashing causes much more duplication of work than consistent hashing), unless I misunderstood the columns or something (quite possible)."}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2014-08-15 15:30:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Joshua: another option would be to lift the Ironic hash-ring implementation[1], after genericizing it to remove the DB dependency, and perhaps promoting it up to Oslo. 

Cheers,

@cdent: WRT to marking each sample with an indication of originating agent.

First, IIUC, true provenance would require that the full chain-of-ownership could be reconstructed for the sample, so we'd need to also record the individual collector that persisted each sample. So let's assume that we're only talking here about associating the originating agent with the sample.

For most classes of bugs/issues that could impact on an agent, we'd expect an equivalent impact on all agents. However, I guess there would be a subset of issues, e.g. an agent being "left behind" after an upgrade, that could be localized. 

So in the classic ceilometer approach to metadata, one could imagine the agent identity being recorded in the sample itself. However this would become a lot more problematic, I think, after a shift to pure timeseries data. In which case, I don't think we'd necessarily want to pollute the limited number of dimensions that can be efficiently associated with a datapoint with additional information purely related to the implementation/architecture of ceilometer.

So how about turning the issue on its head, and putting the onus on the agent to record its allocated resources for each cycle? The obvious way to do that would be via logging. Then in order to determine which agent was responsible for polling a particular resource at a particular time, the problem would collapse down to a distributed search over the agent log files for that period (perhaps aided by whatever log retention scheme is in use, e.g. logstash).'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2014-08-21 09:00:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

@eglynn Nejc made much the same comment on the mailing list thread, and I've made a response there. I think "the problem would collapse down to a distributed search over the agent log files" is an optimistic representation of the multitude of ways that people will be managing their logs. Sure they should be doing something like logstash, but what if they haven't gotten around to it yet? In any case I think the general principle under discussion here is general enough that the mailing list, not this patchset is the better place for it.

Also, jeebus dood, get off the internet, you're on holiday.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-21 09:50:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Verified-1

For example:

Memcache as a tooz backend won't work at scale when memcache servers start flip-flopping (it's a cache after all), which is different than how zookeeper will work (it prefers strong consistency). What will the ceilometer team prefer and how will they inform deployers and operators about these tradeoffs?"}, {'account_id': 7052, 'date': '2014-08-21 20:00:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 12:

Just one small note about debug logging ...

The Tempest gates all run with debug enabled IIRC, and there have been some complaints from the QA team about the volume of log output emitted by ceilometer.

So we've tried to eliminate/reduce logging from the periodic code-paths that's of little diagnostic value (other than to provide a kind of "comfort" indication that something is happening, e.g. "published one sample ...")

If your logging output has good diagnostic value and is not unreasonably verbose, then that's fine. (Especially in the context of cdent's earlier concerns about sample provenance).

However if not, then might be good to consider dialing the logging down a notch.

Cheers,
Eoghan'}, {'account_id': 8052, 'date': '2014-09-01 08:15:35.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 22.'}, {'account_id': 8052, 'date': '2014-09-01 08:16:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 22:

After discussing the diagnostic value of the existing debug logging with Nejc on IRC, I'm OK with keeping the logging that remains.

[{'created': '2014-08-12 15:05:19.000000000', 'message': 'Central agent work-load partitioning

Provides a mechanism to allow the central agent to be horizontally
scaled out, such that each agent polls a disjoint subset of resources.

This is achieved through the use of `tooz` library for distributed
coordination.

If a service wants to use work-load partitioning, it must first
create a PartitionCoordinator object and set it up with the
`set_partition_coordinator` method of the `partitioning` module.
It must also call its `heartbeat` method periodically.

To distribute a set of resources over multiple agents, decorate
a function returning that set with the Partition decorator, for
example:

 @Partition
 def discovery():
     return [...]

The decorator uses the global `PartitionCoordinator` to figure out
which agents are in the same group and figures out which resources
belong to the current agent.

Change-Id: I7adef87b03129f4f8b38109bf547c7403cc6adad
Implements: blueprint central-agent-partitioning

commit_message:
Central agent work-load partitioning

Provides a mechanism to allow the central agent to be horizontally
scaled out, such that each agent polls a disjoint subset of resources.

This is achieved through the use of `tooz` library for distributed
coordination.

If a service wants to use work-load partitioning, it must first
create a PartitionCoordinator object and call its `heartbeat` method
periodically.

To distribute a set of resources over multiple agents, use the
`extract_my_subset` method of the PartitionCoordinator that filters an
iterable, returning only the resources assigned to us.

The `PartitionCoordinator` uses `tooz` to figure out which agents are
in the same group and figures out which resources belong to the
current agent.

DocImpact
Change-Id: I7adef87b03129f4f8b38109bf547c7403cc6adad

Hi Vladyslav, thanks for making the changes. It looks like you've touched almost all the files, which worries me, because it makes it difficult to review which means it makes it easy to miss something especially if it is rebased which means it may take a long time for this to be approved and it may take a lot of reviewers' time to review this.

First, I would suggest that you break this up into smaller patches. If there are a few changes that the rest of the files are dependent on, put those in the first patch. Then the other patches shouldn't need to depend on each other. Which makes it easier to review/approve.

Second, I took a quick look at a few of the files. I don't believe that your commit is descriptive of the changes (or maybe I don't understand the commit description). You're changing LOG lines to use the new _LW, etc stuff.

Third, we should decide how we want to import the _LW, etc, so that it is consistent in all the files. My suggestion is to put something in tox.ini, eg 'import_exceptions = ironic.common.i18n', so that we can do 'from ironic.common.i18n import _LW, _LWhatever'. 

[Feel free to ask other folks; these are my opinions only.]"}, {'account_id': 10343, 'date': '2014-08-20 17:54:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Remove gettextutils _ injection

Now that ironic supports oslo.i18n, using the install function to
inject _ into the builtin has been deprecated. New i18n common module
used instead. In one module _ was imported from gettextutils, now
also changed to i18n import.

Closes-bug: #1346406
Change-Id: I672a975d479991982c24031e834a26e2c2811890

commit_message:
Fix a recent ipv6 UT regression

This fixes UT failures on systems without the procfs entry
by adding appropriate mocking.  The problem introduced by
the following change:
    https://review.openstack.org/#/c/116826/
    commit 0c963f6140237d8d3f361c6aaa7d2a6b656504db

Also, add a test for the case which the change in question fixed.

Closes-Bug: #1363805
Related-Bug: #1361542
Change-Id: I72842c3446f3275e2288adc411540ab036025ed0

Improve some plugins help strings

For consistency add a "." everywhere, remove an extra space at end of a
string, add missing space between strings, fix descriptions and
capitalization.

commit_message:
VMware: add in DVS VXLAN support

The neutron network will be a VLAN port group or a VXLAN port group.
In the case of the latter the backend adds a VXLAX prefix to the
port group name.

The prefix is  'vxw-<dvs moref>-<virtual wiremoref>-sid-'

The patch supports both types of networks and enables VM's to have
network connectivity.

Change-Id: Icb93585eb486d4b6c8f141fd133971e2b0968f92

If we say that the problem is the plugins API it creates, that's still under control as we vote for going upstream. Also, I can't see why the plugins API is so much bad : we already send JSON blobs, here with ERT we update these blobs, no big changes from an architectural PoV

Wrt stability and all the tempatives we do for Objects, that kind of direction which allows to ease the change to Objects is sure good..."}, {'account_id': 5511, 'date': '2014-08-19 13:10:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> I can't see why the plugins API is so much bad

in short - because we do not have sufficient information to make claims in the resource tracker. This needs to be fixed in RT first

> Also, ERT dramatically reduces number of additions to DB fields and Objects. Wrt stability and all the tempatives we do for Objects, that kind of direction which allows to ease the change to Objects is sure good.

This is a red herring - we introduce arbitrary json blobs, there is nothing in the ERT that will help this transition whatsoever."}, {'account_id': 1501, 'date': '2014-08-19 16:52:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Sorry comming to this late, but was away on holiday until yesterday - and can't claim to have followed all of the arguments in the e-mail chain yet. 

However, reverting something which is usable for the use cases it was designed for, and implemented against the spec that went through a pretty thorough review and approval process (not to mention 2 design summits) seems a pretty drastic step to take at this stage.

commit_message:
Flavor update tool for Ironic

As a part of the process of upgrading from Nova baremetal
driver to Ironic it's necessary to upgrade baremetal flavors'
metadata to reffer to Ironic deploy kernel and ramdisk.
This tool allows to do that by specifying the database connection
details and a CSV file containing new flavor metadata in the
flavor_id,kernel_id,ramdisk_id format.

commit_message:
Migrate Nova BM data to Ironic

The convertor retrieves Nova BM data, converts
it for Ironic and saves to the Ironic database.

Change-Id: I5adba49455c17ee59fc9a668a4d91e2b4d39de7b

commit_message:
Check min_ram and min_disk when boot from volume

Currently when boot from volume and the volume is created
from a image, the original image's min_ram, min_disk attributes
are ignored, this is not good.

We should extract these properties from the volume and check
it when boot from volume.

Change-Id: I861a78b5c7efa71e4bf7206d388b8d0d8048c78e
Closes-Bug: #1360022

commit_message:
Remove chain for correct router during update_routers()

The existing code incorrectly used the stale value from a previous list
comprehension - and deleted the chains for the wrong router :(
(Found via pylint)

Also: change to using a set() rather than a list(), since it is used for
repeated membership tests.

Also: refactor test cases to remove test case duplication.

Closes-Bug: #1362466
Change-Id: I4df400d57bab5427362db47a715576faa6340173

commit_message:
Apply different configurations by separate launchers

Add 3 lauchers for 4, 8 and 16 GB RAM on host PC.

For Linux(Cygwin) and Darwin used different way of fetch total memory.

Change-Id: I70487bda3e7492f72b5d5051de2e697bcae03377
Closes-Bug: #1358345

commit_message:
Upgrade, increase timeout for containers stopping

Stop container call send 9 signal after
10 seconds, sometimes it can interrupt
non atomic operations, such as keystone
database migration.
Increase timeout to prevent such issues.

Change-Id: Ia6c09ea0b14fba61c141959a2d065b487d1970ef
Closes-bug: #1364087

Upgrades, install bootstrap images before docker engine

It's required to install bootstrap images
before cobbler container is started.

Closes-bug: #1364138

commit_message:
Change configuration for Trusted Compute Pools

The configuration for TCP (Trusted Compute Pools) in the "Cloud Admin
Guide" is not correct.

Closes-Bug: 1362897
Change-Id: I396a0ebd41cd5672bad8c597751e8db4e82fffdb

commit_message:
Rename glance.store into glance_store

glance.store relied on python namespaces. Since setuptools doesn't
handle python namespaces correctly for py27 - nor it will - we've
decided to rename the package into glance_store to avoid the problem and
any workaround altogether.

Mailing list discussion:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-August/044194.html

Change-Id: Iedfe8d4d450a8ab9edc2de62b666c1b7a0f3171e

commit_message:
Remove unused _validate_endpoint

The _validate_endpoint method in keystone.catalog.controllers was
unused and unnecessary since we've got JSON Schema-based
validation.

Change-Id: I16228c0b9a88b5a05567c7021320081b8081b68b

commit_message:
Display Network panels based on neutron ext-list

Neutron features like LBaaS, FWaaS or VPNaaS are provided as
extensions in Neutron. This commit changes these features are enabled
only when they are included in the extension list from Neutron.

It also change the default settings of enable_lb/firewall/vpn to True.
The default of these settings were set to False to avoid confusion to
users because LB/FW/VPNaaS are optional features in Neutron. By this
commit corresponding features in Horizon are enabled dynamically, so
it is reasonable to change the default to True.

This commit introduces Horizon version of override_settings
"update_settings" decorator which allows override an item in dict.
Django original override_settings replaces a dict completely,
however OpenStack dashboard setting has many dictionary configuration
and there are test case where we want to override only one item
in a dictionary and keep other items in the dictionary.
This version of override_settings allows this.

DocImpact

Implements blueprint neutron-feature-control-with-ext-list

Change-Id: I19424d448c800524de0ee8ac769974272dbb84a0

commit_message:
Use the stable symlink for downloading openSUSE image

The previous workaround for guessing which openSUSE guest
image to download is no longer necessary, since the fix
needed in the Open Build Service has been deployed. Unfortunately
as part of that the sha256sum file has been removed, so it
cannot be cached anymore.

Change-Id: I8733f9b829406d24a2f5678aa69d518cfcb30e3b

commit_message:
openSUSE: Fix code to unpack the qcow2 image

This code relied on assumptions that were never true
on openSUSE (or SUSE for that matter). We don't have
udev rules that automatically rescan partition tables..

Change-Id: Ibcbeea52df97bad1856f012c95c2bd36ed2b76cd

commit_message:
Remove SELECT FOR UPDATE use in update_firewall

SELECT FOR UPDATE expression, which is triggered with the use of the
SQLAlchemy Query object's with_lockmode('update') method, is
detrimental to performance and scalability of the database
performance code in Neutron due to the lock contention it produces.

SELECT FOR UPDATE can be entirely avoided in update_firewall method
with the use of single-shot UPDATE expressions.

Change-Id: I333f726498192295116ca96ff5ca9012c36a6fd1

commit_message:
Transform a Keystone token to a SAML assertion

Add a class to generate a SAML assertion, based on Keystone
attributes.

Co-Authored-By: Marek Denis <marek.denis@cern.ch>

Implements bp keystone-to-keystone-federation
Change-Id: Iff82b4310d10b70fa6447ec52a504ef1f876cac4

commit_message:
Config Ref: Improve Compute scheduler description

Improve the compute scheduler section:
* Add missing filters
* Improve wording for some filters
* Fix default values
* use spaces around "=" in programlistings
* Fix markup

Change-Id: I69c38ba5cba1c04c4a51c519de561083bb59619f
Closes-Bug: #1304089
Closes-Bug: #1361860
Closes-Bug: #1361591
Closes-Bug: #1362425
